<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FAA-McArtor     09-27 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FAA-McArtor,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Chief Says Air Safety Improving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aviation safety is improving, and
technology and training programs are now in place to prevent most
major air disasters, the director of the Federal Aviation
Administration said Monday.
   ``I reject any notion from anybody that would assert that
aviation safety is somehow declining,'' Allan McArtor said during a
visit to the Mike Monroney Aeronautical Center in Oklahoma City.
   Near-collision reports are down 67 percent from last year; pilot
errors are down 63 percent and controller errors are down 18
percent, McArtor said.
   Also down are aviation-related fatalities and delays, he said.
   ``Aviation safety is improving. That does not mean aviation
safety cannot continue to improve. We have a lot of work to do. But
we should never be caught in the trap of assuming that accident
rates reflect aviation safety,'' he said, explaining that as air
travel increases, the number of accidents also would increase.
   Technological advancements in such things as radar, combined
with improved pilot training programs have reduced the danger of
wind shear to air travelers, McArtor said.
   ``Wind shear has been with us since the dawn of aviation. But
just now, we have the technology and the training that can
recognize these microburst conditions,'' he said.
   He referred to sudden shifts in wind direction and speed caused
when a mass of cooled air rushes downward out of a thunderstorm, a
condition that can especially endanger planes taking off and
landing.
   Just last week, the FAA announced that airplanes themselves will
now be required to carry equipment that can detect wind shear, and
to display steering commands so pilots can escape the conditions,
McArtor said.
   In addition, he said all airlines are now training pilots in
simulators to recognize conditions of wind shear and to escape from
them safely.
   He said the 1985 crash of a Delta Airlines flight in Dallas that
killed 137 people probably could have been prevented if such
measures had been in place at the time.
</TEXT>
