<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 0254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-MoneyTalks Bjt   09-27 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Money Talks, Bjt,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Political Millions Dash Proxmire's Illusions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An illusion has been dashed for William
Proxmire, who won his last Senate election in Wisconsin by shaking
scores of thousands of hands and spending $145.
   Proxmire, a member of the Senate since 1957, won that election
in 1982 with 64 percent of the vote and without spending a dime on
television commercials.
   But in the scramble to succeed him _ a scuffle that began when
he announced earlier this year that he would not seek re-election _
a new reality of the American political process emerged.
   Proxmire has found that money does in fact talk.
   The senator predicted the result earlier this year even before
Wisconsin's voters picked free-spending millionaire businessman
Herb Kohl, who never has held public office, as the Democratic
senatorial nominee over a list of veteran politicians.
   Proxmire described to the Senate the way he had established a
victorious and enduring political career by shaking hands and
ringing doorbells. He also correctly described what can happen when
all that hard work comes up against big money.
   ``Meet just as many voters as you can _ day after day, month
after month, year after year,'' Proxmire said in a Senate speech.
   ``The numbers are critical,'' he said. ``They add up. You can
literally meet hundreds every day. By campaigning on main streets
and shopping malls for seven or eight hours a day you can hit a
couple of thousand.
   ``Go out to baseball and football games, state fairs, busy
summer festivals ... and you can meet as many as a thousand an hour
_ literally.
   ``Keep that up year after year and you build remarkable
long-term support,'' he said. ``When you run statewide a few times
... an astonishing number remember you. Many of the
hundred-thousand people you met in your 1952 campaign for governor
still remember meeting you when they vote in 1982.
   ``With every election that passes you have more of those
beautiful voters in the bank.''
   It was a ``magic'' that never failed him.
   But it was not a road that Kohl, a relatively unknown face,
chose to follow.
   According to Proxmire, Kohl got his name recognition with money,
not by meeting voters one after the other.
   ``All that magic can blow away like a puff of smoke in a
hurricane when your opponent turns up with $2 million or $3 million
to buy television time and the good judgment of the experts to tell
him precisely how to build on it,'' he said.
   Kohl's Republican opponent, Susan Engeleiter, minority leader of
the Wisconsin state Senate, also is mounting an extensive and
expensive television campaign but is expected to be outspent by
Kohl, who had pumped $4 million into his campaign by the end of
August.
   Proxmire said that as a result of Kohl's heavy spending in the
Democratic primary campaign, ``the three Democratic candidates,
qualified by years of service in public office and with long
campaigning, were left far behind in the dust.''
   Proxmire's conclusion: ``Building constituent support one on
one, serving well in public office, can help build a political
career, but there is no substitute for money, and lots of it,
wisely spent in buying the most seasoned and shrewd media advice
and the television time to ring that bell.
   ``The candidate who has come from nowhere has been a smashing
success in business,'' Proxmire said. ``He may, if elected, serve
the country and our state as an excellent senator.''
   ``But as a retiring senator who followed the other painstaking
route of years of one-to-one hard campaigning work,'' Proxmire
said, ``I am disillusioned _ and more than a little jealous.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
