<DOCNO> AP880927-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 0043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NukeFleetProtest     09-27 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuke Fleet Protest,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Battleship Nearly Sinks Yacht Carrying Anti-Nuke Protesters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER O'LOUGHLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS New Jersey nearly ran down a
yacht carrying anti-nuclear demonstrators as the battleship
maneuvered into Sydney harbor today through a flotilla of yachts,
canoes and surfboards.
   The New Jersey's skipper, Capt. Douglas Katz, said his
57,000-ton battlewagon would probably have sunk the yacht had it
had not been dragged clear at the last moment.
   ``If it had not been for that police boat pulling it off we'd
have split it in half,'' Katz said. ``The guy on that police boat
was very brave.''
   The police boat managed to secure the yacht and tow it clear
seconds before the battleship steamed by.
   Other protesters in assorted small craft attempted to get
alongside the ship and plaster it with anti-nuclear slogans, but
were kept away by a cordon of police and Australian navy speed
boats.
   Police and navy divers jumped into the water to arrest two
protesters.
   Katz, 46, of Bluefield, W. Va., said demonstrators, some of them
from the international environmental group Greenpeace, risked their
lives coming so close to the New Jersey because turbulence from the
ship's four 18-foot propellors could have sucked them under water.
   The New Jersey is visiting Australia with an international fleet
of more than 40 warships to celebrate the bicentennial of European
settlement of Australia.
   Anti-nuclear demonstrators were protesting the New Jersey's
presence because it carries Tomahawk cruise missiles. The U.S. Navy
refuses to confirm or deny whether the missiles carry nuclear
warheads.
   The New Jersey, built in 1943, is powered by old-fashioned
oil-fired steam engines. It was followed into Sydney Harbor by the
British aircraft carrier Ark Royal and four warships of the Royal
Dutch Navy.
   Sailors from 16 nations will march through Sydney's streets on
Thursday.
   On Saturday, Prince Andrew of Britain and his wife the former
Sarah Ferguson will review the fleet from the deck of an Australian
warship, HMAS Cook.
</TEXT>
