<DOCNO> AP880927-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 0306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-Marshall     09-27 0877</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Marshall,0901</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alabama Center Recovers From Challenger, But Warns Space Is Still
Dangerous</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No matter the care taken and the tests
conducted, eventually there will be another space accident and the
Marshall Space Flight Center probably will once again be the target
of the nation's anger and anguish.
   That, says J. R. Thompson, director of Marshall, is a truth
engineers learn to live with at the NASA center that designs and
develops the most dangerous parts of a space machine.
   ``Ours are the two high-risk elements _ the shuttle main engine
and the shuttle solid rocket,'' Thompson said in an interview at
the facility in the forested hills of northern Alabama. ``In 9
chances out of 10, when there is a catastrophic failure, it will
rest with those two elements.''
   ``When a mission goes good, the focus is going to be on the
operations end,'' he said. ``When things go amiss, the attention is
going to be right here ... It's not an unfair thing. We're big boys
and we know that's the job we've got.''
   A presidential commission concluded that the explosion that
destroyed Challenger and killed its seven crew members on Jan. 28,
1986, was caused by a flawed solid rocket booster that blowtorched
against the external tank.
   Marshall engineers became personal targets of blame. Their
judgment was ridiculed, their diligence belittled and their
competence questioned.
   Larry Mulloy, who headed the solid rocket booster program at
Marshall, received hate mail and endured the collapse of a 23-year
career at NASA. William Lucas, director at Marshall, resigned, with
parting, bitter shots at the press. Ten other managers also left,
retiring or seeking jobs in private industry.
   None of the more than 3,400 workers at Marshall escaped the
stain.
   ``It was devastating,'' said Bob Erwin, an engineer who analyzes
stresses on the spacecraft. ``Everybody was pretty low. There was
not so much a sense of guilt as of loss. There was also the sense
of professional embarrassment. Something had gone terribly wrong
and Marshall was responsible.''
   The drumbeat of blame, recalled Jerry Patterson, an organic
chemist and materials expert, seemed to last forever.
   ``All the nails were driven in place and we were just hanging
there and they were still beating on us,'' he said. ``Eventually it
got to be too much ... We had accepted the responsibility. What we
had to do then was make it right.''
   That involved the most massive effort at reevaluation, repair
and redesign ever attempted by NASA.
   Teams of engineers at Marshall dissected every piece of hardware
developed at the Alabama center. Every design was reexamined. Every
test was checked over and new ones were ordered where needed.
   Work days stretched from 10 to 12 to 14 hours, and, for many,
weekends were forgotten.
   Thompson said more tests were made on the main engines and on
the solid rocket boosters than were conducted before the shuttle
first flew in 1981. The goal was not to find out if the equipment
was just ``good enough,'' but to demonstrate that it was better
than it had to be.
   The full-scale solid rocket engine, with a new design for the
flawed joint, was fired five times at a test site in Utah by its
manufacturer, Morton Thiokol Inc. There were hundreds of other
firings using sub-scale models or partial propellant loads.
   In one full-scale test, flaws were intentionally introduced to
see if the new rocket had a margin of safety. It was a test never
before attempted in the solid rocket industry.
   ``A lot of people inside and outside the agency didn't like that
test because they thought it was pushing the engine too far,'' said
Thompson. If it had failed, it could have caused a long delay in
shuttle flights. But Thompson and the Marshall engineers insisted
because, he said, they ``believed in our design and wanted to go
out on the test stand and prove it.''
   The new rocket engine passed the test with margin to spare.
   Before Challenger, engineers recalled, dissent against consensus
technical views was discouraged. Public differences of opinion were
rare and quickly silenced.
   ``You were part of a team and it seemed a betrayal to take a
contrary view,'' said one engineer.
   Challenger changed that.
   ``The accident strengthened the hand of the engineers in the
trenches,'' said Erwin. ``Before, if you objected to something the
manager could say you were overcautious because we had never had an
accident. Now if a manager wants to yield to schedule pressures, we
tell him that he's on his own.''
   The new openness has resulted in conflicts unknown before
Challenger. In one case, some experts believed a material in a
solid rocket part needed one more test and refused to approve its
use despite pressure from a manager. At conferences, it has become
common for engineers to stand up and object to positions taken by
their own managers.
   ``You admire a guy who has the courage to take a position
different from the crowd,'' Thompson said. ``But that doesn't mean
it's a democracy. You're not going to launch with a democracy.
You've got to have certain people in the system who make decisions
and go.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
