<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 0210EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WelfareOverhaul Bjt   09-27 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Welfare Overhaul, Bjt,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Welfare Agreement Means System Is Headed For Major Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's welfare system is headed for a
major overhaul with the conclusion of complex negotiations on a
five-year plan aimed at moving welfare recipients into jobs and
helping them collect more child support.
   The initiative agreed on Monday by Senate, House and White House
negotiators had been close to death all summer as negotiators
sought a balance between conservatives favoring mandatory work and
liberals concerned about increasing benefits to the needy and
motivating people to enter the mainstream workplace.
   ``This was a critical day,'' said Rep. Tom Downey, D-N.Y.,
chairman of the subcommittee that handled the House welfare bill,
emerging from Monday's pivotal meeting.
   ``There are some who will not be happy'' with the outcome,
Downey said. But when asked if the package would fly when presented
to about 50 House and Senate conferees late this afternoon, he
said, ``Yes.''
   ``I am very pleased,'' said Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas,
chairman of the House and Senate conferees and the Democratic vice
presidential nominee. ``I think it's a good final resolution of the
differences ... an excellent compromise.''
   Reagan's domestic policy adviser, Charles Hobbs, a participant
in Monday's meeting, offered a conditional endorsement of the
compromise. ``If it's okay with the conferees and if it comes down
the way I understand it, it's probably okay,'' he said.
   The $3.34 billion welfare plan comes in above the Senate's own
$2.8 billion measure but would cost less than half of the initial
$7.1 billion plan passed by the House.
   The cornerstone of the compromise is a Job Opportunities and
Basic Skills (JOBS) program offering welfare parents _ including
those with preschool children _ services such as job search help,
education and job training. Child care and transportation aid would
be available to participants.
   States would have to be serving 7 percent of eligible welfare
recipients by 1990 and 20 percent by 1995. States would be given
$600 million for the JOBS program in 1989, rising to $1.3 billion
in 1995. People moving into jobs would qualify for a year of
transitional child care and Medicaid benefits.
   Twenty-seven states now provide welfare benefits to households
with two unemployed parents. The welfare bill would require those
states to continue and, effective in 1991, would require others to
provide at least six months of benefits a year to such families.
   Starting in 1994, one adult in each two-parent welfare family
would have to perform 16 hours a week of community work, on-the-job
training or other specified work activities. People under 25
without high school diplomas would be able to substitute
participation in an education program leading to a diploma or its
equivalent.
   The bill also makes new demands on states to step up child
support collections from non-custodial parents, including tougher
paternity determination requirements and mandatory wage withholding
upon the court award of support payments.
   The 16-hour-a-week work requirement would affect only about 7
percent of the welfare caseload but was a primary obstacle to
achieving agreement on the overall bill. A handful of House
liberals resisted the provision almost as fiercely as the Reagan
administration insisted it be retained.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880927-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 0329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-MortonThiokol     09-27 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Morton Thiokol,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discovery Launch Marks Milestone On Morton Thiokol's Long Road
Back</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morton Thiokol, maker of the rocket
booster that caused Challenger's destruction, hopes a successful
launch for Discovery will begin an awakening from a 32-month-long
corporate nightmare.
   It will be the ``final demonstration to our customer NASA and
the country that solid rocket motors are going to be a reliable
contributor to future shuttle successes,'' said Dick Davis, vice
president and assistant general manager of space operations at
Morton Thiokol's Wasatch Operations in Utah.
   Less easily dispatched are the specters of an FBI investigation,
lawsuits by frustrated former employees and a plague of rocket
fuel-related accidents, including an MX missile motor fire that
killed five employees last December.
   The presidential commission that investigated the Jan. 28, 1986,
shuttle disaster found that an O-ring seal on the right booster
rocket had stiffened in freezing pre-launch temperatures, allowing
superheated gas to escape and trigger an explosion.
   Worse, the commission learned that several Morton Thiokol
engineers had argued the night before that just such a disaster
could occur, but were overruled by superiors who told NASA the
launch should proceed.
   In the relentless glare of the postmortem, Morton Thiokol
embarked on an exhaustive booster redesign that kept some 3,000
workers busy on the field joints as well as the case-to-nozzle
motor joint, the nozzle assembly and hundreds of smaller components.
   ``It's been a very difficult period,'' said Davis. ``I don't
think any company is ever prepared for the kind of intense scrutiny
that you get following a tragedy like Challenger.''
   Allan J. McDonald, a Morton Thiokol engineer who had argued
against the Challenger launch, was made vice president of
engineering for space operations _ overseer of the booster redesign.
   His guiding principle in the $500 million effort has been
redundancy: multiple seals, bolts and clamps to contain the 1.1
million pounds of solid fuel that burn in just two minutes.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has borne the
redesign cost and Morton Thiokol agreed to reap no profit.
   Engineers have conducted five $20 million full-scale
test-firings of the redesigned boosters, as well as hundreds of
sub-scale and component tests. A sixth full-scale test is planned
for December.
   With 8,000 employees and an annual payroll of $220 million,
Morton Thiokol Inc. is Utah's largest private employer. The
Chicago-based company also produces munitions, salt and specialty
chemicals, and manufactures first-stage motors for the MX, Trident
2 and Midgetman strategic missiles and propulsion systems for
tactical missiles.
   Tom Russell, a company vice president, said aerospace profits _
which account for more than a quarter of the company's overall
profits _ fell from $96 million in fiscal 1986 to $73 million in
1987, then rose to $80.8 million in 1988.
   Even as Morton Thiokol struggled to recover from Challenger,
accidents further begrimed its public image. On Dec. 29, 1987, five
men were killed when 108,000 pounds of fuel in an MX missile
segment exploded, destroying a $6.2 million building at the complex
75 miles northwest of Salt Lake City. The state cited Morton
Thiokol for six safety violations.
   Just last week, the company acknowledged that an old model of a
nozzle inlet ring had been used in a motor test-fired in August.
Analysis proved new versions had been placed in Discovery's
boosters.
   Morton Thiokol also has been sued by former employees, among
them Roger Boisjoly, another engineer who protested the Challenger
launch and later resigned. His lawsuits, seeking $3 billion, were
recently dismissed.
   In mid-September, two former consultants, Stephen Agee and
Anthony Laine, filed suit contending they were fired for attempting
to bring redesign problems to light. Their suits also claim the
company violated racketeering laws by filing false reports on its
contractual obligations with NASA.
   Agee said on CBS' ``West 57th'' Saturday that the entire booster
system was unsafe and that he ``wouldn't even want to be around
when they assemble the boosters and stack them prior to launch.''
   Discovery's boosters, of course, have long been in place,
assembly on a second set is nearly complete and a third set is
being shipped to the Cape. And Lisa Malone, spokeswoman for the
Kennedy Space Center, expressed confidence in the redesign and
testing the boosters have undergone.
   Morton Thiokol also is the subject of an FBI inquiry into
allegations by Agee, a contract engineer who worked undercover for
the agency during his 4{-month tenure as a safety analyst. Agee
alleged that, among other things, the company had concealed hazards
from NASA.
</TEXT>
