<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Klan-IndependenceHall     09-27 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Klan-Independence Hall,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Klan Likely To Apply To Rally At Independence Hall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ku Klux Klan and the National Park
Service have been negotiating plans for a ``white pride day'' rally
at Independence Hall in November, a park official says.
   The park service expects to approve an application for a permit
to hold the rally at the hall, where the Declaration of
Independence and the U.S. Constitution were signed, Chief Ranger
Bob Burn said Monday.
   The application has not been filed yet, but will be soon, said
Richard Fogel, a Klan official who lives in Red Lion, Pa.
   For the past two weeks, the KKK and the park service have been
discussing police protection, parking and other concerns associated
with the rally scheduled for Nov. 5 at the hall, Burn said.
   Burn said the application probably would be approved because
``under the First Amendment and the regulations we operate under,
there's not much room for denying (it).''
   Marie E. Jones, an executive board member of the Philadlephia
branch of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People, agreed the Constitution gives the KKK the right to rally.
   But, she said, ``It is sad to see that people who have accepted
violence as a way of life toward people who are not their race or
creed can imbue others with their hatred.
   ``I do hope there will be some black faces there,'' she said.
   The Klan might invite other right-wing groups, such as the
National Democratic Front and the Natiional States' Rights Party,
Fogel said.
   In May, about 40 people dressed in Klan robes marched in
Parkside, Pa., in suburban Philadelphia. They were greeted by a
crowd of about 1,000 counter-demonstrators.
</TEXT>
