<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TreasuryBills     09-27 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interest Up on Short-Term Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in the latest auction.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.0 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.23 percent on Monday, up from 7.17
percent last week. Another $7.0 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.48 percent, up from 7.34 percent
last week.
   The rates were the highest since three-month bills sold for 7.26
percent on Sept. 6 and six-month bills averaged 7.50 percent on
Aug. 29.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.47 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,817.20 and 7.88 percent for six-month bills selling for
$9,621.80.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, rose to 8.07
percent last week after averaging 8.01 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
