<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Iran     09-27 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Iran,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China and Iran Sign Agreements on Consulates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China and Iran have signed an agreement on
setting up general consulates in their two countries to help boost
economic and trade relations.
   Iran will open a consulate in Shanghai under Monday's pact,
while China reserves the right to open a consulate in an as yet
undecided Iranian city, the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   China, which has maintained good relations with both Iran and
Iraq and was alleged to be a major arms supplier in the Persian
Gulf war, has welcomed the cease-fire in the war as an opportunity
to boost trade ties with both countries.
   Earlier this month, China sent a large delegation to an
international trade fair in Tehran that reportedly was promoting
sales of optical, chemical and light industrial products and
petroleum engineering technologies and equipment.
   China is also seeking to export labor for major construction
projects.
