<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     09-27 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Suds,' A New Musical, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Those great pop songs of the early 1960s will
survive ``Suds,'' a numbing regurgitation of many of the musical
hits of the era when the Beatles were changing the sound of popular
music.
   There are some terrific musical memories including ``Respect,''
``Dedicated to the One I Love,'' ``The Loco-Motion,'' ``Do Wah
Diddy Diddy,'' ``You Don`t Have to Say You Love Me,'' ``You Can't
Hurry Love'' and nearly 40 other Top 10 tunes crammed into the show.
   What sinks ``Suds'' is not the songs but the dippy story that
authors Melinda Gilb, Steve Gunderson and Bryan Scott have
inflicted on these golden oldies. It's dumb without being fun.
   They have set their musical in a Laundromat where Cindy, the
world's oldest looking teen-ager, is celebrating her birthday _
alone and depressed. Cindy's cat, Fluffy, has been run over by a
Corvair, her pen pal boyfriend has dropped her because he found
someone with better handwriting and she discovers she owes $10,000
to the Internal Revenue Service for some relative's back taxes.
   Cindy tries to end it all by wrapping pedal pushers around her
neck, throwing them into a Maytag and agitating herself to death.
She's stopped by two guardian angels, one named Dee Dee who looks
like Marlo Thomas on a bad day and the other, Marge, whose red
bouffant hairdo confirms she has cornered the market on hairspray.
   The duo counsel the girl, trying to cheer her up and persuade
her to get on with her life. It's these therapeutic sessions that
take the form of musical interludes, usually three or four hit
numbers stitched together. Occasionally, they take off, like a
funny version of ``Secret Agent Man,'' done with style by
Gunderson, who plays all the men and even one woman in the show.
   More often, you grow impatient with the dialogue, waiting for
the story to end and the music to begin again. The cast is
competent but not distinguished. The women _ Christine Sevec, Susan
Mosher and Gilb _ belt out the songs with gusto if not any
particular style.
   ``Suds,'' which opened last weekend, is the first attraction at
Stage Left, a cabaret theater in the Criterion Center. The Center
is an impressive theater complex located in Times Square and also
contains a more formal theater which will open later in the year.
The playing area has good sightlines and comfortable seating. Now
all it needs is a show.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880927-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 0324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-MoynihanCampaign Bjt   09-27 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Moynihan Campaign, Bjt,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Senate Race Produces Personal Attacks, Hard Feelings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Things have turned nasty in New York's U.S.
Senate race where Democratic incumbent Daniel Patrick Moynihan's
GOP opponent already has called his rival a liar, a coward and a
crummy boss.
   Moynihan, a two-term Senate veteran, is known to most of the
world as a professorial type who writes a lot of books, taught at
Harvard and served as U.S. ambassador to India and the United
Nations.
   But Republican Robert McMillan is hoping to expose another side
of Moynihan using an aggressive campaign with sharp personal
attacks, and, in the process, salvage an underfunded and
underpublicized effort to unseat Moynihan.
   It's a long shot gamble.
   Moynihan, McMillan claims, is an arrogant and overrated senator
who was ``chicken'' to debate him, condones ``safe sodomy'' for
homosexuals, lies to the press, is too abrasive to keep employees
on his staff and too lazy to do his official duties in Washington.
   ``What kind of a man is this Pat Moynihan?'' McMillan asked last
month. ``He's on the record as one who would lie, if he thought he
could get away with it.''
   Moynihan, 61, has tried to appear above the fray in the face of
McMillan's charges.
   When asked about being called a liar, Moynihan said only, ``I
heard that. That's OK. I've been called worse things than that.''
   McMillan, 56, a wealthy Long Island lawyer who worked for
President Nixon in the 1960s, also maintains that Moynihan hasn't
been the kind of ``shining beacon'' to the youth of New York that
McMillan recalls from his adolescent days in front of the radio. He
suggested Flash Gordon, the Lone Ranger, Captain Midnight or Jack
Armstrong as good role models.
   Many attribute the tone of McMillan's campaign to one of its
chief strategists, Robert Blasdell, who once worked with campaign
expert Roger Ailes. An influential voice in Republican nominee
George Bush's presidential effort, Ailes is known for his
bare-knuckles campaign style.
   McMillan's attacks haven't had a discernible effect among
voters, but they have prompted Moynihan campaign aide Lawrence
O'Donnell Jr. to suggest that New Yorkers might be owed an apology
``for the nonsense they've been subjected to by this candidacy.''
   ``This is what comes from desperation,'' O'Donnell said of
McMillan's tactics. ``There's a very cold, calculated decision
being made to go after Pat Moynihan the person. And that, you'll
find in a state where Moynihan has a 70 percent approval rating, is
the most egregious tactical mistake the opposition campaign could
ever have.''
   Moynihan won 65 percent of the vote en route to his defeat of
little-known Brooklyn state Assemblywoman Florence Sullivan in 1982
by more than 1.5 million votes. A poll conducted earlier this month
by the Marist College Institute for Public Opinion in Poughkeepsie,
N.Y., showed him with a 63-21 percent lead over McMillan among 601
likely voters.
   Financially, McMillan has little hope of matching Moynihan in
spending. The most recent contribution filing with the Federal
Election Commission showed McMillan's campaign $40,000 in debt
while Moynihan had $1.9 million in the bank.
   Since starting his campaign May 9, McMillan has been on the road
almost constantly, appearing at county fairs, political picnics and
local television and radio stations. He has logged about 27,000
miles by car.
   In that time, the GOP candidate has tried to prove that
Moynihan's intellectual bent hasn't paid dividends for New Yorkers
since the former Harvard professor won election to the Senate in
1976.
   McMillan says Moynihan has exercised ``benign neglect'' toward
New Yorkers as senator. Moynihan says ``I plead guilty'' about his
enthusiasm for writing and lecturing, but insists that one of his
senatorial duties is to articulate the issues.
   And, O'Donnell says Moynihan has been responsible for delivering
about $5 billion in federal aid to New York in his second term
alone.
   McMillan has also tried to make political hay by pointing out
that Moynihan has missed more than 400 roll call votes since
arriving in the Senate. But Moynihan says that when first elected,
he promised only to do better than the senatorial average as far as
attendance in the House was concerned. He said he's done that by
being present for about 92 percent of the votes.
   McMillan leveled the liar charge in connection with an incident
last year when a Buffalo (N.Y.) News reporter challenged Moynihan
on why he had been excluded from a Moynihan press briefing.
Moynihan denied that he'd ordered the reporter barred, but Moynihan
chief of staff Harrison Rainie said his boss had indeed given
orders to keep the reporter out.
   Rainie, a former New York Daily News reporter, resigned a few
days later.
   ``One day of staff confusion,'' said O'Donnell of the incident.
</TEXT>
