<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AgResearch     09-27 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ag Research,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$206 Million Farm Research Bill Gets House Approval</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agricultural research bill to provide $206
million for programs ranging from alternative crops to fish farming
is headed for the Senate after winning approval in the House.
   ``The land is the only thing that can produce new wealth for
this vast economic empire we call the United States of America and
it begins with research,'' Agriculture Chairman E. ``Kika'' de la
Garza, D-Texas, said Monday as the bill received House approval on
a voice vote.
   Research grants to develop new types of crop production would be
authorized by the bill. The measure also would establish a National
Institute for Alternative Agricultural Products within the
Agriculture Department.
   A non-profit Agricultural Research Commercialization Corp. also
would be created that would use loans, loan guarantees, interest
subsidies and other means to spur product commercialization.
   Under the measure, $20 million a year through fiscal year 2000
would be authorized for development of new agricultural products,
$15 million to commercialize products and up to $600,000 to enhance
marketing of existing ones.
   The bill's overall price tag was estimated by the Congressional
Budget Office at $206 million over five years.
   With perhaps three weeks to go before lawmakers adjourn,
however, the future of the measure is clouded. The Senate has
offered no guarantees that it will get to the measure.
   The bill would establish grants for research into statistical
methods of measuring chemicals and microorganisms in food products
and means of preventing contamination.
   Also under the measure, an office of groundwater policy
determination would be established within the Agriculture
Department. That provision was included at the urging of Republican
Rep. Fred Grandy of Iowa, where concern is growing over findings of
pesticide contamination in groundwater.
   The bill would provide $3 million in each of three years for
research into aquaculture, or fish farming.
   It also would reauthorize federal research aid for examination
and development of crops used in so-called critical materials. The
measure would set the program at an $8 million level for each of
the next two years.
   Most money under that program would go to research into guayule
_ a plant grown in the Southwest that produces a natural rubber
that can be used for high-performance aircraft tires.
   The bill would enable farmers to plant so-called alternative
crops in 1989 and 1990 without losing their base acreage listed
with the Department of Agriculture. The base acreage is used to
calculate the size of the federal payments they get for producing
wheat, feed grains, cotton and rice.
   Meanwhile, the House approved on a voice vote a separate measure
to establish a 25-member Commission on the Improvement of the
Federal Crop Insurance Program.
   Ten of the 21 voting members would come from the insurance
industry and 10 from among agricultural producers with the manager
of the corporation also serving on the panel. The four non-voting
members would come from Congress.
   The goal of the panel would be to recommend changes in the
program, which has lost more than $1 billion since 1980 when a
major overhaul was approved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
