<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Wages     09-27 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wages,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Number Of Low-Wage Jobs Is Rising</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Minimum Wage Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of working Americans with wages
below the poverty level for a family of four increased by more than
1 million last year, according to a new Senate report.
   The report, prepared by the Democratic staff of the Senate
Budget Committee from Census Bureau data, concluded that both
high-paying and low-paying jobs have grown at the expense of a
shrinking middle class over the past eight years.
   Fueling the debate over the quality of 16 million new jobs since
President Reagan took office, the report was immediately criticized
by Senate Republicans as ``misleading and inaccurate.''
   ``Sixty-four percent of American jobs paid middle level wages
(defined as those between $11,611 and $46,444 in 1987 dollars) in
1979,'' said the report, released Monday.
   ``Between the peak of the business cycle in 1979 and the latest
year of the current expansion in 1987, only 38 percent of the
increase in employment was in middle wage jobs,'' it added.
   As a result, according to the data, the share of middle-wage
earners declined from 64 percent to 61.3 percent between 1979 and
1987. Those earning a poverty wage climbed from 32.4 percent to
34.2 percent and those with high wages (more than $46,444) rose
from 3.7 percent to 4.5 percent of the working population.
   The committee's chairman, retiring Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla.,
said a comparison of the 1987 data from the Census Bureau's Current
Population Survey released earlier this month with 1986 data shows
a worsening of the trend.
   According to the data, 40.45 million workers were paid a
full-time equivalent of less than $11,611 last year, compared with
39.38 million in 1986. Meanwhile, the number of Americans with jobs
exceeding $46,444 fell from 5.4 million in 1986 to 5.32 million
last year.
   ``The sad truth,'' Chiles said, ``is that jobs paying below the
poverty level are growing faster than any other kind. And jobs that
provide a middle-class standard of living are a shrinking part of
our job landscape.''
   Sen. Pete V. Domenici of New Mexico, the committee's ranking
Republican and former chairman, called the report ``opportunistic,
political, misleading and inaccurate'' and predicted that it
eventually will be discredited.
   ``Most of the new jobs created during the expansion have been in
occupations that pay well _ in technical and managerial fields, the
kind of jobs we want for our kids,'' he said. ``Only 8 percent of
the jobs generated by this expansion pay under $7,000 annually.''
   The only group going against the trend was women, according to
the report. Middle-wage and high-wage jobs among them increased by
1.2 percentage points and 0.5 percentage points to 55.4 percent and
1.8 percent, respectively, over the past eight years.
   The share of women in the workforce with low-paying jobs,
meanwhile, fell from 44.6 percent in 1979 to 42.9 percent last year.
   Men fared the worst, with the middle-income share falling from
72.1 percent in 1979 to 66.6 percent last year. The share of
low-wage earners among men climbed from 22.3 percent to 26.5
percent over the same period while the proportion of high-wage
earners rose from 5.6 percent to 6.9 percent.
   Among blacks and other minorities, the share of low-income
workers and high-income earners increased by 1.2 percentage points
and 0.6 percentage points to 41.7 percent and 2.3 percent
respectively. The proportion of middle-income minority workers
declined from 57.8 percent to 56 percent over the eight years.
</TEXT>
