<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Dukakis-Ads     09-27 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Ads,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Ads To Feature Closing Statement, Health Care Pitch From Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis has already turned his closing
statement from the first presidential debate into a tag line for
two campaign commercials that begin airing tonight.
   ``The best America is not behind us, the best America is yet to
come,'' Dukakis says in both 30-second spots.
   One, called ``Opportunity,'' includes only the closing lines
from his Sunday night debate with George Bush at Wake Forest
University in Winston-Salem, N.C.
   The other, ``Our Concern,'' focuses on his pitch for universal
health insurance, but also mentions college opportunity and
includes the closing line.
   The length of the run has not been determined, Dukakis
spokeswoman Lorraine Voles said Monday.
   ``We have an opportunity, working together, to build that
future, to build a better America, to build a best America,''
Dukakis said at the close of the debate in a passage also
frequently found in his stump speeches.
   ``Because the best America doesn't hide; we compete,'' he
continued. ``The best America doesn't waste; we invest. The best
America doesn't leave some of its citizens behind; we bring
everyone along. And the best America is not behind us. The best
America is yet to come.''
   The health care pitch focuses on the Democratic nominee's
promise to seek legislation requiring most employers to provide
health insurance to their workers.
   ``I think it's time that when you got a job in this country that
it came with health insurance,'' Dukakis says in the debate footage.
   The passage from the closing statement was chosen for an ad
because it focuses on Dukakis' effort to win broad support among
middle class voters _ a segment Dukakis has characterized as
victims of the Reagan recovery.
   Dukakis aides had planned to use at least one segment from the
debate, and likely the closing statement, for a new ad and then
also decided to make a second ad with the health care material,
campaign aides said.
</TEXT>
