<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     09-27 0917</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,910</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Analysts Say Food Aid To Poor Nations May Fall Further</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Food aid to needy countries has dropped and
could fall further because of rising commodity prices, according to
Agriculture Department analysts.
   The Food and Agriculture Organization, a United Nations agency,
estimates that aid in the form of cereal grain shipments in the 12
months ended June 30 was about 10.5 million metric tons, down 14
percent from 12.2 million tons a year earlier.
   Ray Nightingale of the Agriculture Department's Economic
Research Service said the United States provided 65 percent of last
year's 10.5 million tons and ``was followed distantly'' by the
European Economic Community with 15 percent; Canada, 10 percent;
and Japan and Australia, each with about 3 percent.
   For the fourth consecutive year, he said, the 1974 World Food
Conference goal of 10 million tons of food aid was exceeded last
year.
   ``However, given no significant increases in the major donors'
1988-89 food-aid budgets, and higher commodity prices, the volume
of food aid may fall in 1988-89, and achievement of the
10-million-ton-goal is doubtful,'' Nightingale said.
   The U.S. aid program under Food for Peace, or P.L. 480 as it is
also known, was increased nearly 5 percent for the fiscal year
ending Sept. 30 to nearly $1.5 billion.
   Nightingale, writing in the October issue of Agricultural
Outlook magazine, said about two-thirds of the volume under Food
for Peace was wheat and wheat products, while feed grains and
vegetable oils made up about 5 percent each. Rice, dairy products,
pulses and other products made up the remainder.
   Africa accounted for nearly half the U.S. allocations in
1987-88; Asia, about a third, and Latin America, about a fifth.
   Nightingale said the dollar amount of the 1988-89 allocations
under Food for Peace has not been decided but that the Reagan
administration has requested about $1.4 billion, which effectively
would roll back the 5 percent increase of 1987-88.
   The 1988-89 money for Food for Peace is included in USDA
appropriation bills currently being negotiated by a House and
Senate conference committee.
   Nightingale said that with few exceptions crop prospects in
developing countries ``look good this season'' and that food
supplies are up relative to current consumption.
   ``However, greater assistance is needed this year to rebuild
stocks that were drawn down heavily last year,'' he said.
   Grains are the mainstay of food aid, with cereals making up 75
percent of the diet in Asia and 50 percent to 70 percent in Africa,
Nightingale said. Although these regions produce a large share of
the world's cereal crops, much that enters world trade is grown in
North America, where drought has reduced supplies this year.
   The USDA monitors 55 countries for signs of food shortfall.
Newly available information on the food-aid share of some
countries' food imports ``indicates greater dependence on aid than
previously thought,'' Nightingale said.
   Some countries have allocated less foreign exchange to food
imports than thought earlier, he said. And because prices are up,
the estimated amount of commercial imports will be only 6.5 million
tons, compared with 11.7 million in 1987-88.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says three food
stamp projects using plastic magnetic strip cards instead of paper
coupons will be conducted in parts of Arizona, New Mexico and
Minnesota.
   Assistant Secretary John W. Bode said Monday that nearly 30,000
food stamp households in the three states will use the cards to see
if the system will be easier for people to use and to help reduce
lost or stolen coupons.
   The projects are scheduled to begin within the next 8 to 12
months and run for at least three years, he said. An evaluation
will be made to see if the electronic system might be used
nationally.
   Bode said the $1.3 million project will operate by running the
plastic cards through a computer terminal at grocery checkout
counters. The cost of the food will be automatically deducted from
the family's total monthly food stamp allotment.
   In addition, he said, some of the food stamp recipients will be
able to use the same plastic cards for other public benefits, such
as Aid for Families With Dependent Children.
   Bode said Arizona will get $580,853 from USDA to design its
projects, which will be tested in Mesa, with services to 6,500
households.
   Minnesota will receive $385,309 to test kits system in Ramsey
County among 13,000 households, and New Mexico will get $379 for
its test in Albuquerque among 10,150 households.
   Nationally, nearly 19 million people are getting food stamp
benefits, based on family size and adjusted household incomes. The
program costs about $12.6 billion a year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some penjing trees from China are out of
federal quarantine and will be dedicated at the U.S. National
Arboretum on Sept. 30, says the Agriculture Department.
   Penjing trees are dwarf versions of forest species and are the
result of a 1,200-year-old art, says arboretum director H. Marc
Cathey. The specimens, a gift to the American people, are 20 to 100
years old and are only three feet high.
   Cathey said Monday that the penjing trees will be dedicated and
opened to public display on Sept. 30.
   The trees were donated by penjing experts Wu Yee-sun and Lui
Shu-ying on June 25, 1986, in Hong Kong. All specimens have been
held in quarantine at the department's Agricultural Research
Service plant introduction station in Glenn Dale, Md., to guard
against the introduction of pests and diseases.
</TEXT>
