<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Opera     09-27 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Opera,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Lady Attends Met Opera Opening</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Luciano Pavarotti's singing was ravishing and
his co-stars were in sterling voice for the Metropolitan Opera's
opening night performance of ``Il Trovatore'' Monday, but the
production lacked excitement, at times resembling a concert more
than an opera.
   The staging of the Fabrizio Melano production, which was new
last November, works against excitement. The set is a high
staircase extending across the stage. Most of the time, the singers
take turns standing alone on the stairs. The stage is kept dark,
with a changing backdrop of dark and white clouds.
   Of the three stars, Sherrill Milnes took vocal honors in the
first two acts, his voice strong and warm from the first note,
while Pavarotti and Eva Marton held back for the last two acts.
   Pavarotti, as Manrico, was tender with the Leonora, sung by Eva
Marton, and with Azucena, sung by Fiorenza Cossotto. When there was
reason for Manrico to be firm, Pavarotti's tones became stalwart.
He also acted effectively, using spare but telling gestures.
   In 1976, Pavarotti sang at the Met's opening night in this same
opera. It was his first Met venture into heavier roles than the
light, clear bel canto parts he had been singing. One heard strain
in his voice as he repeatedly sang Manrico that season. Now, the
role sounds natural and totally unstrained.
   Miss Marton was singing Leonora at the Met for the first time.
Her voice is closer to being shrill than soft and sweet, but she
has the volume, flexibility and stamina for the part. The last-act
duet with Milnes was excitingly sung by both. And her ``D'amor
sull'ali rosee'' was affecting.
   Miss Cossotto, who made her Met debut 20 years ago, began with a
hard vibrato but she dug into the part of Azucena with artistry.
   Bass Jeffrey Wells, a native of Baton Rouge, La., made his Met
debut singing virtually the entire first scene. Wells, who has sung
the captain of the guards in this opera with the Washington Opera
and Canadian Opera, was self-possessed and sounded splendid.
   James Levine conducted.
   First lady Nancy Reagan attended the opening, seated in one of
the center boxes. Also in the audience were United Kingdom
Ambassador and Mrs. Antony Acland, Italian Ambassador and Mrs.
Rinaldo Petrignani, Mr. and Mrs. Henry Kissinger, Oscar de la Renta
and Rudolf Nureyev.
   The top-price tickets, $1,000, included a post-opera party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880927-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 0319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoxOffice     09-27 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Dead Ringers' Wins Box Office Weekend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Dead Ringers,'' a disturbing psychological
thriller about twin gynecologists, opened in the No. 1 spot at the
nation's box offices over the weekend while the rest of the field
was dominated by summer holdovers.
   Directed by David Cronenberg and starring Jeremy Irons in the
dual role as brothers Beverly and Elliot Mantle, ``Dead Ringers''
collected $3 million, according to figures released Monday by
Exhibitor Relations Co.
   Two Disney films re-emerged among the box-office leaders, as
``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' moved to fourth with receipts of $1.7
million and ``Cocktail'' advanced to fifth with revenues of $1.64
million.
   The country's box office proceeds continued to be sluggish, with
only three movies netting more than $2 million. Six films passed
the $2 million mark last weekend, and even that was considered
disappointing.
   ``Die Hard,'' the Bruce Willis action film, finished at No. 2
with $2.5 million worth of tickets sold.
   Former box-office champion ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' a comedy
featuring Jamie Lee Curtis and John Cleese, fell to No. 3, with
$2.2 million.
   ``A Nightmare on Elm Street 4'' came in sixth with $1.62
million, followed by ``Young Guns'' in seventh with $1.5 million.
   Rounding out the top 10 were ``Moon Over Parador'' in eighth
with $1.5 million, ``Betrayed'' in ninth with $1.4 million and the
new film ``Kansas,'' starring Matt Dillon, in tenth with $1.3
million.
   Two heavily promoted new movies _ ``Gorillas in the Mist'' and
``Patty Hearst'' _ generated dramatically different business.
   Playing on just 15 screens, ``Gorillas'' drew $367,000, or
$24,462 per screen. ``Patty Hearst,'' on the other hand, averaged
only $1,300 per screen at 460 theaters nationwide.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``Dead Ringers,'' 20th Century Fox, $3 million, 1,042
screens, $2,891 per screen, $3 million, one week.
   2. ``Die Hard,'' 20th Century Fox, $2.5 million, 1,282 screens,
$1,909 per screen, $68.2 million, 11 weeks.
   3. ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' MGM, $2.2 million, 1,164 screens,
$1,895 per screen, $48.3 million, 11 weeks.
   4. ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' Disney, $1.7 million, 1,321
screens, $1,280 per screen, $138.2 million, 14 weeks.
   5. ``Cocktail,'' Disney, $1.64 million, 1,276 screens, $1,287
per screen, $65.4 million, nine weeks.
   6. ``A Nightmare on Elm Street 4,'' New Line, $1.62 million,
1,207 screens, $1,339 per screen, $43.6 million, six weeks.
   7. ``Young Guns,'' 20th Century Fox, $1.5 million, 1,295
screens, $1,168 per screen, $36.9 million, seven weeks.
   8. ``Moon Over Parador,'' Universal, $1.5 million, 1,058
screens, $1,390 per screen, $8.8 million, three weeks.
   9. ``Betrayed,'' United Artists, $1.4 million, 1,066 screens,
$1,305 per screen, $21.7 million, five weeks.
   10. ``Kansas,'' Trans World, $1.3 million, 847 screens, $1,505
per screen, $1.3 million, one week.
