<HEAD>USIA To Broadcast Elections Worldwide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Information Agency will broadcast
24-hour coverage of the Nov. 8 elections on its Worldnet television
satellite network to Europe, Africa, Latin America, Asia,
Australia, the Middle East and the Caribbean.
   Worldnet, created in November 1983, broadcast similar coverage
during the last presidential elections, and has considerably
expanded its audience since then, USIA spokeswoman Robin Kline said
Monday.
   Worldnet ordinarily transmits 17 hours of coverage every weekday
to 95 countries, she said. Election day coverage will begin late on
Nov. 8 and last for the next 24 hours.
</TEXT>
