<HEAD>Dukakis A ``Smart Aleck,'' Ford Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis has developed a ``smart alecky'' campaign style that will
hurt him in the November election, said former President Gerald
Ford.
   ``If I were advising him I'd tell him to shut up,'' Ford said
Monday when asked about the first debate between Dukakis and the
GOP nominee Vice President George Bush.
   ``I think he (Dukakis) hurt himself,'' the former Republican
president said. ``You don't have to be as glib as I think he
thought he was being.''
   Ford also noted Bush committed no gaffe.
   ``That is of course important,'' Ford said. During a 1976 debate
with Jimmy Carter, Ford's statement that Poland was not under
Soviet domination was considered a gaffe that may have cost him the
election.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>James A. Danforth Was Friend Of Quayle Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who Vice President George Bush says
his opponent is ``ridiculing'' when he refers to his running mate
as ``J. Danforth Quayle'' was an Army hero in World War II.
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis has repeatedly
referred to Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind, by his full name of J. Danforth
Quayle, a practice Bush condemned as ``beneath this process''
during Sunday's debate.
   James Alexander Danforth rose to the rank of captain in the Army
infantry and earned three Purple Hearts during the war, including
one in the D-Day invasion of Normandy. He died in an Army hospital
in England of the third wound, said Quayle campaign spokesman Jeff
Nesbitt.
   Danforth was a longtime friend of the Quayle family, and his
father attended the University of Illinois with the senator's
grandfather, said James Quayle, father of the senator.
   ``He was a great guy,'' James Quayle said. ``We lost a lot of
great friends, but Jimmy was the first one that died. What Bush
said was right.''
</TEXT>
