<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 0304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Laos-MIAs     09-27 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Laos-MIAs,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Team Leaves For Crash Site Surveys In Laos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. military team seeking to account
for missing U.S. servicemen flew to Laos today to survey sites
where American planes crashed during the Indochina war, an official
said.
   The team, which departed from Bangkok, is to survey an area
around Sepone in eastern Laos to prepare for possible later
excavations of the crash sites, said Maj. Thomas J. Boyd, spokesman
for the U.S. Pacific Command.
   The team is from the U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution Center and
Army Central Identification Laboratory, both Honolulu-based units
seeking to account for 2,393 Americans missing in action from the
war in Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia.
   Boyd said the team included a Marine with special expertise in
plane crashes.
   ``They will look at crash sites and determine what kind of
aircraft (crashed), how it crashed, and determine the potential for
possible future site excavations,'' Boyd told reporters.
   U.S. losses in that area near the Vietnamese border include
airmen downed in missions to cut off the Ho Chi Minh Trail, used by
communist North Vietnam to infiltrate troops to U.S.-backed South
Vietnam. The war ended with communist victories in all three
Indochinese countries in 1975.
   The United States and Laos have conducted three previous joint
crash site excavations, most recently in May.
   In Vietnam, meanwhile, a U.S. military team was working with
Vietnamese officials on the second day of an unprecedented
investigation to determine the fates of seven U.S. airmen lost in
plane crashes near the capital, Hanoi.
   The U.S. team, which brought its own interpreters, is
interviewing villagers who witnessed incidents in which the men
were lost and is seeking evidence such as local government reports
and human remains.
   Boyd said the seven are among 70 ``discrepancy cases'' _ those
in which the United States says there is strong evidence the men
survived and were taken under Vietnamese control. The United States
says it cannot prove any Americans are alive in Indochina, but
cannot ignore that possibility.
   The Defense Intelligence Agency is currently investigating 119
reports of purported sightings of Americans, Boyd said.
   The Americans drove to the Vietnamese villages Monday in jeeps
they had flown in from Honolulu the day before. The search is
scheduled to last about 10 days.
   Boyd said the two sides may later excavate plane crash sites
found during the investigation.
   Previously, the only significant joint field activity was in
late 1985, when U.S. soldiers and Vietnamese state workers dug up
the wreckage of a U.S. B-52 bomber just outside Hanoi. They found
remains but none were identified as missing Americans.
   Lt. Col. Joe Harvey, leader of the U.S. team in Vietnam, earlier
expressed hope for several joint investigation operations in the
coming months. ``We are prepared to provide four teams, if Vietnam
agrees,'' he said.
   Of the 2,393 Americans missing, 1,757 are in Vietnam, 547 in
Laos, 83 in Cambodia and six in China. U.S. forces withdrew from
Indochina in 1973 after the conflict cost 58,000 American lives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
