<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Floods     09-27 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Floods,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rains Hampers Rescue Efforts In Flood-Affected States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More rain fell today in flooded parts of
the northern state of Punjab, hampering operations to rescue at
least 200,000 people marooned by rising waters, an official said.
   Fifty air force helicopters were deployed to lift people to
safer areas, but the operations were disrupted by rains, said J.F.
Ribeiro, adviser to the state governor.
   Ribeiro said at least 138 people have died in the flooding,
mainly from drownings, in Punjab since it began Wednesday. He said
the inundation had claimed at least 200 lives in the neighboring
states of Haryana, Himachal Pradesh and Jammu and Kashmir.
   Punjab, the most populated of the four states, has borne the
brunt of the floods. The state's road and rail links with the rest
of the country were cut off, though airports were still functioning.
   The three major rivers in Punjab, the Ravi, Beas and Sutlej were
all flowing above danger levels, Ribeiro said. He said six of the
state's nine administrative districts had been affected.
   More than 1,500 villages in the six districts were inundated and
waters have entered low-lying areas of Ludhiana and Kapurthala
cities, he said.
   The floods were caused by heavy rains in northern India as the
annual southwest monsoon draws to a close. In New Delhi,
authorities ordered the closure of a bridge over the adjacent
Jamuna River, which is also flowing above the danger mark.
   A government official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told
reporters Monday that Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi had appointed a
crisis management group to tackle the emergency.
   Floods triggered by the summer monsoon are a frequent problem in
India, Nepal and Bangladesh.
   In late August, monsoon-swollen rivers innundated three-fourths
of Bangladesh in the worst floods in the country's histry. The
government said at least 1,000 people died but newspapers put the
toll at more than 2,000.
</TEXT>
