<HEAD>Dollar Dips, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched down agaist the Japanese yen
Tuesday while share prices rebounded on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar, which opened at 134.60 yen, closed slightly lower at
134.58 yen, down 0.15 yen from Monday's close of 134.73 yen. The
currency traded within a narrow range of 134.52-134.60 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 56.37-point
loser Monday, recouped 165.81 points, or 0.61 percent, to reach
27,499.56. The main index quickly earned 113.83 points shortly
after the market opened and kept the winning trend.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 1.8 billion
shares, the largest amount since July 15, when 2 billion shares
were traded.
   A Nomura Securities' analyst described morning trading as heavy
and led by steels.
   ``Participants have become active mainly because today (Tuesday)
is the first day of a new year in stock trading,'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity. Many Japanese businesses begin
their new financial year Tuesday.
   In addition to positive economic factors for stock investment,
such as less concern about world-wide inflation, participants also
were reacting favorably to news of Emperor Hirohito's stable
condition, the analyst said.
</TEXT>
