<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Stock Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed slightly lower today against the
Japanese yen, while share prices rebounded on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 134.58 yen, down 0.15 yen from Monday's
close of 134.73 yen. Opening slightly higher at 134.60 yen, the
currency moved in a tight range of 134.52-134.60 yen.
   ``Although the dollar-selling intervention in New York and
Europe overnight kept the currency from rising further against the
yen, it could not lower the dollar-yen rate that much,'' said Ikuko
Watanabe, an exchange dealer with the Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo.
   Speculative dollar-buying mostly by financial institutions
increased toward the end of the session, she said.
   Citing the very small range in which the dollar moved today
despite the dollar-selling, Watanabe said the currency remained
strong.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which lost 56.37 points Monday, recouped 165.81 points, or
0.61 percent to close at 27,499.56.
   Led by a quick 113.83-point early morning gain, the trading was
hectic with an estimated 1.8 billion shares traded on the first
section, the largest amount since July 15 when more than 2 billion
shares changed hands.
   ``Because today was the first day of the new business year, the
market had very active trading,'' said a stock dealer with the
Daiwa Securities, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The new fiscal year for most Japanese companies started today.
   Among the issues that attracted investors were steels,
shipbuilding and real estate.
</TEXT>
