<DOCNO> AP880927-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 0658EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Carter     09-27 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Carter,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carter Eulogized as Man of Wit and Courage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLAINS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billy Carter, known to millions as the
wisecracking brother of the nation's 39th president, was eulogized
as a couragous man who was prepared to devote his life helping
others overcome alcoholism.
   ``Billy Carter was struck down in the prime of his life,''
country singer Tom T. Hall said in the eulogy at a graveside
ceremony Monday. ``He was just beginning a new chapter. He was
planning his travels to help others take charge of their lives.''
   Carter, 51, died Sunday of pancreatic cancer, the disease that
killed his father and an older sister.
   About 500 mourners gathered at the Lebanon Cemetery to pay their
last respects to Carter, who was thrust into the national spotlight
after his older brother, Jimmy, became president in 1977.
   The younger Carter became well known for his down-home and often
irreverent witticisms and his beer-drinking at a service station he
once owned in Plains.
   Billy Carter's widow, Sybil, and the couple's six children were
seated in front of Carter's cherry casket, which was covered by a
blanket of exotic flowers and surrounded by dozens of wreaths.
   In the crowd were Jimmy Carter and his wife, Rosalynn, who lived
next door to Billy Carter. The former president said his
relationship with his brother, strained during his years in the
White House, improved in later years.
   ``We worked together for many years, side by side. While I was
president, we went in opposite directions, but in the last year,
we've just been friends,'' he said.
   ``My mother said, `Never underestimate him,''' the former
president said. ``He was the most intelligent one in the family.''
   In delivering the eulogy, Hall noted that Carter had overcome
many of his own personal problems and was planning to work with
others overcoming alcoholism.
   In 1979, Carter spent seven weeks in an alcohol rehabilitation
program.
   ``He died with courage, not to say he went gently into that dark
night,'' Hall said.
   In the year since his cancer was diagnosed, Carter had tried a
variety of experimental treatments. He lived longer than his
doctors expected.
   Carter was buried a short distance from the graves of his mother
``Miss Lillian'' Carter, and his father, James Earl Carter.
   The service was conducted by the Rev. Dan Ariail, pastor of the
Maranatha Baptist Church, where Jimmy Carter teaches Sunday school.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
