<HEAD>Dollar Slips, Gold Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slipped against most major foreign
currencies in early European trading today while gold prices firmed.
   Currency traders said the market was assessing the impact of
Monday's concerted central bank intervention. They said the
intervention, started by the West German Bundesbank, dumped between
$300 million and $500 million on the market.
   In London, traders were also awaiting the 11:30 (6:30 a.m. EDT)
release of British trade figures for August. The current account
deficit is expected to be between 1.2 billion and 1.9 billion
pounds ($2 billion and $3.1 billion.)
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 134.58 yen, down 0.15 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 134.65 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8825 West German marks, down from 1.8835
   _1.5935 Swiss francs, unchanged
   _6.4065 French francs, down from 6.5000
   _2.1212 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1230
   _1,404.00 Italian lire, up from 1,403.50
   _1.2195 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2211
   In London, the British pound was little changed, trading at
1.6695 dollars, compared with 1.6668 late Monday.
   Gold prices firmed in lackluster trading.
   The precious metal opened in London at a bid of $395.70 a troy
ounce, up from $394.50 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $397.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $396.70, up from $392.00 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 3.01 to close at a bid 401.16.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.14 a troy
ounce, little changed from late Monday's 6.16.
