<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC-HotLab     09-27 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC-Hot Lab,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Unveils New `Hot Lab' For Studying World's Deadliest Viruses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Centers for Disease Control researchers
soon will move into their new ``hot lab,'' a $20 million
super-sealed laboratory with a 21st century feel, to study the
world's deadliest viruses.
   CDC officials unveiled it Monday, showing off the secret-code
passageways, air locks, decontamination equipment, containment
cabinets and space suits that will be off-limits to all outsiders
once deadly pathogens are brought in starting next month. The
complex will be formally dedicated Oct. 28.
   For years, the center has studied what scientists call Level 4
pathogens: mircroorganisms or viruses with the most dangerous
classification according to deadliness, availability of vaccine or
treatment and risk of transmission in the laboratory.
   Such agents include Ebola hemorrhagic fever, Lassa fever and
Rift Valley fever, diseases rarely, if ever, seen in this country
and much more hazardous in the lab than AIDS or rabies, said Dr.
Olen M. Kew, chief of the Molecular Virology Laboratory at the
center.
   The CDC's first facility for the study of such pathogens, built
in 1967, was in a large trailer. Two larger labs followed.
   The new facility, officially known as the Viral and Rickettsial
Diseases Laboratory but called ``the hot lab'' by those who work
there, will give CDC researchers more space and more modern
technology than they've ever had before, said Dr. Mike Kiley, a
microbiologist with the Office of Biosafety.
   ``After 10 years, the old Level 4 lab was beginning to show its
age,'' Kiley said.
   ``This will very much contribute to our overall mission of
controlling infectious disease ... around the world,'' said Dr.
James M. Hughes, deputy director of the CDC's Center for Infectious
Diseases.
   The laboratory building, located at the federal health agency's
compound near Emory University, spans more than 95,000 square feet
and is actually two buildings in one _ a six-story facility
containing 12 separate labs, and a three-story Level 4 facility
with two separate state-of-the-art containment labs, connected by a
central atrium.
   The new labs also have intricate waste disposal facilities, to
inactivate, then remove, any hazardous substances.
   Walls in the new Level 4 facility are poured concrete, 9 inches
thick. Inside, the labs themselves, researchers will wear blue
plastic space suits, connected to a safe air supply by red hoses
which dangle from various points above them.
   To enter their lab, they will pass through a series of
increasingly secure checkpoints _ from the card-key system which
opens the outer corridor doors, to a secret-code control which
opens inner doors, to heavy, submarine-style steel gasket doors
opening into a special chemical shower and air lock. That, in turn,
opens onto the lab.
   Getting in takes about five minutes; getting out takes about 20,
as workers shower first in their space suits _ with a special
disinfectant fluid _ then take showers themselves.
   ``We go out to lunch sometimes, but you don't drink a lot of
coffee in the morning,'' joked research microbiologist Luanne
Elliott. ``It takes too long to get in and out.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
