<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KodakSettlement     09-27 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kodak Settlement,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Approves Settlement for Owners of Kodak Instant Cameras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 3.4 million U.S. owners of Eastman Kodak
Co.'s discontinued instant cameras should get up to $70 in cash and
coupons just in time for Christmas under a new settlement.
   ``I think both sides agree it's an excellent settlement,'' said
Burton I. Weinstein of Chicago, one of four attorneys who filed the
class-action lawsuit against Kodak, saying he was ``very, very
pleased'' after Monday's decision.
   Kodak, which was forced to stop making instant cameras and film
after a patent dispute, said the settlement is worth $150 million,
but attorneys for camera owners pegged it at more than $200 million.
   The settlement approved by Cook County Circuit Judge Thomas
Rakowski applies to 39 Kodak instant camera models, ranging from
the Fiesta, the lowest-priced model, to the Kodamatic 980L, the
most expensive.
   Weinstein said the cash and coupons would probably be mailed in
late November, in time for Christmas shopping.
   Depending on the cost of their instant camera, owners will
receive amounts ranging from $52 in cash and $18 in coupons to
$19.50 in cash and $30.50 in coupons.
   The coupons, accompanied by proof of purchase, then can be sent
to the company for a rebate. The coupons could also be used in
purchasing Kodak products such as film, cameras or batteries.
   ``From Kodak's point of view, it's good and fair,'' said William
Campbell, a Chicago attorney representing the Rochester, N.Y.,
company.
   The lawsuit was filed against the company in January 1986,
asking that it compensate owners for instant cameras that were
virtually useless after a ruling against Kodak in its legal battle
with Polaroid Corp.
   A federal judge in Boston said Kodak infringed on Polaroid's
instant-camera patent when it entered the market in 1976.
   Instant photography was invented by Dr. Edwin H. Land, founder
of Polaroid, and was first marketed in 1948. It enables users to
view a photographic print shortly after taking a picture.
   Polaroid retained a monopoly in the instant photography field
until 1976, when Kodak entered the market with a competing system.
Polaroid immediately filed a lawsuit, charging patent infringement.
   A federal judge in Boston sided with Polaroid and the U.S.
Supreme Court let stand lower court rulings when it refused to hear
Kodak's appeal in October 1986.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
