<HEAD>China Announces End to Rocket Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has concluded a rocket launching into the
East China Sea and normal navigation and air flights through the
area can resume Wednesday, the official Xinhua News Agency
announced today.
   The report did not say when the launching took place or what was
the purpose of launching the ``carrier'' rocket.
   Western military experts in Beijing speculated that the launch
either could be a test of new models of satellite booster rockets
now being developed or, more likely, a Chinese Navy missile.
   On Sept. 8, Xinhua warned ships and planes to stay out of the
target area, located about 112 miles off of China's Zhejiang
province and with a radius of 35 nautical miles, between 10 a.m.
and 5 p.m. from Sept. 14 to Oct. 3.
