<1ST_LINE>u p PM-ACLU-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0481 09-27 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ACLU-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0481,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ACLU Official Accuses Bush of `McCarthyite Slander'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Eds: Top 8 grafs new with ACLU official's comments; picks up pvs
3rd graf bgng, ``In terms.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The executive director of the American Civil
Liberties Union today accused Vice President George Bush of
``McCarthyite slander'' against the organization during his
nationally televised debate Sunday night with Democrat Michael
Dukakis.
   The official, Ira Glasser, said Bush's statement that the ACLU
is involved in a lawsuit seeking to remove the tax exemption of the
Roman Catholic Church is wrong, as is a suggestion that the group
favors allowing child pornography.
   ``That kind of slur, that kind of McCarthyite slander, in
characterizing what the ACLU does, is outrageous and it does not
characterize what the ACLU is about,'' Glasser said on ``CBS This
Morning.''
   He referred to the 1950s anti-communist campaign of Sen. Joseph
McCarthy, R-Wis., in which many people were tarred as Communist
sympathizers without proof.
   There is a court case challenging the Catholic church's tax
exemption but the ACLU is not involved, Glasser said. He said his
organization is on record favoring criminal penalties in cases of
child pornography.
   ``The fact is that we are devoted to only one thing, and that is
the non-partisan defense of the Bill of Rights,'' Glasser said.
``Sooner or later everybody needs the ACLU. When your
constitutional rights are threatened or violated, you'll come to
the ACLU.''
   Haley Barbour of the Bush campaign responded: ``The ACLU has a
well-earned reputation as caring more about criminals' rights and
prisoners' rights than they care about victims' rights.''
   On Monday, ACLU president Norman Dorsen said Bush had ``totally
twisted'' the group's positions Sunday night as he sought to
portray Dukakis as a liberal outside the American mainstream.
   ``In terms of our day-to-day work over many years, we have
consistently acted in a non-partisan way on behalf of some of the
most basic principles of the Constitution,'' Dorsen said. ``Our
positions are mainstream positions.''
   Bush has repeatedly attacked Dukakis for being a ``card-carrying
member'' of the civil liberties union.
   In Sunday's debate, he said: ``I don't want my 10-year-old
granddaughter to go into an X-rated movie. ... I don't think
they're right to try to take the tax exemption away from the
Catholic Church. I don't want to see the kiddie pornography laws
repealed. I don't want to see `Under God' come out from our
currency. Now, these are all positions of the ACLU and I don't
agree with them.''
   Dorsen said the ACLU does not want 10-year-olds to see
pornographic movies, but believes that the movie rating system
amounts to illegal censorship.
   ``We believe that's a decision that should be made by each
family,'' he said.
   He agreed that the ACLU opposes tax exemptions for churches on
the basis that they amount to a government subsidy of religion. He
stressed that the organization's position applies to all religious
groups, not just the Catholic Church.
   Dorsen also took issue with Bush's ``kiddie pornography''
attack, saying, ``Our view is that the government can prosecute the
makers of pornography (for) the improper use of children for this
purpose. We don't feel that the material itself can be censored.''
   Finally, Dorsen said, the ACLU has never challenged the use of
``In God We Trust'' on currency, although he agreed that such use
is contrary to the organization's principles.
   ``It's not part of the government's job to promote a religious
belief, and the Supreme Court has said that as far back as 1947,''
he said. But Dorsen said the ACLU has never tried to have the words
removed from currency.
   Dorsen also pointed out that the organization recently defended
Lt. Col. Oliver North, saying the government violated his Fifth
Amendment rights when it prosecuted him for his role in the
Iran-Contra affair.
   And, Dorsen said, the ACLU is about to file a brief in federal
court in Washington on behalf of former White House aide Lyn
Nofziger, saying he is being improperly prosecuted for illegal
lobbying.
</TEXT>
