<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-Convoys 2ndLd-Writethru a0489 09-27 0784</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Convoys, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0489,0804</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Views Gulf Escort Operation As Qualified Success</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with first unescorted tanker sailing through
gulf, 46 killed since convoys began, details. EDITS to trim and
conform. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD USS VANDEGRIFT IN THE PERSIAN GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sailing into
the Strait of Hormuz under a full moon, this U.S. missile frigate
tried to draw within 900 feet of the supertanker Townsend, a
lumbering 294,739-ton behemoth more than 81 times its size.
   The purpose, explained the Vandegrift's skipper, was to see if
the little warship could snuggle close enough to the tanker so that
together they would appear as one blip on radar screens in Iran's
so-called ``Silkworm Alley.''
   ``It's just something the Pentagon wanted us to try,'' said
Cmdr. Eric Utegaard of Alexandria, Va., as his ship struggling to
maintain 17 knots in the churning wake of the Townsend's
30-foot-wide propeller.
   Utegaard could not know last Saturday that ``Operation Earnest
Will'' mission No. 89 would mark the final time a U.S. warship
would escort a Kuwaiti oil tanker through the Persian Gulf.
   Today, the first U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tanker to sail without a
close escort of U.S. warships left Kuwait's main terminal, heading
south through waters where peace has prevailed since the Iran-Iraq
cease-fire began Aug. 20.
   Although traveling alone, the 81,283-ton oil products carrier
Surf City would not be unprotected should trouble arise during its
two-day, 550-mile passage through the gulf and Strait of Hormuz,
U.S. military sources said.
   ``She's on her way, and will be under surveillance at all
times,'' one source said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   While the Vandegrift trailed the tanker at a distance, for the
first time since the U.S. convoy escort policy began July 21, 1987,
no warship was sailing directly behind it.
   However, mine fears remain high following reports that Italian
mine-hunters had found an explosive in the south central gulf _ the
third discovered in five days.
   The White House announced Monday the reduction of tension since
the Iran-Iraq cease-fire had led President Reagan to end the
``tight escort'' operation.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said U.S. warships will
continue to be stationed in the gulf, prepared to assist any ship
that might need help. The United States now has 26 ships in the
region.
   Right to the end, the Navy was looking for better ways to
conduct an operation in which its ships had already sailed 50,000
miles escorting convoys through the embattled oil artery.
   The Long Beach, Calif.-based Vandegrift was the Townsend's lone
escort for the voyage northward, and earlier had accompanied the
88th mission, a northbound convoy with the 401,382-ton Bridgeton,
famous for hitting a mine during the first ``Earnest Will'' mission.
   The Bridgeton's encounter with a 500-pound mine apparently laid
by the Iranians pointed up what U.S. officers such as Utegaard say
is ``still the single biggest threat in the gulf.''
   Apart from the Bridgeton, no ship under U.S. escort encountered
any difficulty with mines, missiles, aircraft or gunboat attacks.
   Last Oct. 16, however, an Iranian Silkworm missile attack
severely damaged the 81,283-ton tanker Sea Isle City at Kuwait's Al
Ahmadi loading terminal and the ship's American master was badly
wounded.
   The ship, like the Bridgeton, later returned to service.
   Forty-six Americans have died in the gulf since shortly before
the U.S. began escorting ships. On May 17, 1987, an Iraqi fighter
jet mistakenly fired two missiles into the frigate USS Stark,
killing 37 U.S. sailors. Nine Americans died in the gulf after the
escorts began _ seven in helicopter crashes and two in the crash of
a Navy plane from a carrier support group in Arabian Sea.
   The cruiser USS Vincennes shot down an Iranian jetliner in the
gulf on July 3, killing all 290 people aboard, after crewmen
mistook it for an attacking Iranian fighter jet.
   Although the ostensible purpose of ``Operation Earnest Will''
was to protect the 11 reflagged Kuwaiti tankers and underscore a
U.S. commitment to freedom of navigation, officials say it was
motivated greatly by Washington's concern about growing Soviet
influence in the gulf.
   Some diplomats noted it was only after Moscow agreed to lease
three tankers to Kuwait and give them armed escort protection that
the United States moved firmly to reflag and escort part of
Kuwait's fleet.
   The escort missions proved formidable enough that other foreign
ships became ``tag-alongs,' lining up ahead, behind or alongside
the American convoys as they traveled the dangerous waters of
Hormuz and the southern gulf where Iranian raiders were most active.
   Some even painted their sterns with American names to dupe
Iranian gunners into thinking they were part of the reflagged
Kuwaiti fleet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
