<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0431,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Emphasizes Debate High Points, Distances Himself from ACLU</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new graf after pvs 8th graf bgng, ``I don't,'' with
ACLU response.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis is moving quickly to
exploit his high points from the presidential debate and distance
himself from the American Civil Liberties Union.
   At a rally Monday evening in downtown Journal Square, the
Democratic nominee said that during Sunday night's debate, his
Republican opponent George Bush ``suggested that I agree with every
position ever taken by the American Civil Liberties Union.''
   ``That's nonsense and he knows it,'' Dukakis said.
   ``Two months ago I signed one of the toughest child pornography
laws in the United States of America,'' he said. Meanwhile, his
staff passed out a ``fact sheet'' which said the ACLU has urged
repeal of all child pornography laws.
   ``I've always supported tax exemptions for religious
institutions,'' said Dukakis, ``and I certainly do not support
Oliver North who the ACLU is defending.''
   Dukakis' membership in the ACLU is one of the issues the
Republican nominee has raised in an effort to portray the
Massachusetts governor as a liberal out of the mainstream of
current thinking.
   During the debate, Bush referred to Dukakis as a ``card-carrying
member'' of the ACLU, described the group as a liberal organization
and attacked some of its positions.
   ``I don't want my 10-year-old granddaughter to go into an
X-rated movie,'' Bush said. ``I don't think they're right to try to
take the tax exemption away from the Catholic Church. I don't want
to see the kiddie pornography laws repealed. I don't want to see
`Under God' come out from our currency. Now, these are all
positions of the ACLU and I don't agree with them.''
   ACLU officials accused Bush of distorting the organization's
positions and engaging in ``McCarthyite slander.'' ACLU president
Norman Dorsen said the group has consistently taken ``mainstream
positions'' intended to safeguard constitutional rights.
   The Dukakis campaign fact sheet said the ACLU has represented
people suing the Massachusetts governor's administration in an
effort to overturn its policies on drunk driving road blocks and a
regulation giving homosexuals low priority when seeking to become
foster parents.
   Dukakis campaign officials put together two new television
commercials showing excerpts from the debate.
   One of the 30-second commercials shows Dukakis talking about
college opportunity, health insurance and concluding, ``The best
America is not behind us. The best America is yet to come.''
   The second commercial is an excerpt from his closing statement.
People interviewed in focus groups after the debate resppnded very
favorably to his closing statement.
   Campaign aides said the commercials would run nationally on the
major television networks.
   At rallies in Ohio and New Jersey, Dukakis attacked Bush for
failing to talk about health insurance, college opportunity, Social
Security and Medicare.
   ``Mr. Bush offers the easy way,'' said the Democratic nominee.
``He sees no challenges; he offers no solutions, and he will lead
America nowhere as president of the United States.''
   He was campaigning today in another key industrial state _
Illinois _ with appearances in Peoria and Melrose Park, a suburb of
Chicago.
   When Dukakis landed at Newark Airport on Monday he got a look at
an airplane he hopes one day will be his to use, Air Force One.
President Reagan had flown into the same airport earlier en route
to address the United Nations.
   Dukakis was taking advantage of the presence of many world
leaders for the U.N. session.
   He was flying to New York on Wednesday to meet with Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze. Before leaving the city the
following morning, Dukakis also planned to meet with French
President Francois Mitterand.
   The meetings are designed to help him counter arguments by the
Republicans that he lacks foreign policy experience.
</TEXT>
