<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CarChase-Arrest     09-27 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Car Chase-Arrest,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Simon and Simon' Stunt Men Chase Hit-Run Suspect Into Arms Of
Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four ``Simon and Simon'' stunt drivers turned
into real-life heroes when they chased a man straight to a police
station after he ran down an officer directing traffic during
filming of the TV show, authorities said.
   Samir Shamoun, 29, of Calabasas was arrested Monday after the
angry stunt drivers chased him at speeds up to 70 mph for more than
a mile to the Los Angeles Police Department's West Valley station.
   ``It's a little ironic,'' said Officer Frank Nuckles. ``This guy
runs over a `blue suit' and then he runs to the police station for
safety.''
   Officer Dick Neuenschwander, 53, was struck while working
off-duty in a restaurant parking lot in the San Fernando Valley,
police said. He was in serious but stable condition at Northridge
Hospital.
   Witnesses said Shamoun, who worked near the filming site, got
angry when told him he couldn't drive through a parking lot
bustling with movie people.
   Shamoun appeared to decide to back up, but then the van lurched
forward, police Detective Don Bellante said. Neuenschwander fell
while trying to get out of the way and the van ran over his left
arm and leg.
   Four members of the ``Simon and Simon'' crew jumped into two
cars and chased the van as it fled the scene, Bellante said.
   ``He was getting away with running over a policeman,'' one of
the crew members, Gary Daily, said later. ``That's totally wrong.''
   One of the cars eventually cut in front of the van, forcing it
to a stop at the curb right in front of the police station,
Bellante said. All five men ran into the station where officers
stopped the fracas before anyone was injured, Bellante said.
   ``They came crashing through the front door of the station with
this donnybrook going,'' he said. ``Officers jumped over the desk
and grabbed them all until they could sort out who was who and what
was going on.''
</TEXT>
