<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KraftTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0532 09-27 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kraft Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0532,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mass Murder Trial Opens With Accounts of Necrophilia, Mutilation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents. LEADS with 4 grafs to RECAST, add that trial
repeatedly delayed since his 1983 arrest. Picks up 5th graf pvs,
`He has...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former computer programmer on trial
for 16 murders was described by a prosecutor as a homosexual who
drove on Southern California roads for a decade, picking up young
hitchhikers and drugging, strangling and mutilating them.
   During his opening statement Monday, Orange County Deputy
District Attorney Bryan Brown pieced together the last hours of the
men Randy Kraft is charged with killing. Most were allegedly
hitchhikers picked up by Kraft in a car stocked with drugs and beer.
   ``This is a road map of what the evidence will show,'' Brown
told a Superior Court jury.
   Kraft, 43, has pleaded innocent to 16 counts of murder and
various other counts of mayhem and sodomy. His trial was delayed 12
times since his arrest more than five years ago. Prosecutors
believe they can link him to 21 other slayings and say the death
toll may be as high as 60.
   He has been jailed since May 14, 1983, when a California Highway
Patrol officer stopped him because his car was weaving and found a
dying Marine on the passenger seat.
   Authorities found what they believe was a coded ``score card''
of victims in the car, and 47 color photographs of several young
men, many of them nude and apparently posed after they were slain.
   The evidence shows Kraft would bind his drug-dazed victims,
choke them with a belt around the neck and have sex with them, the
prosecutor said.
   Many victims were mutilated before they were heaved from a
fast-moving car, Brown said.
   Kraft's fetish for saving mementos of victims and taking
post-death photographs was his undoing, Brown said.
   Defense attorney C. Thomas McDonald, who responded to the
Brown's two-hour statement with a 10-minute opening, warned jurors
against being swayed by vivid descriptions of the killings.
   ``These are tactics designed to inflame you,'' McDonald said.
``This is a tactical decision made by the prosecutor. He won't be
able to prove it. This case is based on suspicion, innuendo and
prosecutorial rhetoric.
   Brown detailed the deaths of the 16 victims, six of them Marines
and all age 18 to 25. The killings occurred between December 1972
and May 1983.
</TEXT>
