<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MaineBishop     09-27 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Maine Bishop,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maine's Catholic Bishop Stepping Down for Health Reasons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishop Edward C. O'Leary, spiritual
leader of Maine's 278,000 Roman Catholics, is retiring because of
declining health, a spokesman for the statewide Diocese of Portland
said today.
   The 68-year-old bishop, who has headed the diocese since 1974,
planned to make the formal announcement at a news conference at the
Catholic chancery.
   O'Leary's decision was prompted by a decline in his overall
medical condition rather than any specific ailment, according to
Marc Mutty, director of communications for the diocese.
   ``The schedule is just too much for a man of his age,'' Mutty
said. ``He just does not think he can keep up with the pace it has
demanded.''
   The announcement followed word from the Vatican that Pope John
Paul II had accepted O'Leary's resignation, Mutty said, adding that
``nobody had any inkling of this before this morning.''
   Until a successor is named, O'Leary will serve as apostolic
administrator of the diocese, leaving him in charge but without the
authority to launch new initiatives, according to Mutty.
   It usually takes three to six months before a new bishop is
named, he said.
   A Bangor native, O'Leary was educated at Holy Cross College in
Worcester, Mass., and St. Paul's Seminary in Ottawa. He was
ordained a priest in 1946.
</TEXT>
