<1ST_LINE>u a PM-GangRape 3rdLd-Writethru a0545 09-27 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Rape, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0545,0723</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts Man Of Sexual Assault In Gang Rape Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS after 2nd graf pvs, `Jurors deliberated...was
announced,' one graf with sentencing date. SUBS 7th graf pvs,
`District Judge...' to delete now-redundant first reference to
Garcia. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Jurors were...'. Note contents.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury early today convicted a man
described by a prosecutor as the ``head dog'' in a gang rape and
recommended that he get the maximum term of 20 years.
   Jurors deliberated about 20 minutes before returning with a
recommendation that Orlando Garza, 24, be given the maximum term
for his part as the alleged ringleader. He had also faced a fine of
up to $10,000 but there was no mention of a fine when the jury's
decision was annnounced.
   State District Judge Ricardo Garcia set sentencing for Oct. 17.
   There was little reaction from the defendant after the decision
was read. He declined comment after the court session ended and as
he left the Duval County Courthouse with his lawyers.
   Garza, the first of 10 defendants to stand trial in the case,
was accused of being the first man to sexually assault the
19-year-old woman on the night of March 26-27.
   The woman said as many as 23 men raped her after she was forced
to go to a ranch where illegal cockfights were being held near this
town of about 5,000 people south of Corpus Christi.
   A counselor who helped the woman at a sex abuse center said she
telephoned the victim, who has moved from here, to tell her about
the jury's verdict. ``She's happy,'' said counselor Barbara
Jackson. ``She said, `Thank the Lord.'''
   Garcia kept the jury late because he said he wanted the panel to
reach a verdict before he left for a judicial conference in Fort
Worth today.
   Jurors were told they could go home to get some rest and return
for the punishment phase of the trial, but they chose to continue.
   Defense attorneys urged that Garza get probation, but the
Assistant District Attorney Rodolfo Gutierrez asked jurors to
recommend the maximum sentence.
   The prosecutor said he believes that some of the other
defendants might want to plea bargain for shorter prison terms as a
result of Garza's sentence. The next trial in the case is scheduled
for next month.
   Final arguments began shortly before midnight before a courtroom
packed with more than 150 spectators. Jurors began their
deliberations at 2:15 a.m., returning the guilty verdict two hours
later.
   ``To me, it's devastating that a young woman placed herself in a
situation where something just extraordinary may have happened,''
defense attorney Albert Pena said in his final argument to the
six-man, six-woman jury.
   ``She went out there to that cockfight because she wanted to be
with this man here,'' said defense counsel Nago Alaniz, referring
to Garza.
   Alaniz said the woman fabricated the kidnapping and gang-rape
story to protect her reputation and keep her husband from finding
out about her illicit sexual activity with Garza, who said he had
been in an affair with the woman since January.
   Garza on Monday said the woman insisted on having sex with him
that night inside the car and later on the hood of the car, and
that she refused to leave the ranch when he tried to take her home.
   All 10 defendants pleaded innocent to charges ranging from
kidnapping to sexual assault.
   But Gutierrez said in his final argument that Garza ``was the
head dog. He was the one who brought the meat.''
   Assistant District Attorney Rocky Carrillo told the jury, ``You
all will have to determine if we have to reside in our county with
the likes of Orlando Garza.''
   The week-long trial featured testimony by the victim, her
husband and a 12-year-old boy present at the cockfight, who said
his family has moved to another city to escape harassment since he
presented himself as a witness.
   ``He was the only one who was man enough to come up here and
tell you the truth,'' Gutierrez said of the boy while addressing
the jury today.
   Garza also faces an aggravated kidnapping trial in the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
