<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DukakisTargets 1stLd-Writethru a0770 09-27 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis Targets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0770,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Plans To Redirect Resources In Search For Electoral
Majority</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS math, 179 sted 183, and that Texas has third-most
votes, subbing grafs 15-16, The current ... border states</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, refining his plan to break
the Republican Electoral College lock, plans to curtail his efforts
in several states that appear out of reach while escalating the
fight for critical swing states and the major battleground of
Texas, according to campaign aides.
   In all, the states in which Dukakis aides concede their chances
of defeating Republican nominee George Bush are slim carry roughly
100 of the 538 possible Electoral College votes, with 270 needed to
win the White House.
   One Dukakis aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
campaign would begin ``pulling back budget and pulling back staff''
and saving the resources for states that are closer to Dukakis'
reach.
   ``Decisions are being made about every state, about where it's
best to schedule visits and where it would be more productive for
us to be spending time and money,'' another aide said. ``Clearly
there are certain places where we would be better off dedicating
our resources.''
   Considered high among those is Texas, with 29 electoral votes
and where Bush currently holds a lead in the polls. Dukakis and his
running mate, Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, plan an aggressive campaign
there, including ads asking what Bush has done for his adopted home
state and highlighting Bentsen's Texas ties, said a third aide.
   Two of the advisers pointed to Dukakis' recent travel schedule
as evidence of the refined strategy and said it was a good
barometer for states considered competitive.
   ``The governor is committed to a 50-state campaign and so are
we, but we all understand what drives a schedule and we are working
on it together to make the sound strategic decisions,'' said one of
them.
   By that measure, most of the South and Rocky Mountain states
appear to have been de-emphasized.
   Dukakis has campaigned extensively in Texas, and will return
there this week, but he has visited Florida, which has 21 electoral
votes, only once in the past several weeks. He has visited
Mississippi and Virginia one time each, briefly, and has not been
to South Carolina. Dukakis made two stops in Alabama several weeks
ago but has not returned. He has not visited Georgia since the
Democratic convention in July, although he is expected to do so in
the next few weeks in an effort to keep the race competitive there.
   In contrast, he has been to Arkansas and Kentucky at least twice
since the convention, and aides say those states, along with
Tennessee, North Carolina and Louisiana, are considered more
competitive, as is Missouri.
   Turning West, Dukakis strategists concede they have little hope
for carrying traditionally Republican Alaska, Utah, Idaho, Nevada,
Wyoming, and Arizona, as well as Kansas and Nebraska in the farm
belt, GOP vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle's home state of
Indiana and New Hampshire.
   The Dukakis aides say they will not outright concede any state
but, with six weeks to go before the election, must make decisions
on where best to allocate staff and money. If internal tracking
shows a significant shift among voters in any of the states now
being de-emphasized, the plan could again be revised, the aides
said.
   ``We track this stuff very carefully and will be ready to
respond if we see a new opportunity somewhere,'' said one aide
involved in targeting decisions. ``By keeping it competitive, if we
can, we keep the Republicans spending time and resources. You see
where we are by looking at the schedule but that doesn't mean we
don't keep targets of opportunity open.''
   If paid staffers are relocated, the campaign will rely on
volunteers to maintain a presence in all 50 states, that aide said.
   The current plan is to target two of the largest electoral
prizes, California and Texas, and the traditionally Democratic
states in the Northeast and industrial Midwest. The race in many of
those states is very tight, another factor in decisions to
reallocate resources, the aides said.
   New York, which ranks second only to California in electoral
votes, New Jersey, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut,
Maryland, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Illinois and Michigan carry a total
of 179 votes, and Dukakis hopes to win most of them and offset any
losses with victories in the border states.
   Despite the decision to de-emphasize some states, Dukakis aides
are convinced they can break the GOP electoral lock by reclaiming
the Northeast and industrial Midwest and picking up the rest of the
needed votes from other states that supported President Reagan in
the last two elections.
   ``Whether it's in the border states or the far West, it's clear
that it's very different this time,'' said one aide. ``The
opportunity is clearly there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
