<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Gunfire-Advisers 1stLd-Writethru a0463 09-27 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gunfire-Advisers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0463,490</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says He Would Never Deny US Advisers in El Salvador Right
to Defend Selves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, asked about a firefight
involving guerrillas and U.S. military advisers in El Salvador,
said today he would never deny the advisers ``the right to defend
themselves.''
   In the incident two weeks ago, the U.S. advisers to the
Salvadoran army found themselves in the middle of a rebel attack on
an army headquarters, the Pentagon said.
   Maj. Kathy Wood, a Pentagon spokeswoman, said that the advisers
``fired in self defense'' and that none was injured.
   ``They were caught in the middle of a fire fight and their own
lives were in jeopardy, so they fired in self defense,'' she said.
   Reagan, asked about the incident during a picture-taking session
with NATO leaders in New York, replied, ``I'll never send any of
our people into danger without allowing them the right to defend
themselves if they are attacked.''
   The Washington Post and the Miami Herald in editions today
quoted a Defense Department memorandum as saying 16 Salvadoran
soldiers and five guerrillas were killed in the assault at the
Salvadoran Army's 4th Brigade headquarters in north central El
Salvador.
   Here is how the memorandum described the action, according to
the published reports:
   ``During the attack, the U.S. personnel positioned themselves in
a sandbagged and reinforced bunker position adjacent to the trainer
quarters. From this position, the U.S. personnel could observe
guerrillas moving about surrounding high ground and firing their
weapons at, or in the general direction of, the U.S. personnel.
   ``Perceiving a direct threat to their safety, the U.S. personnel
engaged the guerrillas with their assigned personal weapons.''
   It was not known specifically whether the three U.S. soldiers
killed anyone. They reportedly returned fire with M-16 rifles.
   ``There are no indications of guerrilla casualties as a result
of the U.S. defensive fire,'' the Post quoted Lt. Gen. Charles W.
Brown, director of the Defense Security Assistance Agency, as
writing in the memo.
   The encounter occurred Sept. 13, but word of it surfaced Monday
because the Defense Department referred to it in a report it is
required to send to Congress whenever a hostile action in El
Salvador involves an American, the spokeswoman said Monday.
   She said she had not seen the memo referred to in the published
reports.
   The same Salvadoran army headquarters was the site of a fierce
gun and mortar battle in late March 1987, resulting in the death of
a U.S. Army sergeant.
   Army Sgt. Gregory Fronius, 27, an intelligence specialist who
was advising the Salvadoran army, is the only soldier reported
killed while on duty in the midst of combat during the eight years
of civil war in the country. U.S. military advisers arrived in the
country in 1981.
   Fronius was one of two advisers assigned to the camp at the time
of the 1987 attack. The other U.S. soldier was away.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
