<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NIreland-Arsenal     09-27 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-Arsenal,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Forces Find Huge Arsenal Of Terrorist Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces found a large
arsenal of weapons, including a Soviet-made rocket launcher, hidden
in underground bunkers, police said today.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary said ``a number of people'' were
arrested for questioning about the caches, discovered on Monday and
today around Strabane, County Tyrone, near Northern Ireland's
northwest border with the Irish Republic.
   ``Security forces have found a huge arsenal of terrorist
weapons,'' a police statement said.
   The haul included a Soviet RPG-7 rocket launcher and two
warheads, more than 1,000 pounds of homemade explosives, two
Soviet-made AKM assault rifles, one shotgun, a large quantity of
ammunition and detonators, explosive fuses and propellant charges,
police said.
   The arms were concealed in 40-gallon drums that had been welded
together and buried in elaborately constructed bunkers under a
hillside, police said.
   ``It is obvious that people within our community were fully
aware of the presence of these caches,'' said a police spokesman,
who requested anonymity. ``Where human life is being taken so
frequently it is long past time that those who are aware of such
activity should act more responsibly.''
   The spokesman urged citizens to report any information about
terrorist activities or arms so that ``lives can be saved.''
   Last week, Sir John Hermon, head of the Royal Ulster
Constabulary, said the outlawed Irish Republican Army ``has very
considerable quantities of very powerful weaponry which they have
not yet used,'' including surface-to-air missiles.
   Libya is believed to have supplied the weapons to the IRA for
its fight to oust the British from Protestant-dominated Northern
Ireland and unite the province with the mainly Roman Catholic Irish
Republic.
   This year a series of IRA attacks in Northern Ireland, mainland
Britain and continental Europe have killed 27 British soldiers and
11 guerrillas. Since November, 20 civilians have died in bungled
IRA operations.
</TEXT>
