<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     09-27 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Methodist Minister In Soweto Detained By Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police detained a Methodist
minister today in an early morning raid, claiming he violated a ban
on calls for an election boycott, his wife and church colleagues
said.
   The Rev. Tom Mbanane of Soweto was taken into custody as the
Methodist and Roman Catholic churches released the text of pastoral
letters urging their followers to consider refusing to vote in the
Oct. 26 nationwide municipal elections.
   Agnes Mbabane said her 55-year-old husband was taken from his
home in the black township at 12:45 a.m. by officers who alleged he
had preached against participation in the October elections.
   Mrs. Mbabane said her husband had not advocated an election
boycott but had conveyed the Methodist Church's appeal to its
congregations to consider carefully whether they should vote.
   Mbabane is a regional vice chairman of the Methodist Church. The
chairman of his district, the Rev. Peter Storey, said in a
statement: ``The authorites must have taken leave of their senses
to remove someone of Mr. Mbabane's stature and integrity from
Soweto at this tense time.''
   The pastoral letter from Methodist leaders said abstention from
voting would be the only way for some voters to convey their
rejection of apartheid.
   ``Only candidates who are openly and sincerely committed to the
complete abolition of apartheid are worthy of Christian support,''
the letter said.
   A similar letter issued by the Southern African Catholic Bishops
Conference said the elections could further entrench apartheid.
   The elections will mark the first time South Africans of all
races go to the polls the same day. Most anti-apartheid activists
oppose participation in segregated local elections as long as the
black majority is excluded from full participation in national
elections.
   Numerous activist clergymen, including Anglican Archbishop
Desmond Tutu, have defied a state-of-emergency regulation
forbidding calls for an election boycott.
   State-of-emergency regulations in effect since 1986 restrict
reporting about unrest, security force actions, treatment of
detainees, some forms of protest, and a range of statements the
government considers subversive. Enforcement of the regulations has
not been comprehensive.
   Apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the
26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million
whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools
and health services.
</TEXT>
