<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0433,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Boasts He's Pasted Liberal Tag on Dukakis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede CINCINNATI</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Bush speech at Miami University; picks
up pvs 4th graf bgng, ``My values;'' deletes pvs grafs 10-11 bgng,
The vice, to eliminate redundant material.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush boasted today that
he's successfully pasted a liberal label on Democratic rival
Michael Dukakis and declared that ``I'm going to keep on using it''
in their tight campaign race for the White House.
   Bush also told several thousand students at a Young College
Republicans rally on the University of Miami campus that Dukakis is
inexperienced in foreign affairs.
   ``America doesn't need a president who has to enroll in Foreign
Policy 101 to understand the kind of world we live in,'' the vice
president said.
   Bush asked, ``How did I do?'' in his nationally televised debate
with Dukakis on Sunday, and the reply was a roar of approval from
the crowd.
   About three dozen protesters waving pro-Dukakis signs and
chanting ``Where Was George?'' were kept several hundred feet away
and out of earshot from the platform where the GOP nominee spoke.
   Bush said he was successful in portraying Dukakis during the
debate as a liberal who stands far to the left of most Americans.
``We smoked him out,'' he said.
   ``For most of the campaign the man I call the stealth candidate
has tried to hide where he stands,'' Bush said.
   The vice president said Dukakis didn't like it when Bush used
``the big L word,'' referring to the word liberal. ``I'm going to
keep on using it,'' Bush said.
   ``He's just itching to spend money and he wants to set the clock
back to those days of misery and malaise, and I'm not going to let
him do it,'' Bush said.
   Expanding on that theme, the vice president criticized the
Massachusetts governor Monday for his membership in the American
Civil Liberties Union during campaign stops in the South.
   Aides said Bush would drive the point home today on a tour that
also took him to a Republican convention in Columbus, Ohio, and a
rally at Owensboro. Ky. Bush planned Wednesday to take an
eight-hour bus trip through Illinois.
   ``My values are your values and they are not the values of the
ACLU,'' Bush told a rally and barbecue on Monday at a farm in
Hampton, Ga., near Atlanta.
   He spoke as Dukakis, at a campaign appearance in Jersey City,
said he did not agree with all positions taken by the civil
liberties' organization ``and he (Bush) knows it.''
   Dukakis stressed his support for tough laws against child
pornography, his support for tax exemptions for churches and other
charitable organizations, and his opposition to the ACLU's support
of former White House aide Oliver North, a key figure in the
Iran-Contra scandal.
   Bush aides voiced delight with what they viewed as Dukakis'
squirming on the issue. ``My advice to him is, make my day, come
south,'' said Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater, predicting the
ACLU issue would loom even larger in the days to come in the South
and other conservative rural areas.
   Meanwhile, Bush says he thinks his Sunday night showdown with
the Democratic presidential nominee was probably a draw _
contradicting an array of senior aides who crowned him the clear
victor.
   ``I kind of thought it was even,'' Bush told reporters.
   However, he also said he thought the debate ``turned out pretty
well.''
   At a joint appearance in Jackson, Tenn., with GOP vice
presidential candiate Dan Quayle, Bush voiced strong praise for his
running mate and urged supporters to ``stay tuned'' for next week's
vice presidential debate in which he predicted Quayle would do well.
   Quayle declared Bush the winner of the debate, which he called
``the nice man versus the ice man'' and said Dukakis would have
been ``better off to take advice from his friends at the ACLU and
exercised his right to remain silent.''
   Over and over, Bush and his lieutenants drove home the ACLU
issue.
   In particular, Bush in his Georgia speech accused the
organization of opposing penalties for distributing child
pornography and of advocating the legalization of drugs ``including
crack and heroin.''
   ``I don't think that is the American way,'' Bush said. ``It is
not my way. It is the way of the ACLU.''
   In the same speech, Bush said that, ``To wrap up that Democratic
nomination, he (Dukakis) had to stay where he's been in his entire
political life _ and that is on the left side of things. And now
he's trying to move back and pre-empt the mainstream in the
middle.''
   ``I will not let him do that. I'm going to make him be what he
is, not what he wants to be,'' Bush added.
</TEXT>
