<HEAD>Opposition Alliance Names Leaders</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf ``In another development...'' with one graf to
add that unofficial reports said as many as 400 people were killed.
SUBS 8th graf pvs ``The three figures...'' with one graf to remove
outdated material.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aung Gyi, a retired army officer who broke
with strongman Ne Win and became the country's leading dissident,
today was named chairman of a newly formed opposition alliance.
   The alliance urged workers to continue a general strike until
they achieved their goal of democracy. The strike began Sept. 18
when Gen. Saw Maung seized power in a military coup.
   In another development, the government said today that 348
people had been killed in Burma since the coup. Western diplomats
in Rangoon estimated earlier that as many as 400 people were killed
by the government in the days following the coup.
   Government spokesman Kyaw Sann told a press briefing that 219
others had been wounded and 1,107 arrested by authorities.
   Widespread rioting broke out when Saw Maung seized power, and
the general immediately ordered troops into the streets to quell
the protests.
   The government spokesman also said rebels of the Burma Communist
Party have launched major attacks against army outposts in
northeastern Burma, killing 44 government soldiers and wounding 92.
The fighting, said to be continuing in some areas, involved both
government air strikes and fierce infantry clashes with bayonets.
   The spokesman for the opposition alliance said another former
military officer, Tin Oo, was named vice chairman of the League for
Democracy while Aung San Suu Kyi, daughter of a revered Burmese
independence hero, was chosen general secretary.
   The three figures formed the league Saturday and immediately
called on all citizens to join in a peaceful struggle against the
new military regime.
   The alliance marks the first formal opposition attempt to unify
under one leadership the millions of students, Buddhist monks,
workers and professionals who have taken to the streets over the
past two months to demand an end to 26 years of repressive
one-party rule.
   The new opposition league demands than an interim government be
created to lead Burma out of chaos.
   ``We still believe that an interim government is the only way to
solve the present crisis in the country ... to revive stalled
government, to reactivate the broken-down economy and to hold
genuine, free and fair general elections,'' Aung Gyi said today.
   The alliance also named nine members of a 12-member executive
committee. The three remaining positions are to be filled later by
representatives of Burma's numerous ethnic minorities, who are also
fighting the government.
   The alliance later will elect a 37-member governing body, which
will include one representative from each of the seven states where
ethnic minorities predominate _ Arakan, Chin, Kachin, Shan, Kayah,
Karen and Mon.
   The 70-year-old Aung Gyi earlier this year circulated a series
of letters to former leader Ne Win, criticizing the government's
economic performance and its brutal suppression of student
demonstrations last March.
   Aung Gyi, who broke with Ne Win in 1963 over economic policy,
was jailed for several years in the 1960s and again briefly this
summer when hardliner Sein Lwin assumed power after Ne Win resigned.
   Tin Oo, 61, was removed by Ne Win as defense and army chief in
1976 and was later jailed in connection with an alleged
anti-government plot.
   Aung San Suu Kyi, 42, is the daughter of the late Aung San, the
much revered hero of Burmese independence from Great Britain. She
had been living in Britain but returned to Rangoon for a visit
earlier this year and stayed to campaign for democracy.
   Analysts say the three, who had trouble cooperating in the past,
were pressed to unite by the bloody crackdown on dissent following
Saw Maung's coup.
   Since the coup, demonstrations have ceased in Rangoon and some
students have fled to the rugged frontier with Thailand to seek
refuge with ethnic minority insurgents.
   On Monday, top officials appealed to parents and teachers to
stop the students from linking up with the rebels.
</TEXT>
