<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Indians-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0554 09-27 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indians-Hostages, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0554,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules That Hatcher Is His Own Attorney</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th-7th to UPDATE with today's jury selection. Picks up
8th graf pvs, `The hostages...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ruled that an American
Indian accused of hostage-taking must act as his own attorney, a
decision the man's lawyer called a ``disgrace.''
   Eddie Hatcher's trial opened Monday but his lawyer, William
Kunstler, was in New York at a trial expected to last until
mid-October.
   ``The court is ready to proceed and will proceed with this
trial,'' U.S. District Court Judge Terrence Boyle said after
Hatcher declined to be represented in court by two attorneys other
than Kunstler.
   ``Mr. Hatcher has chosen to defend himself,'' Boyle announced.
   ``No, your honor, I have had that decision forced on me against
my constitutional rights,'' Hatcher replied.
   Jury selection in the trial continued today. By midmorning,
Boyle had questioned 43 jurors and excused 15, including two who
said they were ``unalterably in favor'' of Hatcher and the trial's
other defendant, Timothy Jacobs. Both potential jurors said they
had some American Indian ancestry.
   Hatcher, 31, and Jacobs, 20, are charged with taking up to 20
hostages and possessing illegal firearms in a 10-hour siege at The
Robesonian newspaper office Feb. 1 in Lumberton.
   The hostages were released unharmed when Gov. Jim Martin agreed
to appoint a state task force to investigate the defendants'
allegations of drug trafficking and racial discrimination among
county law enforcement officials. No evidence of drug trafficking
has been found.
   The trial opened with Jacobs at one table with his three lawyers
and their two staff members, while Hatcher sat alone at another
table.
   Before jury selection could start, a Chapel Hill law professor
who is counseling Hatcher, Barry Nakell, argued that the trial
should be delayed until Kunstler, a prominent attorney known for
his defense of leftist causes, could be in the courtroom.
   Boyle denied the request. Then the federal judge ruled that an
associate of Kunstler's who was present, Stephanie Moore, would be
Hatcher's trial attorney, despite Ms. Moore's argument that she was
representing Hatcher only before the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
   Ms. Moore refused to participate in the trial and walked out of
the courtroom just before the lunch recess. In court after the
break, Boyle asked Hatcher if he would accept either Ms. Moore or
Nakell as his trial attorney.
   ``Mr. Hatcher, do you want to fire Mr. Nakell or keep him?''
Boyle asked. Hatcher replied, ``Bill Kunstler is my attorney, and I
feel like I'm being forced to make this decision, and my
constitutional rights are being violated.''
   Kunstler criticized the federal judge, saying it was ``a
disgrace'' for a federal judge to deny a defendant the counsel of
his choice and calling the decision ``a wicked and misleading
charade.''
</TEXT>
