<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Soviets 1stLd-Writethru a0470 09-27 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Soviets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,0733</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE AT NOON EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister Calls for World Space Organization</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS 16 grafs to update with Shevardnadze speech, quotes.
Picks up graf 11 pvs, `On Monday ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union today called on the
United States to join Moscow in creating a World Space
Organization, which would use a disputed Siberian radar base as its
eye on the heavens.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev suggested earlier this month
that the Soviet radar base at Krasnoyarsk, Siberia, be turned over
to an international agency for the peaceful exploration of space.
   The United States says the radar base violates the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty and must be demolished.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said in his
speech today to the General Assembly that the United States should
join the Soviets in the space agency and donate U.S. radar units in
Greenland and Britain.
   Shevardnadze said the latest Soviet diplomatic initiative was
sincere, and that he wanted to make the United Nations a ``unique
global center for ensuring universal and regional security, and the
security of each country.''
   The Western allies, which regard the Soviet proposal as a new
organizational plan that would replace the U.N. Charter, are
reluctant to tinker with the existing structure of the world body.
   Last year, the Soviets were unable to win a majority of votes in
the General Assembly when they introduced the plan as a resolution.
   Shevardnadze also said the U.S.-Soviet treaty to scrap all
intermediate-range nuclear missiles should be supplemented by an
agreement limiting the spread of military missile technology that
``could be worked out only under the auspices of the United
Nations.''
   On conventional arms, the Soviet diplomat suggested the United
Nations register all conventional arms sales and transfers.
   Shevardnadze called for an expanded role for the Security
Council, suggesting periodic meetings of its foreign ministers and
that it meet in areas of regional tensions.
   In the last 18 months, increased U.S.-Soviet cooperation has
allowed the Security Council to act unanimously on major issues
including the Persian Gulf peace plan in Resolution 598, and in
denouncing the use of chemical weapons in the gulf war.
   Turning to Afghanistan, Shevardnadze said ``the Geneva accords
are not just an isolated local instance of a regional conflict
settlement. ... They are a new promising beginning in world
politics, attesting to a qualitative change in poltiical thinking.''
   Under those U.N.-mediated accords, Soviet troops are to be out
of Afghanistan by Feb. 15 in a withdrawal that began May 15.
   Shevardnaze also called on the United States and other nations
to join the Soviets in abolishing some planned or ongoing military
programs and channel the funds toward setting up an international
system of environmental security.
   Shevardnadze also acknowledged President Reagan's speech Monday
in which the president noted U.S.-Soviet cooperation had
contributed to breakthroughs in regional security.
   ``Here I can only agree with President Reagan's remrks yesterday
about the beneficial impact of Soviet-American political dialogue
on that process,'' he said.
   On Monday, Reagan delivered a mostly conciliatory, upbeat
farewell speech before the world body he had in the past chastised
for its alleged anti-Western attitudes.
   The president condemned the use of outlawed chemical weapons in
the Persian Gulf war and called for a new global ban on such
warfare.
   He indirectly criticized Iraq's use of poison gas against its
Kurdish minority and against Iranians. Kurdish rebels have long
been fighting for a separate homeland in northern Iraq and sided
with Iran during the war.
   Reagan called on all nations to convene a conference that would
consider ways to enforce the 1925 protocol barring chemical weapons
in international conflicts. He also urged nations to cooperate in
negotiating a verifiable global ban on chemical weapons at the
Conference on Disarmament in Geneva.
   Reagan praised the United Nations for negotiating a cease-fire
in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war and for opening talks to formalize
a peace treaty.
   He said U.S. and Soviet negotiators were making steady progress
on an accord to halve the superpowers' long-range, or strategic,
nuclear arsenals.
   While completion of the pact this year was ``highly doubtful,''
Reagan said, ``I can tell you a year from now is a possibility,
more than a possibility.''
</TEXT>
