<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolReform     09-27 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Reform,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thompson Seeks More Control Over Chicago School Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. James R. Thompson is asking the legislature
for changes in Chicago school reform legislation that would, among
other things, give him more power over a board that is to oversee
the reform process.
   The governor says his proposed changes in the legislation would
further the bill's goal of shifting power to the local school level.
   Thompson signed the legislation Monday in an amendatory veto, a
procedure under Illinois law in which a bill is sent back to the
legislature for consideration of the governor's written changes or
amendments.
   ``The legislation radically reforms the administrative structure
in Chicago in terms of budgeting and planning,'' Thompson said in a
statement. ``I believe that the changes suggested today will make
this bill stronger and that a majority of people throughout the
city and state agree with me.''
   Some legislative supporters of the bill said they could accept
Thompson's suggestions.
   But Chicago Teachers Union President Jacqueline Vaughn raised
objections to changes that would affect some teachers' seniority
rights, and some black lawmakers took issue with the proposed
expansion of the governor's power.
   Perhaps the most significant change sought by Thompson would
increase his authority over the seven-member Chicago School Reform
Oversight Authority, a body created to ensure that the reform
measures are put into place.
   The original bill called for four authority members to be
appointed by the mayor of Chicago and three by the governor.
Thompson's version would give the governor and the mayor three
appointments each, with the seventh member to be chosen jointly.
   Among Thompson's other proposals for change:
   _Allow the oversight authority to withhold funds if school
officials don't implement reforms properly.
   _Give principals more authority over ``remediation programs''
for teachers whose work is judged to be substandard.
   _Require local school councils to return to the Board of
Education any unspent funds at the end of a budget year, rather
than carrying the money over into the next budget year.
   _Remove a requirement that teachers with seniority whose
positions are eliminated get first preference for vacancies in
other vacant teaching posts.
   When lawmakers convene for their veto session in November, they
may accept Thompson's changes by a majority vote or override him by
a three-fifths vote and enact the bill as originally drafted. If
they fail to do either, the bill is dead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
