<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ReedTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0549 09-27 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reed Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0549,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NAACP's Alabama State President's Extortion Trial Under Way</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with today's prosecution
testimony. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `In opening...' ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecution witnesses testified today that
Alabama's NAACP president said it would cost about $10,000 for his
efforts in helping secure early release of a convicted killer.
   A federal court jury of 10 whites and six blacks, including
alternate jurors, began hearing testimony today in the extortion
trial of Thomas Reed, a Democratic state representative and head of
the Alabama branch of the National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People.
   Woodson Chesser of Columbus, Ga., the inmate's father, testified
that he took out two loans totaling $4,600 and combined it with
cash to pay Reed $10,000. He said he did so after meeting with Reed
about the imprisoned Anthony Chesser, who is serving a 40-year
sentence for murder in Alabama.
   ``I explained my son's situation and asked if he could help me.
He said he'd helped a lot of them and we'll see,'' Woodson Chesser
said.
   Robert Muncy, a partner in the Columbus business where Woodson
Chesser worked, testified that Reed told him he believed he would
be able to help the inmate.
   ``He mentioned that in order to get some help, it would probably
cost some money. The figure I remember is $10,000,'' said Muncy.
   Reed, the senior black member of the Alabama House, is charged
with accepting $10,000 in cash and between $5,000 and $10,000 in
restaurant equipment from the Chesser family. Reed operates two
restaurants in Macon County.
   U.S. District Judge Joel Dubina ruled Monday he would allow into
evidence a tape of a conversation between Reed and Bobby Gene
Chesser, a Columbus, Ga., restaurant equipment salesman.
   In opening arguments Monday, defense attorney Bill Baxley
described Bobby Gene Chesser, Anthony Chesser's uncle, as a ``crook
to beat all crooks and a con man to beat all con men.''
   Bobby Gene Chesser, who was convicted in 1980 to a 10-year
sentence on a felony theft charge, testified Monday he recorded the
conversation with Reed on Aug. 28, 1986, when Reed came to his
business. FBI Special Agent Bruce Koenig of Bloomington, Va.,
testified that the 27-minute tape was authentic.
   The tape was not played in court Monday.
   Chesser wanted back the money allegedly given Reed after the
state Board of Pardons and Paroles revoked an order to move up his
nephew's consideration for parole, prosecutors have said.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Broward Segrest told the jury that the
five-count indictment of Reed described the payments Chesser made
to Reed for his ``political influence'' in obtaining the early
prison release of Anthony Chesser.
   Reed's attorneys challenged allowing the tape recording into
evidence because they said it first went to a state parole board
member before it reached the FBI. Bobby Gene Chesser told the judge
he gave the tape directly to the FBI.
   The trial is expected to last three days.
   ``If the truth prevails, I'll be a free man when I leave here,''
Reed, 60, told reporters when he arrived at the U.S. District Court
in Mobile on Monday.
   The trial was moved to Mobile from Montgomery because of
publicity surrounding Reed's indictment. He also is scheduled to go
to trial Nov. 7 in Montgomery on related state bribery charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
