<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BabySwap     09-27 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Swap,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer: Florida Girl Isn't Pennsylvania Couple's Long-Lost Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who claim their newborn was swapped
for a baby with a heart defect are looking in the wrong place with
a lawsuit claiming a Florida girl is theirs, a lawyer said.
   Ernest and Regina Twigg claim in a $100 million federal lawsuit
filed here that their healthy newborn was swapped at Hardee
Memorial Hospital.
   Florida birth records show only one other white girl was born at
the hospital about the time Mrs. Twigg gave birth in 1978. Based on
public records, the Twiggs believe the Florida girl, who has not
been publicly identified, could be their child.
   The girl the Twiggs, now of Langhorne, Pa., took from the
hospital was named Arlena, and she died Aug. 23 of complications
after heart surgery at the Deborah Heart and Lung Center in Browns
Mills, N.J. The suit says that while Arlena was being prepared for
a blood transfusion last May, a doctor at Johns Hopkins in
Baltimore determined that neither of the Twiggs could be her parent.
   But Dale Swope, a lawyer for the Florida child's father, said he
believes the Twiggs are wrong.
   The girl's father ``sees her mother's look in her face,'' Swope
said. The girl's mother died of cancer in 1981.
   Swope said Monday he will probably advise his client to provide
a sample of the girl's blood for genetic testing as a ``courtesy''
to the Twiggs.
   The blood test, a procedure called HLA testing that compares
proteins on white blood cells, is frequently used in paternity
disputes and can prove that adults are not the biological parents
of a child. It also can offer an extremely high probability that
adults are the biological parents of a child.
   Marvin Ellin, who represents the Twiggs, has said that if the
Florida girl's father refuses requests for testing, he will seek a
court order. The Twiggs say they aren't sure if they'll seek
custody if the girl proves to be their daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
