<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Greece-Taxis     09-27 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Greece-Taxis,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Athens' 17,000 Cabbies Go On Three-Day Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The capital's 17,000 taxi drivers began a
three-day strike Tuesday to protest anti-pollution measures that
restrict cab circulation in the city center.
   Taxis are included in traffic restrictions banning half the
city's 800,000 cars from a five-square-mile zone around the center
between 7 a.m. and 8 p.m. on weekdays, according to odd and even
license plate numbers.
   It was the first strike by taxi drivers since the resrictions
were reimposed Sept. 1 after a two-month summer break.
   ``The anti-pollution measures create tremendous problems for us
as we make half our money in the city center. This walkout is just
the beginning of more strike action,'' said Kostas Lainis,
president of the taxi drivers' union.
   Taxis were first banned from the center in January when
anti-pollution measures were stepped up in an effort to reduce a
brown smog cloud that hangs over Athens on warm, still days. Cars,
diesel-powered taxis and the city's ageing buses are blamed for
spewing most pollutants into the atmosphere.
</TEXT>
