<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Laos-USMIAs     09-27 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Laos-US MIAs,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Team Leaves For Crash Site In Laos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. military team flew to Laos on
Tuesday to search plane crash sites from the Indochina war for
clues about missing American soldiers, an official said.
   In Vietnam, another U.S. team was working with local officials
on the second day of an unprecedented investigation to determine
the fates of seven American airmen lost in plane crashes near the
capital of Hanoi.
   Maj. Thomas J. Boyd, spokesman for the U.S. Pacific Command,
said the team that left Bangkok for eastern Laos will examine an
area around Sepone to prepare for possible later excavations of the
crash sites.
   The team is from the U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution Center and
Army Central Identification Laboratory, Honolulu-based units
seeking to account for 2,393 Americans missing in action from the
war in Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia that ended in 1975 with communist
victories in all three countries.
   ``They will look at crash sites and determine what kind of
aircraft, how it crashed, and determine the potential for possible
future site excavations,'' Boyd told reporters. He said a Marine
with special expertise in plane crashes was on the team.
   Losses in that area near the Vietnamese border include airmen
downed in missions to cut off the Ho Chi Minh Trail, used by
communist North Vietnam to infiltrate troops to U.S.-backed South
Vietnam.
   The United States and Laos have conducted three previous joint
crash site excavations, most recently in May.
   The American team in Vietnam, which brought its own
interpreters, are interviewing villagers who witnessed the
incidents in which the men were lost and are seeking evidence such
as local government reports and human remains.
   Boyd said the seven are among 70 cases in which the United
States says there is strong evidence the men survived and were
taken under Vietnamese control. The United States says it cannot
prove any Americans are alive in Indochina but cannot ignore that
possibility.
   The Defense Intelligence Agency is investigating 119 reports of
purported sightings of Americans, Boyd said.
   The Americans drove to the Vietnamese villages Monday in jeeps
flown in from Honolulu the day before. The search is planned for
about 10 days.
   Boyd said the two sides may later excavate plane crash sites
found during the investigation.
   Previously, the only significant joint field activity was in
late 1985, when U.S. soldiers and Vietnamese state workers dug up
the wreckage of a U.S. B-52 bomber just outside Hanoi. They found
remains but none identified as missing Americans.
   Lt. Col. Joe Harvey, leader of the U.S. team in Vietnam, earlier
expressed hope of several joint investigation operations in the
coming months. ``We are prepared to provide four teams, if Vietnam
agrees,'' he said.
   Of the missing, 1,757 are in Vietnam, 547 in Laos, 83 in
Cambodia and six in China. U.S. forces withdrew from Indochina in
1973, after the conflict cost 58,000 American lives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
