<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LegalAidPacts     09-27 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Legal Aid Pacts,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Legal Cooperation Agreements With Six
Nations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treaties with six countries calling for
cooperation in narcotics prosecutions and other criminal matters
were approved by the Senate Foreign Relations Committee on Tuesday
after Sen. Jesse Helms tried and failed to shelve agreements with
Mexico and the Bahamas.
   The committee voted 17-2 to recommend the full Senate approve
the legal cooperation treaties with those two nations.
   Helms, R-N.C., protested that they should not be ratified until
the president can certify that no Mexican or Bahamian officials are
involved with narcotics trafficking.
   Cooperation treaties with Canada, Belgium, Thailand and the
Cayman Islands were approved on a voice vote and sent to the Senate
floor for action.
   Helms contended that the governments of the Bahamas and Mexico
include senior officials who have assisted the drug trade. He said
ratification of the treaties would send a signal that the United
States is not serious in waging war against narcotics.
   ``You don't fight drugs by being partners with the drug
traffickers,'' he said.
   But Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said the treaties, negotiated by
the Justice Department, will provide both a potentially important
law enforcement tool and a gauge by which to judge whether the
Bahamas and Mexico are living up to their commitments.
   ``If we have this treaty in place we will have a Justice
Department to Justice Department relationship that will be almost
strictly law enforcement oriented,'' Kerry said. ``There will be an
opportunity for creative requests that will let us see if there is
cooperation.''
   The Mutual Legal Assistance treaties are designed to provide a
framework by which the United States can request the cooperation of
the countries involved to obtain evidence to use in criminal
prosecutions in the United States.
   Each of the six countries could make similar requests of the
United States.
</TEXT>
