<2ND_LINE>PM-Williams Parole, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0568,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Teamsters Leader Released From Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd-6th grafs, bgng `Officials at...', with 5 grafs to
UPDATE with comment from lawyer. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `This
release...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Teamsters President Roy Williams
was released from prison early today after serving less than 34
months of a 10-year sentence given him for conspiring to bribe a
U.S. senator.
   Government officials said they would expect Williams to continue
his involvement with the government's war on organized crime as a
condition of his release.
   Officials at the U.S. Medical Center for Federal Prisoners said
Williams, 73, was released at 1 a.m., through prisoners ordinarily
are released later in the day. ``He didn't want to be exposed to
press coverage and cameras,'' said his lawyer, Bruce Houdek.
   Williams, 73, suffers from acute emphysema and an enlarged
heart. Houdek said he is ``disabled from any work'' and needs an
artificial supply of oxygen 24 hours a day.
   The U.S. Parole Commission announced Friday that Williams, who
has been treated for emphysema and an enlarged heart while serving
his term at the Springfield medical center, would be paroled in
recognition of testimony against organized crime figures that ``was
at great risk to his personal safety.''
   Houdek said Williams traveled from Springfield to his farm home
in Leeton in west-central Missouri.
   ``He's basically trying to be at home and relax and wake up
without bars on the windows and people telling him what to do,''
Houdek said. ``Basically, he's trying to acclimate himself to
normal life.''
   ``This release is contigent upon his continued cooperation with
law enforcement authorities,'' parole commission chairman Benjamin
Baer said in a statement Friday. Baer added that Williams could be
returned to prison if he did not cooperate.
   Russell Millin, a Kansas City attorney who represents Williams,
has said his client ``will tell the truth if he's asked, as he has
done in the past.''
   Williams was convicted in 1982 of conspiring to bribe a U.S.
senator for his help in defeating legislation to deregulate
trucking.
   In an 1985 effort to get his prison sentence reduced, Williams
testified for federal prosecutors that reputed Kansas City crime
boss Nick Civella paid him $1,500 a month from late 1974 to
mid-1981. Williams said he had agreed to help Civella's
organization secure a multimillion-dollar loan from the Teamsters
Central States Pension Fund.
   The parole commission's announcement Friday came the day a
federal judge had threatened to release Williams if his parole was
not re-evaluated.
   U.S. District Judge William Collinson had ruled that the parole
commission was unconstitutionally trying to block Williams' release
because of the statements he made about his own links to organized
crime, statements that were made after Williams was granted
immunity from prosecution.
   Williams began serving the sentence Dec. 3, 1985.
</TEXT>
