<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan-Interior     09-27 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Interior,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Appropriation Bill Despite Objections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today signed a $10.5 billion
appropriation bill for the Interior Department and related
agencies, but warned that it represents ``congressional
overspending'' and runs the risk of across-the-board budget cuts
under the deficit-reduction act.
   The measure appropriates $680 million more than the president
requested. He said it bings the nation $198 million closer to
triggering cuts under the Gramm-Rudman law.
   The measure was the fifth appropriation bill that Reagan has
received and signed of the 13 bills Congress annually considers.
   ``I urge the Congress to act swiftly to send me the remainder of
the fiscal year 1989 appropriations bills _ on time and on
budget,'' Reagan said.
   Although he said that ``on balance the act merited my
approval,'' the president complained that it once again extended
the moratorium on granting oil and gas leases for certain areas of
the outer continental shelf.
   ``The Congress increased the damaging effect of the moratorium
by extending it to apply to grants of permits for drilling and
exploration activities under leases already granted,'' he said.
``For the Congress to prohibit the issuance of such permits to
those who already had obtained leases is unfair.''
   Reagan also said that portions of the bill, requiring approval
of congressional committees for such things as changes in Forest
Service regional boundaries, are unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
