<1ST_LINE>r p CampaignAbroad-Debate     09-27 0773</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Campaign Abroad-Debate,0823</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Newspapers Comment on Bush-Dukakis Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers overseas are still commenting on Sunday's the first
debate of the U.S. presidential campaign between Republican George
Bush and Democrat Michael Dukakis. Here is some of what they said:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DENMARK</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Politiken (liberal) of Copenhagen: ``The debate was mostly to
Dukakis' advantage because he is the least known of the candidates
and the one who trailed in the polls since the Republican
convention. Even though Bush still leads, the election is still
wide open.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NETHERLANDS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _De Telegraaf (conservative) of Amsterdam: ``Vice President
George Bush has emerged as the big winner of the first and most
important television debate for the American presidential
elections. ...
   ``Bush, who as vice president had most to lose, overshadowed ..
. Dukakis especially in the fields of foreign affairs and security.
Although he did not deliver a knock-out blow, Bush managed to push
aside his opponent frequently.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SWEDEN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Dagens Nyheter (liberal) of Stockholm: ``To change the election
wind, Dukakis should have made something of an Olympic gold medal
performance in his first long-awaited TV battle against Reagan's
crown prince. This he did not do.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Svenska Dagbladet (center-right):
   ``Dukakis got his best opportunity so far to remind the
Americans of his opponent's not so honorable role in the Irangate
scandal. But do voters ever let themselves be influenced by
scandals involving those who hold power?''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Aftenposten (conservative) of Oslo: ``The debate hardly gave
any firm clue about the final outcome when the voters go to the
poll in six weeks.
   ``As in most elections in democratic countries these days, it
will be the big `undecided' group which in the end decides whether
Bush or Dukakis will move into The White House.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Verdens Gang (independent) of Oslo: `` ... a draw. Among those
already decided, it is not likely that many voters went from Bush
to Dukakis or the other.
   ``Today that is a bigger problem for Dukakis than for Bush,
because the democratic candidate was trailing in the opinion polls
before the debate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Arbeiderbladet (social democratic) of Oslo: ``This debate will
hardly decide the election outcome. Bush made no major mistakes.
Dukakis demonstrated debate skill, but without giving the
appearance of a great potential president.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRAZIL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Rosental Calmon Alves, writing from Washington in the Jornal do
Brasil (independent) of Rio de Janeiro: ``Both George Bush and
Michael Dukakis tried to appear tranquil and answered cautiously. .
.. The lack of discussion of concrete themes in fact has been one
of the most important characteristics of the current U.S. electoral
campaign.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FINLAND</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Helsingin Sanomat (independent) of Helsinki: ``... both scored
a victory but the Democrats' Michael Dukakis has to make a clearer
win in the next TV debate if he wants to win the election.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Ilta-Sanomat (independent) of Helsinki: ``Many had felt
Dukakis, who had done his homework and practiced with videos, would
floor Bush.
   ``But this did not happen, as Bush, who campaigned surprisingly
calmly and relaxedly, managed to get in a few painful hooks right
through the cold technocratic protection put up by Dukakis.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ITALY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Vittorio Zucconi, writing from New York in La Repubblica
(liberal) of Rome: ``Sunday night, on the stage, there were two
candidates but no leader.
   ``Neither Bush nor Dukakis has the natural gift of spontaneity
nor the talent for communication with the public that the `Great
Old One' (President Reagan) had in such abundance. ... Dukakis
could try ... to mobilize those Americans who don't vote anymore
because of indifference, cynicism, repulsion. However, he does not
have the human means, the charisma.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Roberto Pesenti, writing from New York in Il Messaggero
(moderate) of Rmne: ``Vivacious, aggressive and on target with
criticism: thus `Duca' (Dukakis) won, but ... without winning the
coveted political crown, which has remained in the hands of Vice
President Bush.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AUSTRIA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Neue Krone Zeitung (conservative) of Vienna: ``Bush was perhaps
more sympathetic, but Dukakis came across as the stronger man.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Kurier (centrist) of Vienna: ``The first debate ... brought no
clear winner or loser. But without doubt it was more useful for the
Democrat Dukakis than for the Republican Bush. Many millions of
U.S. viewers were seeing Dukakis in action for the first time: the
governor of Massachussetts ... showed himself relaxed and superior,
while Bush several times slightly lost his thread.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Die Presse (conservative) of Vienna: ``No one got a bloody
nose. ...''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
