<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-DebatePolls 1stLd-Writethru a0444 09-27 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate Polls, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Debate Polls Call it a Draw; One Marks Rise in Dukakis Stature</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS throughout to show NY Times NOT part of CBS poll</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national survey found ``major gains in
stature'' for Democrat Michael Dukakis in the presidential debate,
although that poll and three others rated the confrontation a tie
overall.
   None of the surveys found much change in voter preferences as a
result of Sunday's debate between Dukakis and Republican George
Bush, and most found relatively narrow movement in underlying
opinions of the candidates.
   But Dukakis did better than expected at standing up under
pressure and at appearing ``more presidential,'' a Los Angeles
Times poll found, and Bush lost ground in his rating on being able
to handle the federal deficit.
   Bush, however, improved his ratings in the poll on holding down
taxes, controlling crime and maintaining the national defense, and
more viewers rated him as likable than had expected to before the
debate.
   The outcome was rated even overall: Thirty-five percent of the
637 voters polled by the newspaper said Dukakis won the debate, 34
percent picked Bush and 29 percent called it a tie.
   Similarly, in a Gallup poll for Newsweek 42 percent said Dukakis
did the better job and 41 percent said Bush did better; in a ABC
News poll 44 percent said Dukakis won, 36 percent Bush; and in a
CBS News poll 42 percent said Bush won, 39 percent Dukakis.
   All the splits were within sampling error. The polls were
conducted Sunday night by calling back voters who had been
interviewed before the debate and said they intended to watch it.
   ``It's a wash,'' said Larry Hugick, political pollster for the
Gallup Organization. ``What we found is that the debate simply
reinforced the image that voters had of these men prior to the
debate.''
   As in pre-debate polls, Bush was rated higher on national
defense _ 63-31 in the Gallup poll of 337 voters _ while Dukakis
scored better on compassion, 51-33. The two were rated even on
being able to create needed changes and on having the ideas to
foster good economic conditions.
   Said Hugick: ``These guys are just even on a lot of things that
seem to be critical to who's going to win.''
   ABC's poll, of 639 debate watchers, indicated a possible
``sliver of movement'' toward Dukakis, said poll analyst John
Brennan. When polled before the debate, the 639 favored Dukakis in
the election by 48-46; when called back after the debate, they
favored Dukakis by 52-45.
   But the CBS poll of 415 debate viewers found the possibility of
incremental movement the other way. That group favored Bush by
49-44 before the debate and by 52-43 after it.
   In any case, ``Over 90 percent of each man's supporters stayed
with him through the debate,'' said Brennan. ``And that is the way
these things go. Even if it's a knockout, the effect on the horse
race is usually marginal.''
   On the movement in Dukakis' stature, the Los Angeles Times poll
found that before the debate respondents were split on who would
stand up better under pressure, with 36 percent picking Bush to 35
percent for Dukakis. After the debate, 48 percent said Dukakis has
stood up better, to 24 percent for Bush.
   And voters by 49 percent to 22 percent had expected Bush to be
``more presidential.'' After the debate, the division was narrower:
Forty-five percent said Bush had been more presidential, 29 percent
said Dukakis.
   The Los Angeles Times' analysis called those results ``major
gains in stature'' for Dukakis.
   Also, before the debate the newspaper poll found that 36 percent
thought Bush could do better at handling the deficit; after the
debate, that fell to 23 percent. Overall, though, the race was a
tie: Forty-six percent favored Bush for president, 46 percent
Dukakis.
   The horse race results applied just to debate watchers and not
to the entire electorate. Also, the polls had relatively small
sample sizes, and one-night surveys can be difficult to analyze
because they measure visceral reaction to a single event. The
margin of sampling error was five points in the Los Angeles Times,
CBS and ABC polls, six in Gallup's.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
