<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     09-27 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor's Condition Shows No Improvement; Grandson Summoned Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito thanked the Japanese people on
Tuesday for their outpouring of concern over his fragile health,
but doctors expressed no optimism about his condition.
   Palace officials said physicians have failed to contain Emperor
Hirohito's internal bleeding, and the government said it has
summoned the ailing 87-year-old monarch's grandson home from
Britain.
   Kenji Maeda, head of general affairs for the Imperial Palace,
quoted chief palace physician Akira Takagi as saying: ``The
emperor's condition is stable but it's not improving either. It's
an extremely difficult situation.''
   Maeda said doctors found ``slight traces'' of blood in the
emperor's bowel discharge Monday night, an indication of internal
hemorrhaging.
   Chief Cabinet Secretary Keizo Obuchi told reporters that Prince
Aya, the 22-year-old younger son of Crown Prince Akihito, would
return to Japan shortly from his studies at Oxford University.
   Japanese officials have refused to confirm or deny media reports
that the world's longest-reigning monarch is dying of cancer.
   Cabinet members have remained within calling distance and
scheduled visits by the prime ministers of Italy and Ireland have
been put on hold.
   More than 30,000 well-wishers called on the Imperial Palace in a
chilling rain Tuesday to sign registries wishing for the emperor's
recovery, the palace reported. Nearly 600,,000 people had signed
their names to registries at the palace and at 11 locations around
the country.
   Elderly Japanese, some wiping away tears, knelt in front of the
285-acre imperial residence in central Tokyo to pray for the
monarch, who was considered a deity until the end of World War II.
   Informed of the public response to his illness, the emperor
commented today: ``I thank everyone for their concern. Please
express my gratitude,'' according to a palace official.
   ``All we can say is that the emperor has come through one week
in stable condition,'' the agency quoted Akira Takagi, Hirohito's
chief physician, as saying.
   Hirohito received another blood transfusion Tuesday.
   His slight fever of 98.2 was down from 99 Monday evening but
still above his normal level of about 95.9.
   Although the emperor's body temperature and other vital readings
appeared to have stabilized, doctors said they were using
antibiotics to control fever and inflammation. News reports said
the emperor was also suffering from jaundice and anemia.
   Hirohito has had no food in eight days and aside from two small
ice cubes, has been unable to swallow water and is being fed
intravenously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
