<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0454,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Promises Students a `Drug-Free, AIDS-Free America'
^Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Quayle speech; picks up pvs 4th graf
bgng, Texas.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Previous NEW ORLEANS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE CHARLES, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle promised college
students today that a new Republican administration will give them
``a drug-free and AIDS-free America.''
   The GOP vice presidential nominee, heading for important
campaign appearances in Texas, appealed to 2,000 McNeese State
University students as ``children of the 80s'' for support in the
Nov. 8 elections.
   ``Let me tell you something, children of the 80s, the values of
family, future and freedom will never change,'' said the Indiana
senator, 41, the first baby boomer on a national party ticket.
   He promised if the GOP ticket headed by Vice President George
Bush is elected, ``we will do all that we must ... to give you a
drug-free and AIDS-free America.''
   He also promised every effort to provide better health care for
Americans as each generation takes care of elderly citizens who are
living longer than ever.
   ``George Bush and I are the leaders of tomorrow,'' Quayle said.
``We will lead this country forward into the decade of the 1990s.
We will make the future better than the past.''
   Quayle stood at Bush's side Monday at a Jackson, Tenn., rally in
his first joint appearance with the vice president since the
Republican National Convention in mid-August. He beamed as Bush
said he had ``not only confidence but pride'' in his embattled
running mate.
   From Lake Charles, Quayle headed for to Houston and El Paso on
his first campaign foray into Lone Star State, whose senator, Lloyd
Bentsen, the Democratic vice presidential candidate, will meet
Quayle in a nationally televised debate early next month.
   Texas, with its 29 electoral votes, is a key battleground in the
general election.
   Bush's judgment in picking Quayle was questioned by Democrat
Michael Dukakis in Sunday's debate, but Bush made a point during
Monday's rally of publicly praising his youthful running mate.
   The vice president predicted that the public would ``see some
more action'' when it tuned in to watch Quayle's Oct. 5 debate with
Bentsen, the Texas senator running with Dukakis.
   ``He's going to do just fine,'' Bush said, at one point giving
Quayle's arm a fatherly pat.
   Quayle was lavish in his praise for Bush's debate performance as
he addressed the rally of several thousand people at Casey Jones
Village, a railroad theme park.
   And, he had an answer for Dukakis' comments that ``the notion of
President Quayle is a very, very troubling notion tonight.''
   For most people, Quayle said, ``the notion of President Dukakis
is a very, very troubling notion today.''
   Despite the scripted rallies, the day was not without its drama.
   Quayle's plane, a 727 American Trans Air jet, had to abort its
landing just before it was to touch down in Jackson because the
pilot said another aircraft was in the process of landing on a
perpendicular runway in front of Quayle's plane. The airfield has
no air traffic control operation.
   The Quayle jet landed uneventfully on its second try, just
before Air Force Two arrived carrying Bush.
   In New Orleans later, Quayle toured the Martin Marietta NASA
Michoud assembly facility, which makes the external fuel tank for
the space shuttle, and then spoke to a convention of the National
Alliance of Business.
   At the Martin Marietta plant, Quayle noted that the countdown
had begun for this week's launch of the space shuttle Discovery. He
said the shuttle ``must and will remain vital ... and as confidence
in the space program is once again restored, through your hard
work, the U.S. will move on to other steps such as the space
station.''
   After his Texas swing, Quayle returns to Washington on Thursday
to begin preparing for the debate with Bentsen in Omaha, Neb.
   Quayle, 41, has said he views the event as an opportunity to
give the American public a ``direct and unedited'' look at his
qualifications and put to rest doubts they may have because of
media coverage of his candidacy and controversies over his military
service, academic record and personal life.
   Quayle has already begun receiving briefings on various issues
for the debate, aides said. Over the weekend, he received briefings
on economic issues from Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., ranking member
of the Senate Budget Committee, and on labor issues from Labor
Secretary Ann McLaughlin. Quayle also had a foreign policy session
recently with former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger.
   Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., will stand in for Bentsen during
Quayle's debate preparation.
</TEXT>
