<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Music Bjt   09-27 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Music, Bjt,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Rock Fans Await Amnesty Concert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They've never seen Michael Jackson but
do a fair imitation of moon-walking. For Indian fans of Western
rock music, the Beatles are a cult, Elvis is still alive, and
Madonna is scintillating.
   Almost no major Western rockers have toured India, but that
hasn't prevented thousands of Indians from being hooked on their
music.
   The long wait for a top Western pop concert ends Friday when a
rock-star-studded entourage including Bruce Springsteen, Sting and
Tracy Chapman hits New Delhi as part of a worldwide Amnesty
International tour.
   ``This is the biggest show to reach Southeast Asia,'' said Anil
Gupta, an organizer of the concert. ``It's the first time music's
mega-stars are playing in the region.''
   It will be staged in Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, with 70,000
tickets on sale.
   ``I visualize it as more than a sellout,'' said Gupta. ``I have
gotten inquiries for tickets from as far away as Trivandrum.''
   Trivandrum, on the southern tip of India, is 1,115 miles from
New Delhi.
   It is the first large Western music concert in India since the
groups Boney M and Osibisa performed in the early 1980s.
   But cassettes of Western artists sell by the hundreds every day
in the shops of major Indian cities.
   Letters pour into the Western music section of the
government-owned radio station, which runs at least three weekly
request programs from New Delhi and other big cities.
   ``I hear music from every house when I return home at night,''
says Rocque Fernandes, a drummer and the leader of a band which
plays in New Delhi hotels and restaurants.
   ``It's mostly beat music played on loud stereos. But there's
almost no Hindi music to be heard _ maybe because Hindi music
nowadays is Western music for 11 bars at a time.''
   Under international copyright laws, any duplication of at least
12 bars of existing music is an infringement.
   Hindi music is the term used to describe songs in films in the
Hindi language. In earlier years, the films were mostly lyrical
romances, and their soulful songs helped make a movie popular.
   But more recent films are more action-oriented, pulsing with a
disco Hindi-language soundtrack whose rhythms are usually taken
from Western hit tunes.
   Fernandes, from the Indian state of Goa, a former Portuguese
colony, leads a band which provides a rare opportunity to hear
Western music live in India.
   In live Indian performances, the music imitates the original,
but the vocals often have the unmistakable accent of an Indian
speaking or singing in English.
   Fernandes concedes his trio, which usually consists of a lead
guitarist doubling as the vocalist, a bass guitarist and himself on
the drums, cannot provide the best quality of music. ``Our
equipment isn't that good,'' he said.
   ``It's also difficult for most people to afford the prices our
hotels and clubs charge,'' he said. ``Ultimately, most fans have to
be satisfied with their stereos. Live music is expensive and even
then it's not too good.''
   The cassettes sell for about $2.15, and pirated versions go for
about two-thirds the price. Records are difficult to come by, and
compact discs have not yet made an impact in the country.
   The recent top sellers, according to New Delhi shop owner Ashok
Chehal, are Madonna, Samantha Fox and Michael Jackson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
