<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1441EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FallsAccident     09-27 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Falls Accident,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescue Workers Search For Student Feared Drowned At Cumberland
Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORBIN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers searched Tuesday for a college
student who was swept over the 65-foot Cumberland Falls as other
students watched in horror, authorities said.
   Teresa Dalton, 18, of Princewick, W.Va., slipped and fell over
the weekend while she was wading in shallow water just above the
falls, said Kentucky Water Patrol Officer Conley Allen. The
powerful current pulled Ms. Dalton over the waterfall.
   David Bryant, a Cumberland College junior from Miramar, Fla.,
was wading with Ms. Dalton and holding her hand when the accident
occurred. He also fell but grabbed a rock and kept from going over
the falls, he told police.
   On Monday, rescue workers unsuccessfully dragged the area. The
search, which has been hampered by rising water and fog, resumed
Tuesday.
   As Ms. Dalton went over the falls, students who had accompanied
her on the outing watched.
   ``I was yelling her name and hoping she would find something to
grab onto, but she kept going,'' Natalie Strange, a freshman from
Prattville, Ala., said in a statement to the Water Patrol.
   Danny E. Brown, superintendent of Cumberland Falls State Park,
said that until this summer it had been five years since anyone
went over the falls and died.
   On Aug. 27, a Tennessee man drowned after he jumped off the
overlook at the falls. The last death before that occurred Dec. 30,
1985, when a 13-year-old boy fell from a cliff while he was hiking
downriver from the falls.
</TEXT>
