<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Rowan-Trial 1stLd-Writethru a0425 09-27 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rowan-Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0425,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rowan's Attorney Rebuffed on Request for Verdict of Innocence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for syndicated columnist Carl T.
Rowan today argued that errors on a police form make it impossible
to prove Rowan used an unregistered handgun to wound a teenager
intruder.
   Sgt. Rise Williams, who works in the District of Columbia police
department's gun control unit, testified that the form _ filled out
several days after the June 14 incident to show that Rowan had not
registered the weapon used in the shooting _ did not specify
whether the paper referred to the columnist or his son, Carl Jr.
   Under questioning from Raoul Carroll, Rowan's attorney, Williams
also testified that Rowan's birthdate is listed on the form as
Sept. 11, 1925. Rowan's actual birthdate is Aug. 11, 1925.
   Williams said the columnist's address is listed correctly on the
form, but also testified that Rowan's son, a former FBI agent, had
used his father's address when he registered other weapons.
   A photograph of the person named on the form is another method
by which police can identify the individual named on the document,
but prosecutor Thomas C. Collier did not ask Williams to say
whether the columnist's or his son's photograph is attached to the
document. Williams refused to tell reporters after her testimony
which Rowan's picture was attached to the form.
   Arguing that the registration form, the police department's
formal method for telling prosecutors an unregistered weapon has
been used in a crime, fails to link Rowan to an unregistered
weapon, Carroll asked D.C. Superior Court Judge Arthur L. Burnett
Sr., for an immediate judgement of innocence. Burnett denied that
motion.
   Rowan, an outspoken opponent of handgun use and possession, on
June 14 shot a teenager who took a dip in the columnist's pool
without permission. If convicted on the charges of unlawful
possession of a gun and ammunition, Rowan would face a maximum
penalty of two years in jail and a $2,000 fine.
   Burnett on Monday selected a panel of 14 jurors, including two
alternates, from a pool of 60 prospective jurors.
   The jurors are eight men and six women. Eleven are black, three
are white. Rowan, 63, is black.
   During the proceedings, Rowan sat impassively at the defense
table, occasionally glancing at family members seated in the
courtroom.
   Burnett said the trial could last as long as a week, but Carroll
estimated that the matter could be sent to a jury by Wednesday.
   Rowan has steadfastly maintained that his son was repeatedly
rebuffed by city officials in his efforts to register the weapon
used in the shooting.
   Carroll had argued that the charges against the columnist should
be dismissed on these grounds, but Burnett rejected that motion,
ruling that the case centered on whether Rowan was authorized to
use the weapon, not whether it had been properly registered.
   However, Burnett ruled Monday that Rowan can enter as evidence
his son's account of efforts to register the .22-caliber weapon,
and detailed information about death threats the columnist says
prompted him to accept the weapon from his son in early 1983.
</TEXT>
