<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Panama,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panamanian President: U.S. Plans Overthrow Of Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man appointed president of Panama
today described the U.S. drug charges against Gen. Manuel Noriega
as lies and charged Washington with trying to overthrow the
Panamanian government.
   President Manuel Solis Palma in an address to the U.N. General
Assembly portrayed Panama as waging a battle against narcotics
traffickers. Palma said Noriega and his country were victims of a
U.S. propaganda war that could grow into armed conflict.
   Outside the assembly hall, Vernon A. Walters, the chief U.S.
representative to the United Nations, described the allegations as
``a litany of false accusations against the United States by Gen.
Noriega's hand-picked chief of state.''
   Noriega, considered the de-facto ruler of Panama, named Solis
Palma president in February, after deposing Solis Palmas'
predecessor, Eric Arturo Devalle. The United States continues to
recognize Devalle as president.
   Noriega was indicted in Florida this year on drug trafficking
charges after a lengthy U.S. investigation. Noriega denies
wrongdoing and has resisted U.S. efforts to remove him from power.
   ``I say that the whole campaign ... is nothing other than a
sinister tissue of lies and falsehoods carried out by the United
States government,'' Solis Palma said.
   The purpose of the attack is ``to overthrow the legitimate
government of Panama and impose a de-facto regime headed by figures
committed to renegotiation'' of the latest Panama Canal treaty,
Palma said.
   Under provisions of that treaty, the United States agreed to
relinquish operational control over the canal on Dec. 31, 1999.
</TEXT>
