<NOTE>EDs: Leads with 9 grafs to update with Reagan remarks on NATO
alliance; deletes grafs 10-11 pvs, Reagan had, as now outdated;
picks up 2nd graf pvs, Posing for.; deletes last 5 grafs pvs, In
other, to trim.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Asks Allies to Share in Defense Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, in a farewell meeting
with West European and Pacific figures, said today that free
nations must work harder to share the cost of defense.
   In a meeting with officials of 18 European and Pacific allies,
including South Korea, Australia and Japan, the president raised
anew the question of alliance burden-sharing _ the persistent U.S.
plea that America's allies shoulder a larger share of the costs of
defending Western Europe.
   In reply, allied leaders underscored the heavy contributions
their governments were making to developing countries, and said
this should be considered a significant contribution to the joint
objectives of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   ``They spoke in the same general terms as the president,
recognizing that everyone must continue to do their share,'' said
Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne Ridgway.
   She said that Reagan, who leaves office in about four months,
told the allied leaders that ``prosperity and security are
inextricably linked.''
   Winding up two days of meetings with a wide array of world
figures, Reagan also restated American condolences over the death
of Pakistani President Mohammed Zia ul Haq.
   But he told reporters that he did not know the circumstances
behind Zia's death in an airplane crash.
   ``All I've heard are speculations and so forth,'' the president
said during a picture-taking session. ``I have not gotten an
official report yet from any of our people.''
   On Monday, Reagan told leaders of Persian Gulf states that the
U.S. decision to stop escorting individual ships represents ``just
a slight difference'' in the Navy's waterway policing operation.
   Posing for pictures with Sheik Jaber Al-Almed Al-Sabah, the emir
of Kuwait, Reagan said, ``We're not lessening our protection there
at all.''
   On a busy day in which the president made his swan-song visit to
the United Nations, Reagan also heard an upbeat assessment of
Middle East peace prospects and voiced new hope that American
hostages in Lebanon might be set free.
   But the meetings were dominated by talk of the administration's
decision to abandon the policy of escorting U.S-flagged ships
traveling the dangerous Persian Gulf oil shipping lanes.
   ``We didn't stop. This is just a slight difference,'' Reagan
said. ``It was a Navy decision made because of a change in the
situation in the Middle East.''
   U.S. officials said the threat to commercial shipping in the
area has waned since Aug. 20, when Iran and Iraq began observing a
U.N. cease-fire resolution.
   Assistant Secretary of State Richard Murphy acknowledged during
a news briefing that the Kuwaiti leader had told Reagan he was
concerned that the United States ``keep open international shipping
channels.''
   Murphy said the move from individual ship escorts to a more
general U.S. military surveillance and protection operation
represents ``no significant reduction in our force levels and no
reduction in our commitment to help defend the freedom of
navigation.''
   ``There has been no overnight decision to drastically reduce the
forces within a set time frame,'' Murphy said. ``The position
remains, the forces will go down as the threat goes down.''
   During a separate picture-taking session with foreign ministers
Esmat Abdel Meguid of Egypt and Shimon Peres of Israel, Reagan
seemed to raise new hope for the release of American hostages,
although presidential aides insisted there were no new developments
to warrant optimism.
   ``We're encouraged,'' Reagan said when asked about chances the
nine Americans might be released. `` ... But I'm superstitious
about calling a no-hitter before the game is over.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters, ``What he
said was, `I don't want to talk about hostages because it might be
bad luck.'''
   Meanwhile, Reagan got assurances from Meguid that the Palestine
Liberation Organization was trying to find a way to acknowledge
Israel's right to exist.
   That would meet a primary U.S. condition for dealing with Yasser
Arafat's organization, which all Arab governments recognize as the
sole representative of Palestinians.
   Reagan told Meguid and Peres that the U.S. goal was to move
beyond the 1979 Egyptian-Israeli peace treaty to an overall
settlement that takes into account the ``legitimate rights'' of
Palestinian Arabs.
   According to Israeli sources who declined to be further
identified, Peres said his government would not deal with Arafat
and the PLO so long as they are involved in terrorism and violence
and speak of trying to force Israel back to the partition lines set
by the United Nations in 1947.
</TEXT>
