<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF-SovietInspection     09-27 0139</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF-Soviet Inspection,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Stage Surprise Inspection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union exercised its right for the
first time Tuesday to conduct a surprise inspection under the new
Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty, the Pentagon said.
   Dan Howard, the Defense Department's chief spokesman, said a
10-person team of Soviet inspectors had arrived earlier Tuesday at
the Rhein Main Air Base in West Germany and declared its intention
to conduct a so-called short-notice inspection.
   Under the treaty, the Soviets must inform the United States
which missile facility they want to inspect later Tuesday, the
spokesman added.
   The INF Treaty, which requires the elimination of all
intermediate- and shorter-range nuclear missiles, authorizes up to
20 short-notice inspections each calendar year for the next three
years. A smaller number of surprise visits are authorized during
each of the following 10 years.
</TEXT>
