<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mexico-BuildingCollapse 2ndLd-Writethru   09-27 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Building Collapse, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0587,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Six-Story Building Collapses, 2 Killed, Others Trapped</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout, 2 dead, others missing. quotes. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A six-story apartment house collapsed
today and slid down a steep mountainside in a wealthy district of
this northern industrial city. Officials said at least two people
were killed and others were trapped in the debris.
   At least two people survived the collapse, but both were
injured. The number of people trapped was not known.
   Francisco Javier Nakashima, an investigator with the state
judicial police, said the 3-year-old cement building collapsed
shortly before 9 a.m.
   ``One of the neighbors told us that six months ago they told the
architect that the building was loosening and and it was leaning,''
he said.
   Asked if the severe rains brought by Hurricane Gilbert 11 days
ago could have caused the collapse, he said: ``It had to have
something to do with it.''
   The bodies of a man and a boy were removed from the collapsed
building, Nakashima said.
   The building, which had one apartment to a floor, collapsed like
a pancake into a pile about one story high, and part of it slid
about 30 feet down the mountain. Mattresses, clothing and furniture
were strewn over the area.
   Perched high in the wealthy district of San Pedro Garza Garcia,
it was one of the highest buildings in Monterrey.
   Ruben Salinas Garcia, 27, was sleeping in his second floor
apartment when the building collapsed. ``I woke up and the roof was
on top of me,'' he said. He said his maid apparently was trapped
inside the builidng.
   His face and pink T-shirt were covered with blood and his chin
covered with white gauze bandage.
   Humberto Junco said his 19-month-old granddaughter, Ingrid
Junco, and a maid were inside his son's third floor apartment at
the time of the collapse. They have not been found, he said.
   A block down the street, the girl's weeping mother was attended
by neighbors.
   Francisco Rodriguez Loredo, an ambulance driver, said he took
two bodies from the scene and transported a survivor, a man about
25 years old, to Monterrey's Civil Hospital. The man appeared to
have broken ribs, he said.
   Gilbert caused heavy flooding in Monterrey. At least 140 people,
most of them passengers on buses, were swept away when water rushed
through the normally dry bed of the Santa Catarina River.
   Monterrey is Mexico's third largest city, with 2 million
residents, and the capital of the state of Nuevo Leon. It is a
major steel- and beer-producing city, and is located about 120
miles southwest of Laredo, Texas.
</TEXT>
