<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Whaling     09-27 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Whaling,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan To Kill Hundreds Of Whales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan plans to kill about 300 whales this winter in
a research project aimed at proving there are enough of the mammals
to resume commercial hunting, government officials said Tuesday.
   A similar plan last year was sharply criticized by international
environmental groups, which accused Japan of conducting the
experiment to circumvent an international ban on commerical whaling.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Japan
recently submitted the whaling plan to the International Whaling
Commission for review, but decided not to publicize its contents
until the evaluation was complete.
   They said Japan planned to catch ``very close'' to 300 minke
whales in the Antarctic this winter. The species is estimated by
the commission to number more than 430,000 worldwide.
   The Japanese government says research whaling is necessary to
assess whale stocks, and such factors as age, sex and health.
Japanese officials say they hope the research will prove there are
adequate numbers of some whale species, such as the minke, to allow
a resumption of limited commercial whaling.
   Last year, Japan told the commission it would kill 875 minke and
sperm whales for research purposes, but strong opposition from
international environmental groups and other commission members
reduced the catch to 273 minke whales, according to officials, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The officials said this year's research methods will be similar
to those practiced last year, when ships sailed along a fixed route
and killed only one or two whales in each group sighted.
   In 1982, the commission passed an international ban on
commercial whaling to allow scientists to study whale populations
without hunting pressure. The ban went into effect in 1986 and is
to be re-evaluated in 1990 on the basis of the research results.
   Japan officially ended its commercial whaling in Antarctica at
the end of the 1986-87 season, when it caught 1,941 of the mammals.
   The commission's charter allows member nations to conduct
research whaling without approval from the 42-member body.
   Environmentalists have charged that Japan _ where whale meat has
long been an important protein source _ is using the research
provision to maintain its whaling industry. Japanese officials say
other commission members have not been serious about conducting
research during the moratorium and plan merely to renew the ban in
1990.
   ``In the Antarctic, only Japan is conducting research,'' one
official said, speaking anonymously. ``The people who are
criticizing Japan are not presenting any data of their own.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
