<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma     09-27 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Claims Burmese Troops Executed Protesters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Burmese fleeing to frontier areas
claimed Tuesday they saw troops execute anti-government protesters,
and a newly formed opposition group accused the military government
of torture.
   Western diplomats in Rangoon say there are increasing reports of
executions of lower-level, anti-government leaders but they have
yet to be confirmed.
   The opposition League for Democracy league issued the torture
charge in a statement Tuesday, which said:
   ``It (the league) condemns and demands immediate ending of
irresponsible and illegal acts of arrests, torture and killings in
Rangoon and other towns.''
   The statement provided no other details.
   The coalition also named retired army officer Aung Gyi as its
chairman, former defense minister Tin Oo as vice chairman and Aung
San Suu Kyi, daughter of slain independence leader Aung San, as
general secretary and spokeswoman.
   Aung Gyi immediately called for an interim government to replace
the military government of Gen. Saw Maung, which took power in a
Sept. 18 coup and cracked down on nationwide street demonstrations.
   The government announced Tuesday that 348 persons had been
killed nationwide, 219 others wounded and 1,107 arrested since
Sept. 18. But the government has not mentioned actual executions of
detainees.
   The government previously acknowledged more than 250 deaths but
has not mentioned executions. Western diplomats believe troops
killed up to 400 civilians in the first few days after the coup.
   In Ghay Baw Bo near the Thailand border, some Burmese said the
executions took place as people protesting 26 years of
authoritarian rule fled to areas of Burma controlled by Karen
guerrillas.
   Soe Hlaing, a 36-year-old lawyer from Pegu, said he saw nine
people executed by soldiers on a bridge in the town of Tharrawdy
during his flight.
   ``Each was shot with a gun. One bullet to the heart,'' Soe
Hlaing said.
   A student from the Rangoon Institute of Technology said he
witnessed the ``sysematic killing'' of 10 people in Mudon, south of
the coastal city of Moulmein. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Most of the alleged killings occurred after Saw Maung sent
troops into the streets of Rangoon and other cities to put down
massive anti-government demonstrations.
   The League for Democracy, formed Saturday, united Burma's
traditionally fragmented opposition to revitalize the
anti-government movement after the military crackdown.
   A league official announced the leadership appointments. Nine of
12 Executive Committee members also were named with the open seats
reserved for ethnic minorities also fighting the central government.
   Aung Gyi said the group believes ``that (an) interim government
is the only way to solve the present crisis in the country.''
   Saw Maung has promised the first multiparty elections since 1960
but has not set a timetable. He has not responded to calls for an
interim government.
   The league also said Tuesday it ``firmly supports the general
strike being staged by the government servants and workers, and
urges the strikers to continue until the movement for democracy
achieves its goal.''
   Saw Maung has ordered civil servants, who left their jobs Aug. 8
to protest political repression and economic decline, to returned
to work by Monday.
   Although the government claims some workers are back on the job,
business remains crippled.
</TEXT>
