<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CadetsStricken 2ndLd-Writethru a0567 09-27 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cadets Stricken, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0567,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stricken Cadet Undergoes Liver Transplant as Investigation
Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede SPRINGFIELD, Mass.
^Eds: UPDATES throughout with comments on investigation, deleting
outdated material. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A comatose police academy cadet, one of 16
overcome last week by strenuous training, underwent a liver
transplant today, but officials said an investigation showed no
evidence that he or others had been abused at the academy.
   At a news conference, the officials said the training was
routine for the first day at the academy, including repeated heavy
exercise.
   Dr. George Grady, the chief state epidemiologist, had said
earlier that his preliminary examination last week found ``it's
very clear the exercise was stressful.''
   But he said today that further investigation found ``at this
time that the cause of the illness was a relatively insufficient
intake of water relative to the amount of exercise they were
doing.''
   Gary Egan, executive director of the Massachusetts Criminal
Justice Training Council, said, ``There was strenuous physical
activities, as there always was on that first day ... (but) we have
found no one that was denied water upon request.''
   Asked if his conclusion was that it was the fault of individual
cadets that they took ill, Egan said, ``Some of them were unware of
the fact that they were doing damage to themselves.'' Earlier, some
cadets had said they had been given only a small amount of water
the day the cadets had taken ill.
   Timothy Shepard, 25, of Pittsfield, who has been in a weeklong
coma, entered surgery Monday night for a liver transplant at
Pittsburgh's Presbyterian Hospital.
   Rose Eberts, hospital nursing administrator, would say only that
Shepard's condition was critical this morning.
   Pittsfield Mayor Anne Everest Wojtkowski, who is acting as a
spokeswoman for the Shepard family, said said the surgery was
completed at 5:30 a.m. today and the family was told that Shepard
came through the operation ``very well.''
   Shepard was the most seriously ailing cadet after last week's
series of illnesses swept the Edward J. Connelly Criminal Justice
Training Center in Agawam just south of Springfield.
   Several former cadets have suffered similar fatigue-related
medical problems at the academy over the past four years, according
to former cadets and an Amherst physician.
   Dr. Constance Lentz said she treated between three and eight
police recruits from Holyoke in 1984 after they were overcome on
the first day of training at the academy.
   Among the 16 cadets who were hospitalized beginning Sept. 19,
the first day of classes, ailments ranged from dark urine to
exhaustion and dehydration.
   Although several stricken cadets refused to be interviewed
Monday without clearance from superiors, one former trainee said
the training routine was severe.
   ``I've been through basic training in the Army and it was twice
as bad as that,'' said Mike Purcell, who quit the academy after one
day. ``The doctors told me that if I had gone back for a second
day, I could have suffered permanent kidney damage.''
   After Shepard collapsed while running Sept. 19, instructors
allowed the recruits to drink two small cups of water, Purcell
said. ``Before that, they had lined us up at the bubbler twice
during the day and only let us take one cup of water each.''
   Six recruits remained hospitalized Monday.
   Several local officials, including Wojkowski and North Adams
Mayor John Barrett III, asked the state attorney general's office
to review the training program.
   Wojkowski met Monday with Egan and state police Capt. Thomas
White of the Agawam academy.
   ``I was completely dissatisfied with their responses,''
Wojkowcki said. ``I suspect that the incidents are not isolated.''
   Shepard was in top shape and had worked out more than six months
preparing for the academy, said his brother, Thomas Jr. ``He really
wanted to be a policeman,'' the brother said.
   Jeff Grossman, a spokesman for the state office of public
safety, said Shepard's condition may have resulted in part from a
``self-induced, severe diet.''
   But Thomas Shepard said his brother spent the days before
reporting to the academy with his family and ate normally.
</TEXT>
