<DOCNO> AP880927-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1810EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Lebanon     09-27 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Lebanon,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New U.S. Ambassador Urging Rivals to Agree on Peaceful Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newly arrived U.S. ambassador in Beirut
has begun meeting rival Lebanese leaders, urging restraint and
support for a peaceful presidential election according to the
country's constitution, the State Department said Tuesday.
   ``Our highest priority now is to urge restraint on all parties
and to emphasize the contribution they can make to peaceful
constitutional presidential elections,'' department spokeswoman
Phyllis Oakley said.
   Ambassador John McCarthy arrived from the United States over the
weekend. On Tuesday he talked with Michel Aoun, the Christian
general appointed by outgoing President Amin Gemayel to head a
military government, as well as acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss
and Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini, both Moslems, she said.
   Aoun's government has been rejected by the Moslem majority,
which recognizes only the Hoss Cabinet, and reports from Beirut
said the appointment pushed the country closer to formal partition.
   Mrs. Oakley said the ambassador's meetings were undertaken ``in
the context of maintaining contact with ... as many of the Lebanese
groups and leaders important to the political process as possible
under existing security conditions.
   ``With a successful election, the Lebanese can begin to restore
the functioning of government and initiate the process of reform
and reconciliation that Lebanon needs,'' she added.
   Although the size of the U.S. Embassy has been reduced because
of insecure living conditions in Beirut, ``all essential embassy
functions are continuing,'' and McCarthy and his staff will
continue to ``maintain as broad contact as possible,'' Mrs. Oakley
said.
   She had no comment on a Beirut report that Aoun had banned
direct helicopter flights to the Embassy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
