<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-Debate     09-27 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Debate,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Now Says He Was Better Than Even In Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<HEAD>AP White House Correspondent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush upgraded his
assessment of his debate with Democrat Michael Dukakis, saying
Tuesday ``maybe we did a little better'' than just a draw.
   Bush, who had tried to play down his forensic skills as he went
into the debate, told reporters on Air Force Two: ``I feel better
today about the way the debate went than I did the night of the
debate.
   ``As I think I told you, I felt it was about even and I now
think maybe we did a little better than that in terms of what we
needed to do. But I can't prove it.''
   Asked why his assessment was so much more modest than that of
other GOP officials, Bush said, ``Well those are what we call the
spin merchants.''
   When a reporter expressed surprise that he was willing to use
that term, Bush replied: ``I've learned to. We've got different
levels of hand wringing in our campaign.
   ``The lowest levels were relieved that I didn't massively foul
it up. It's what we call the relief factor. ...
   ``And I tell you as that worry factor subsided and it was
replaced by what we call the relief factor, you can understand the
rising up of exuberance.
   ``And so there were some proclamations of a `knockout,' `clear
win,' but some of it was the adrenalin rising in that level of
hand-wringers.''
   Asked why he would keep hand-wringers on his staff, he replied:
``Because they need to keep me on the ball. I need their advice. I
welcome their criticism and advice, unlike others. I know I'm not
perfect. This will come as a surprise to you.''
</TEXT>
