<2ND_LINE>AM-Racial Tension,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Racial Tension Causes Police to Increase Patrols</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLINTON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police increased patrols at the high
school and will have all off-duty and reserve officers at the
school's homecoming football game Friday to prevent a flare up in
recent racial tensions, officials said.
   ``We're taking extra precautions,'' said Police Chief Don
Byington.
   A small group of white and black students in recent weeks have
been pushing and shoving each other and shouting racial slurs on
the Clinton High School campus, Byington said. Similar tensions
have arisen in past years in the 71 percent white district, said
Byington and School Superintendent Virgil Belue.
   The disturbances peaked Friday night, when a white Clinton High
student was beaten by ``three or four'' black Clinton High students
at a convenience store, Byington said.
   Belue said administrators and parents have acted to quell the
unrest. On Sunday and Monday, parents met with school and police
officials to talk about ways to stop tension.
   Officials say they're unsure what sparked the tension.
   ``Sometimes it starts over a disagreement,'' Belue said, adding
an incident several years ago started in this town west of Jackson
with students fighting over a parking place. ``Some of these things
aren't necessarily race-related when they start.
   ``But when that difference comes up and a white student is on
one side and a black student on the other, it's identified as a
racial thing,'' he said.
</TEXT>
