<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1803EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Nielsens     09-27 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nielsens,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Olympics Increase in Ratings But Still Lag Below Guarantee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC's seven nights of Summer Olympics coverage
made the top seven prime-time shows in the A.C. Nielsen Co.
television ratings last week despite that coverage is receiving
lower-than-anticipated ratings.
   NBC had guaranteed advertisers an average 21.2 rating. Last
week's coverage ranged from 20.1 to 16.8. A 13.9 was recorded for
the half-hour before the presidential debate on Sunday. The
90-minute pre-emption ``seriously affected the overall rating,''
said NBC analyst Jeff Boehme. Otherwise, the Olympics ratings
pretty much rose as the week went on and showed an increase over
the disappointing first three nights.
   If the Olympics rating doesn't live up to the guarantee to
advertisers, NBC has to provide them with free commercial time on
other programs to make up the difference.
   NBC won the week, nevertheless, with its highest weekly rating
in a year, a 19.3 that was also the highest network weekly rating
since a win for ABC during the Winter Olympics. ABC was second with
a 10.7 and CBS third with a 9.8.
   The Olympics were good news and bad news for ``NBC Nightly
News.'' It probably would have been in first place for the first
time since 1987 thanks to the Olympics boost. But it only tied with
ABC for second place _ because of pre-emptions on the West Coast
for live coverage of the Olympics.
   The ``CBS Evening News'' won the week with 10.1 rating and 20
share. ABC ``World News Tonight'' tied NBC with a 9.8. ABC had a 20
share and NBC a 21 share, a result of different time periods that
gave NBC a bigger portion of a smaller audience.
   Each rating point equals 904,000 households with televisions.
The share is a percentage of sets in use.
   The week ending Sept. 25 was the first of the official new
television season. However, ABC and CBS are maintaining the season
doesn't really begin until late October, when all three networks
have premiered most of their new fall shows. ABC and CBS are airing
reruns and movies to counter NBC's two weeks of Olympics
programming.
   NBC's Thursday night coverage was the top-rated show of the
week, followed by Saturday, Friday, Sunday, Wednesday, Tuesday and
Monday. CBS followed with its rerun TV movie ``A Stranger Waits,''
and ABC made the top 10 with Tuesday night comedies, ``Head of the
Class'' and ``Growing Pains.''
   The lowest-rated shows of the week were: ``Cadets,'' ``Live!
Dick Clark Presents,'' ``The Best of SCTV,'' ``48 Hours,'' ``Beauty
& the Beast,'' ``Garry Shandling Alone in Las Vegas,''
``Bodywatching,'' ``West 57th,'' ``First Impressions'' and
``Frank's Place.''
</TEXT>
