<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1616EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Targets Bjt   09-27 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Targets, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commitment To 50-State Campaign Appears Not Quite Solid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With six weeks to go to election day, aides to
Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis are scaling back
expectations across parts of the South and Rocky Mountain West but
express continuing hopes for Texas and a handful of border states.
   The West Coast states are still viewed as prime battlegrounds,
as well, and practically the entire Northeast and Industrial
Midwest are up for grabs in the view of campaign officials.
   But one aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
campaign would soon ``begin pulling back budget and pulling back
staff'' from some states where chances of victory are dim, and
saving them for the more competitive regions.
   Dukakis and his aides have pledged frequently to run a 50-state
campaign this fall.
   ``Watch the schedule'' for clues about which states are regarded
as more winnable, said one adviser, also speaking on condition he
not be identified by name. In his campaigning since the Democratic
National Convention, Dukakis has appeared sparingly in the Deep
South, with the exception of Texas, home state to running mate
Lloyd Bentsen. Dukakis' recent trip to Arkansas and Kentucky were
indications of a continued commitment to several border states in
what shapes up as a close election, officials said.
   Publicly, senior advisers say they will not concede any state to
Bush. ``We are not going to fall into the Republican trap of
cutting off parts of the country,'' said Dukakis' field director
Charlie Baker, who said that the Democrats have assembled a
50-state field organization for the first time in several elections.
   Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas, addressing a meeting of
Southern governors Tuesday at Sea Island, Ga., said, ``We're being
realistic, but we're also campaigning here and will continue to do
so becuase we think we can be successful in the South.''
   Officials hotly dispute that they have reduced efforts in
Florida, with 21 electoral votes, and say they have recently
dispatched new aides to the state. They say that talk of scaling
back is a Republican-inspired ploy to undermine their chances.
   But in contrast to Texas, where the campaign is committed to
running television advertisements specially created for the state,
no similar decision has been made for Florida. And in contrast to
Dukakis' periodic visits to Texas, the Democratic candidate has
been to Florida only once since the Democratic convention in July,
and is not scheduled to return until Oct. 11.
   Dukakis and his advisers have repeatedly pledged their
commitment to a 50-state campaign, and at a meeting of campaign
officials in July, senior adviser Jack Corrigan said he promised
the directors of the 50 statewide oranizizations that Dukakis would
commit the necessary resources in each of them.
   In states such as Virginia, Mississippi, South Carolina, Alabama
in the South and traditional Republican strongholds in the West
such as Wyoming, Idaho and Utah, Arizona, Nevada and Alaska, as
well as Kansas and Nebraska, campaign officials concede privately
they have little chance for success.
   Republican vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle's home state
of Indiana is regarded as an extremely difficult state, as is New
Hampshire, according to officials.
   In all, the states involved carry roughly 100 Electoral Votes,
out of 270 needed for victory in the race for the White House. The
states have voted Republican in most recent elections, and Bush
campaign officials have said all year they would give the
Republicans a solid launching pad for their campaign.
   ``We are not at a point yet in our views to completely write off
any states and it is not our plan to do that,'' said Baker, field
director for Dukakis. ``But clearly as this thing tightens up in
terms of last-minute media buy decisions and last minute scheduling
decisions you've got to make some decisions on how you put together
an electoral college majority.''
   Another aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said it is
important to keep states competitive in order to keep the
Republicans spending time and resources. ``You see where we are by
looking at the schedule but that doesn't mean we don't keep targets
of opportunity, either,'' the aide said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
