<2ND_LINE>AM-Firefighters-Homosexuals,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gay Firefighter Appointed Liaison to Gay-Lesbian Community</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veteran firefighter appointed the city's first
liaison to the gay and lesbian community said Tuesday he hopes to
use his post to promote tolerance and change homophobic attitudes.
   Fire Inspector Jim Murphy said he also wants to provide support
for other homosexuals in the department and help alleviate tension
between the department and the gay community.
   ``I'll be there to listen,'' Murphy said. ``I'm an openly gay
man and I have been out, so to speak, within the department for 15
months.
   ``Primarily, I hope to address, in one small measure, the issue
of violence within the gay community. ... Homophobia, violence, gay
bashing and all that. That's what I hope to change,'' said Murphy,
41.
   City officials said they hope the job, believed to be the first
of its kind in the country, will improve relations with the gay
community, which reached a low point two years ago when three young
people reported they were violently attacked by off-duty
firefighters shouting anti-gay slurs.
   ``We have an image within the community of being very macho,
sometimes parochial men. It's not wholly true,'' said Murphy, who
has worked for the department for nine years.
   ``A lot of these guys, they have brothers and cousins that are
gay, they just don't discuss it.''
   Fire Commissioner Leo Stapleton agreed immediately to a
suggestion that the new job be created, said Ann Sanders, Mayor
Raymond Flynn's liaison to the gay and lesbian community.
