<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Defectors     09-27 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defectors,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Who Defected to Soviet Union Then Returned Home Now Jobless
and Broke</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ERI1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who sought a better life in the Soviet
Union following financial setbacks in the United States are back
home, saying they are broke, embittered and have been deceived by
U.S. officials.
   Theodore and Cheryle Branch, who returned to the United States
last week after 10 months in the Soviet Union, were staying Tuesday
in a small motel in Erie. They had previously lived in nearby
Summit Township.
   ``By Monday, we will be broke so we are going to move into the
U.S. Courthouse to live,'' said Branch, 42, referring to the
federal courthouse in Erie.
   The Branches said they moved to the Soviet Union because ``we
were so mad at the U.S. government, but not at the people.''
   ``We're really mad now,'' he said.
   The couple claimed that after Soviet officials gave them a
furnished apartment and jobs at Radio Moscow's North American
Service, officials at the U.S. Embassy there offered them the same
benefits plus help resolving their financial troubles if they
returned to the United States.
   However, State Department officials in Washington, D.C., said
the Branches were offered only the same loan available to any
stranded U.S. citizen to finance passage home.
   ``They made promises there, and now they are backing out,''
Branch claimed.
   Branch said that after they arrived in Moscow, the Soviets asked
them to visit the U.S. Embassy because American officials were
worried about them.
   He said they refused because ``we vowed we would never step
inside another federal building. They weren't worried about us
there, why would they be worried about us here?''
   The Soviets asked them in February to assure the U.S. Embassy
that they were not being held against their will. Branch claims
that during a subsequent meeting, Jill Farrelly-Byrnes, the
embassy's second secretary and vice consul, said, ``Do you need
money? We have jobs for you. We have a place for you to live and
medical care.''
   At an August meeting, the embassy officials said they could not
help the Branches solve their problems unless they returned to the
United States, Branch said.
   ``We thought if they were willing to work with us, to make
amends, why should we hold a grudge?'' he said.
   No one greeted them in Washington as promised, Branch said.
   ``I think we have been deceived. We have been stripped of
everything,'' said Mrs. Branch, 40. ``It is hard to believe that in
a democratic society two people could be in such a predicament.''
   The couple want to be reimbursed for the $3,000 airfare and the
motel room.
   ``The government is heavily indebted to us and why shouldn't we
feel like this?'' said Mrs. Branch. ``It is supposed to be a great
democracy.''
   ``We wouldn't be here looking for a job if they hadn't promised
us,'' Branch said.
   He said they might return to the Soviet Union but are ``tired of
moving back and forth across the ocean at somebody's whim.''
   The troubles that made the Soviet Union look good included the
couple's inability to collect $10,000 in back wages from Central
Florida Broadcasting Co. despite a federal court judgment in their
favor.
   Land they owned in Erie County was declared part of a flood
plain by the federal government and is worthless, Mrs. Branch said.
</TEXT>
