<1ST_LINE>u i AM-HamadiTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0708 09-27 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,0764</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hamadi Didn't Kill Navy Diver Aboard Hijacked Jet, Witness Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-5 pvs `The attendant...Waldorf, Md.' with 4
grafs to CORRECT spelling of Stethem throughout. PICKS 6th graf pvs
`Ms. Hesp ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flight attendant testifying at
the murder and air piracy trial of Mohammed Ali Hamadi said Tuesday
that Hamadi's accomplice killed a U.S. Navy diver aboard a hijacked
TWA airliner.
   The attendant, Hazel Hesp, said hijacker Hassan Ezzeddine killed
diver Robert Stethem after the TWA jet was commandeered June 14,
1985.
   The testimony contradicted that of John Testrake, the plane's
pilot, who told the court he believed Hamadi was the hijacker who
killed Stethem.
   Ms. Hesp also testified that Ezzeddine claimed a friend of his
had carried out the bombing mission that killed 241 U.S. servicemen
in Beirut in 1983.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, has admitted hijacking the TWA
jetliner on the Athens-to-Rome flight and holding 39 Americans
hostage for 17 days. But said the other hijacker killed Stethem, of
Waldorf, Md.
   Ms. Hesp said Ezzeddine, who is at large, ``seemed to be giving
the orders'' during the hijacking.
   The 47-year-old Ms. Hesp said ``Said'' was the name Ezzeddine
used during the hijacking. Hamadi, she said, called himself
``Castro.''
   Ms. Hesp did not name her home or nationality, under guidelines
set by the court to protect witnesses in the trial, some of whom
have said they feared reprisals. Her speech had a British accent.
   Outside the courtroom at Preungesheim prison, security remained
tight as it has been since the trial began July 5. There were about
two dozen policemen near the entrance, and at least three carried
machine guns.
   Asked by the court judge if she knew who killed the 23-year-old
Stethem, Ms. Hesp paused, then said: ``Yes. But I did not see the
shot, so it is only my opinion. It would be my opinion that it
would be Said who shot.''
   She added: ``They were both terrifying, of course, but of the
two men it is my feeling that Said was the more vicious.''
   ``I remember when we first took off from Athens and they punched
our heads down and they were running up and down screaming,'' Ms.
Hesp said. ``I remember I was always more afraid when I saw the
white shoes, because I knew they belonged to Said.''
   Other witnesses, including flight engineer Benjamin Zimmermann,
have testified Ezzeddine was the more violent of the two hijackers,
but that both seemed to have equal authority.
   When asked to comment, Hamadi, who sat quietly through much of
the testimony with his elbow propped on the table and chin in his
left palm, told the court in Arabic through his translator he had
nothing to say.
   Throughout the trial, the court has given Hamadi the opportunity
to comment without having to take the witness stand.
   Ms. Hesp said Ezzeddine could speak a litte English and told her
a friend of his drove a truck laden with explosives into the U.S.
Marine compound in Beirut in 1983, blowing up the barracks and
killing 241 U.S. servicemen.
   ``He seemed to be very proud of this and told of how he hates
Americans, and wondered how non-Americans could work for an
American airline,'' said Ms. Hesp.
   Across the courtroom, facing Hamadi, Patricia and Richard
Stethem, the parents of the slain Navy diver, took notes and
listened quietly.
   In other testimony Tuesday, another flight attendant, Jody Cox,
47, described how she and others on the flight were forced to sit
for hours with their heads between their knees and hands on the
back of their heads.
   Speaking in an unsteady voice, Ms. Cox, an American, said she
heard the screams of hostages being beaten by the hijackers.
   ``I saw Clinton Suggs with his hands bound, and Stethem too.
They had cloths tied around their heads as blindfolds,'' Ms. Cox
said.
   Suggs testified Monday he thought he would die next when one of
the hijackers said after Stethem was shot, ``One more in five
minutes.''
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt Airport on Jan. 13, 1987, after
customs officials discovered liquid explosives in his luggage. In
the following week, two West Germans were kidnapped in Beirut. Both
men have been freed.
   Hamadi's brother, Abbas Hamadi, was convicted by a Duesseldorf
court of taking part in the kidnappings in a failed effort to
pressure West Germany into releasing Mohammed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
