<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 2014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ExportPromotion     09-27 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Export Promotion,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAO Says Export Promotion Programs In `State Of Disorder'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia Rep. Doug Barnard charged Tuesday that
export promotion programs run by the Department of Commerce are
doing more to confuse American businesses seeking to market their
products abroad than to help them.
   Barnard, a Democrat who heads the House government operations
subcommittee on commerce, consumer and monetary affairs, said a
General Accounting Office study requested by the subcommittee
concluded that the department's management of trade shows and trade
missions abroad is in ``a state of disorder.''
   ``Instead of helping American businesses to get into the export
business, it seems that the Commerce Department is doing more to
confuse and frustrate anyone who thinks about selling abroad,''
Barnard said. ``This situation must be remedied without delay.''
   A draft copy of the GAO report, released by the subcommittee,
said about 55 percent of the major trade events scheduled abroad by
the department's International Trade Administration in 1987 were
canceled.
   The GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, said the frequent
cancellation of advertised trade shows or missions ``has limited
the credibility of the program in the U.S. business community and
in some overseas locations.''
   Desiree Tucker, a spokeswoman for the ITA, said the agency has
reviewed the GAO report and is preparing a written response.
   Major responsibility for export promotion programs abroad lies
with the ITA's U.S. and Foreign Commercial Service, which has 155
commercial officers in 66 countries. The agency, which also has
offices in 48 states, had a $68.9 million budget in fiscal 1987,
with $39.2 million for foreign operations.
   Two other ITA divisions share the responsibility for export
promotion programs, the GAO said, and a lack of coordination among
the three units has resulted in poor planning and execution of
trade events and a lack of accountability.
   The GAO also criticized the U.S. and Foreign Commerical Service
for failing in three attempts since 1978 to develop a computerized
trade information data base that would provide up-to-date
international marketing and trade information to government and
business officials.
   A ``very limited'' version of the data base is supposed to be
operational by tne end of the year, the GAO said. Full
implementation is expected to cost $39.9 million through 1993, not
including the $13.4 million spent on the two previous attempts to
computerize the trade data.
</TEXT>
