<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ArmsCurbs     09-27 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Curbs,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Seeks to Keep Nuclear Arms Out of Troop Reduction Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, in a move
bound to reassure France, said Tuesday that East-West troop
reduction talks would not be expanded to cover nuclear weapons.
   But it still was not clear when the negotiations might begin
despite President Reagan's statement that they would open soon and
discussions this week at the United Nations.
   The negotiations between the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
and the Warsaw Pact are intended to reduce non-nuclear forces,
tanks and other mobile weapons in Europe.
   French President Francois Mitterrand and Defense Minister
Jean-Pierre Chevenement, during talks Thursday in Washington with
Reagan and Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci, are expected to reject
any Soviet attempt to use the forum to promote nuclear weapons
reductions.
   France agreed to the negotiations only with reluctance. The
French are determined to protect their independent nuclear force
from cutbacks under joint U.S.-Soviet pressure. In fact, France is
planning to deploy a new tactical missile system.
   Shultz, at a news conference here, said flatly: ``The talks will
not be expanded to include nuclear weapons. They are confined to
conventional weaons.''
   The start of negotiations has been delayed by a dispute over
human rights. The United States has sought assurances from the
Soviet Union that there would be a simultaneous improvement in
human rights conditions in Eastern Europe.
   The issue was discussed at meetings that Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze had in Washington last week with Reagan and
Shultz.
   U.S. officials said afterward that the Spviets had promised to
release 27 political prisoners and to reform their emigration
regulations.
   Reagan, in a speech Monday to the U.N. General Assembly, said
the East-West talks would open soon.
   Both Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Vladimir Petrovsky and
British Foreign Secretary Geoffrey Howe, in separate meetings
Tuesday with reporters, said the chances were good the talks would
be held this year.
   Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne L. Ridgway said, however,
Shevardnadze's visit to Washington ``certainly did not erase all of
the differences.''
   She said U.S. officials reviewed the situation this week with
West European allies attending the U.N. session.
   ``I think there's a sense here that the last issues have been
defined,'' she said. ``But there is nothing that has been done here
to specifically _ on a case-by-case basis _ to change the
situation.''
</TEXT>
