<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Books     09-27 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Books,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Book Exhibit Opens In Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of Soviet readers got a tantalizing look
Tuesday at American books that most of them still cannot buy.
   The exhibit of several thousand volumes is the latest foreign
joint venture to offer Western products for the foreign currency
that few are permitted to hold. Soviets can order the books by mail
from publishers.
   Soviets browsed among books such as an atlas with more detailed
and accurate maps of their own country than those published by
Soviet map makers; a handbook on future NASA missions; fiction by
once-banned native authors and a book by Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   Despite the currency limitations and the exhibit's obscure
location _ behind two gates and in a corner of an international
exhibition hall _ the American organizers were grateful.
   ``It ain't Gorky Street,'' a popular Moscow shopping area,
acknowledged Martin Levin of the firm Cowan, Liebowitz and Latham
of New York.
   But Gorky Street is next on Levin's agenda. He hopes a store
that accepts Soviet rubles will open within a year.
   Levin defended the current, hard-to-find site because ``having
the (Soviet) public come in is counterproductive'' as long as they
lack the right money to spend.
   Only the few Soviets with hard currency legally obtained through
such means as a trip abroad, and retained in a Soviet bank account,
will be able to order books from the exhibit, said Dmitry Mamleev,
deputy chairman of the State Committee on Publishing, Printing and
Book Trade.
   The yearlong exhibit will cater to Soviet libraries and Soviet
businesses with hard currency such as dollars. U.S. publishers
chose to send largely scientific and technical works sought by
Soviet institutional customers.
   American fiction was nearly non-existent. The handful of volumes
included Alex Haley's ``Roots,'' and Tom Wolfe's ``The Right
Stuff'' and ``Bonfire of the Vanities.''
   The books can be ordered for the regular U.S. price plus 10
percent, but most customers will have to wait as long as four
months for delivery, according to the Soviet government's
distributor, the International Books agency.
   Alexander Belostotsky, deputy director of International Books,
gave assurances that any book ordered through his agency will reach
its buyer, despite a Soviet history of prohibiting individual
importation of most foreign publications.
   Other joint ventures in the Soviet Unio with goods available
only for foreign currency include Baskin-Robbins ice cream and
British beer.
</TEXT>
