<HEAD>Nancy Caught In Traffic, Holds Up Reagan's Motorcade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The heavy traffic in the heart of New York City,
can be unforgiving, even for the president of the United States and
his wife.
   President Reagan's departure from The Waldorf-Astoria hotel was
delayed for about 20-30 minutes Tuesday when his wife, Nancy, was
held up in traffic returning from another part of Manhattan.
   Reagan's long motorcade was wrapped around the hotel at the
corner of 50th Street and Lexington Avenue. While frustrated New
York motorists leaned on their horns, the president's party held
fast while they awaited the first lady.
   That didn't put a damper on things, however, for the thousands
of New Yorkers who poured out onto the streets in the early
afternoon sun to witness the presidential party's motorcade as it
wended its way through streets totally cleared for its passage to a
heliport in Manhattan.
   Mrs. Reagan seemed to go out of her way to assure reporters that
the delay was unavoidable. ``I got stuck in traffic,'' she said as
she joined the president in boarding Air Force One at Newark
International Airport for the return trip to Washington.
   Once on the ground at Andrews Air Force Base in suburban
Maryland, Mrs. Reagan walked toward reporters briefly and said
again that she had been held up in traffic.
   Asked if she had been shopping in New York City, Mrs. Reagan
shook her head and said, ``Lunch.''
   Asked whether the president had gotten angry over the delay, she
smiled broadly, looked in his direction, and said, ``No.''
   Reagan conducted two days of talks with a host of foreign
leaders and addressed the United Nations' General Assembly.
</TEXT>
