<1ST_LINE>r w AM-S&LCrisis     09-27 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&L Crisis,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Would Appoint Panel To Investigate S&L Crisis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Banking Committee
said Tuesday he will introduce legislation to create a 14-member
panel to study the savings and loan crisis and make recommendations
to the next president and Congress early next year.
   The bill, to be sponsored by Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I.,
is similar to legislation that passed the Senate on Friday.
   The effort to create study commissions comes as debate is
intensifying over the need for a taxpayer bailout of the Federal
Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. Federal S&L regulators say $31
billion is required to rescue the industry. However, the General
Accounting Office, Congress' auditing wing, and others say $50
billion or more _ with at least some of it coming from taxpayers _
will be needed.
   In July, the House Banking Committee rejected another measure to
create a study commission, sponsored by Rep. Stan Parris, R-Va. St
Germain had objected, saying that Republicans would be too heavily
represented on Parris' commission.
   The 14-member St Germain commission would have six members
appointed by Democratic leaders in Congress, four by Republican
leaders and two by the Reagan administration. The next president
would appoint the remaining two.
   A St Germain aide said the legislation would likely be
introduced and acted on by the committee before the end of the week.
   The Senat bill, sponsored by Sens. James Sasser, D-Tenn., and
Bob Graham, D-Fla., would create a 12-member panel required to
report to Congress by Feb. 1. In addition to studying the S&L
crisis, the Senate committee would examine the deposit insurance
system for commercial banks.
   Meanwhile, Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady, as a step
toward developing an administration recommendation for solving the
S&L problem, has ordered Undersecretary George D. Gould to evaluate
the conflicting estimates of the cost of bailing out the industry.
</TEXT>
