<HEAD>O'Neill Faults Bush for Sinking to the Level of the ``Haters''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former House Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill, an
unabashed liberal, awkwardly came to the aid of Michael Dukakis on
Tuesday following weeks of Republican efforts to paint the
Democratic presidential nominee as a liberal.
   Republican candidate George Bush, President Reagan and others
have repeatedly called Dukakis a liberal ``out of the mainstream''
of American politics.
   ``I'm an old-fashioned liberal,'' O'Neill said in drawing a
contrast between himself and Dukakis. ``He's a progressive, he's a
technician, he's a leader.''
   At a news conference, O'Neill also chided Bush for forgetting
his roots in Massachusetts and ``slurring'' Boston in recent
remarks. Bush was born in suburban Milton, Mass.
   In the presidential debate Sunday night, Bush noted that Dukakis
called one Reagan administration program ``phony'' and added
sarcastically, ``or one of those other marvelous Boston
adjectives.''
   ``I certainly am resentful of the slurring manner he talked
about Boston _ as though we weren't Americans and didn't love our
flag and our country,'' O'Neill said.
   When asked for a response, Mark Goodin, a Bush campaign
spokesman in Washington, said, ``I think Tip should have stuck to
American Express ads. He's much more believable in that role,
rather than on the stump trying to convince people Mike Dukakis
isn't just as liberal as he is.''
