<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 2029EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     09-27 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SAfrican Police Hold Methodist Minister; Bombing in Cape Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Methodist minister was taken
from his home early Tuesday and detained by police who claimed he
violated a ban on calls for an election boycott, the clergyman's
wife reported.
   Church colleagues confirmed that the Rev. Tom Mbabane's
detention as the Methodist and Roman Catholic churches released the
text of pastoral letters urging their followers to consider
refusing to vote in nationwide municipal elections on Oct. 26.
   Also on Tuesday, a bomb exploded outside a police station in
Cape Town, damaging a door and breaking windows but causing no
injuries, police said.
   Most of the more than 50 bombings in South Africa this year have
been blamed on the outlawed African National Congress guerrilla
movement. The government says the ANC intends to step up its
bombing and sabotage campaign in the weeks leading to the elections.
   Agnes Mbabane said officers who took her 55-year-old husband
from his home at about 12:45 a.m. Tuesday in the black township of
Soweto alleged that the minister had preached against participation
in next month's elections.
   She said her husband had not advocated an election boycott but
had conveyed the Methodist Church's appeal to its congregations to
consider carefully whether they should vote.
   Methodist leaders sent out a pastoral letter saying abstention
from voting would be the only way for some voters to convey their
rejection of apartheid. The letter said, ``Only candidates who are
openly and sincerely committed to the complete abolition of
apartheid are worthy of Christian support.''
   The Southern African Catholic Bishops Conference issued a
similar letter.
   Mbabane is a regional vice chairman of the Methodist Church. The
chairman of his district, the Rev. Peter Storey, said in a
statement: ``The authorites must have taken leave of their senses
to remove someone of Mr. Mbabane's stature and integrity from
Soweto at this tense time.''
   Oct. 26 will be the first time South Africans of all races go to
the polls the same day. Anti-apartheid activists generally oppose
taking part in segregated local elections while the black majority
is excluded from full participation in national elections.
   A state-of-emergency regulation bans calls for an election
boycott, but Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu and many other
activist clergymen defied the ban.
   Apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which
South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs.
The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate
districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
