<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryMoves     09-27 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Moves,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Nominates Officers For Promotion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has nominated five generals
and admirals for promotions and announced the retirements of three
others, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
   Lt. Gen. Craven C. Rogers Jr. of the Air Force has been selected
as the next deputy chief of the U.S. Central Command, the Pentagon
said. That is the military organization responsible for U.S. forces
in the Middle East.
   Rogers, 54, is a native of Galveston, Texas, who is currently
serving as the commander of the 7th Air Force in South Korea.
   Air Force Maj. Gen. Thomas A. Baker, meanwhile, has been
nominated for promotion to the rank of lieutenant general and
ordered to replace Rogers in South Korea. Baker, 53, is a native of
Galconda, Ill., who is currently serving as the vice commander of
the Air Training Command.
   The president also has nominated Navy Rear Adm. James F. Dorsey
Jr. for a promotion to the rank of vice admiral and a new
assignment as commander of the U.S. 3rd Fleet in Hawaii. Dorsey,
54, is a native of Baltimore, Md., who is currently serving as the
assistant deputy chief of naval operations for plans, policy and
operations.
   Rear Adm. Henry H. Mauz Jr. has been nominated for promotion to
the rank of vice admiral and assignment as the next commander of
the U.S. 7th Fleet in Japan. Mauz, 52, is a native of Lynchburg,
Va., who is currently serving as the deputy chief of staff for
plans and operations with the U.S. Pacific Fleet.
   The fifth promotion involves Rear Adm. John E. Gordon, who was
nominated to receive a second star and to move to the position of
deputy judge advocate general of the Navy. Gordon, 47, is a native
of Kingston, Pa., and is currently serving as the head of the Naval
Security and Investigative Command.
   Each of the promotions will require Senate confirmation.
   The three retirements all involve naval officers. They include
Vice Adm. Clyde R. Bell, Vice Adm. Walter T. Piotti Jr. and Vice
Adm. William E. Ramsey, the Pentagon said.
   Bell will step down on Dec. 1 after completing more than 35
years of active-duty service. He is currently serving as the vice
director of the Joint Strategic Target Planning Staff.
   Piotti is retiring on Jan. 1, 1989, after completing more than
32 years of active service. He is now the head of the Military
Sealift Command.
   Ramsey is planning to retire on March 1, 1989, after completing
more than 35 years of active service. He is currently the deputy
commander of the U.S. Space Command.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
