<DOCNO> AP880927-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 2131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-USATodayEditor     09-27 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USA Today Editor,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gannett Newspaper Outlines Succession Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USA Today on Tuesday outlined its plan of
succession for the retirement of editor John C. Quinn in 1990 and
placed Peter Prichard, 43, in line to become the daily's next chief.
   John J. Curley, president of Gannett Co., Inc., USA Today's
parent company, said Quinn will move from editor to editor-in-chief
on Oct. 1. Prichard, a senior editor at USA Today, will succeed
Quinn as editor.
   In another key promotion, Curley announced the appointment of
Nancy J. Woodhull as president of Gannett News Services, a unit
that includes the Gannett News Service, a supplemental wire
service, and Gannett New Media, a research and development unit of
Gannett.
   Woodhull, 43, succeeds Quinn as president of the wire service.
   Curley said Ronald D. Martin will continue as executive editor
and vice president of USA Today. Martin has been executive editor
of the newspaper since its inception in 1982.
   Martin, 50, also was appointed to the newspaper's management
committee with responsibility for the daily direction of the
newspaper's news staff and coverage, including its cooperation with
``USA Today: The Television Show.'' He also becomes executive
editor of USA Weekend.
   Charles L. Overby, another of the top four Gannett news
executives, continues as vice president@news of the parent company.
Overby, 42, will focus his attention on the newspaper division,
working with editors of Gannett's 88 other daily newspapers,
according to Curley.
   Quinn, who will be 63 next month, will continue as Gannett's
executive vice president-news while turning over his titles as
editor of USA Today and chief of the Gannett News Service. He also
continues as a director of Gannett Co., Inc. and a member of the
Gannett and USA Today management committees.
   Prichard began his journalism career in 1970 at The Greenwich
(Conn.) Time. He joined Gannett in 1972 as a reporter at the
Rochester Democrat & Chronicle. He worked at WOKR-TV in Rochester,
N.Y., in 1975 and returned to the Rochester Times-Union in 1976.
Later, he worked on the corporate staff of Gannett before joining
USA Today in 1982.
   He is the author of ``The Making of McPaper: The Inside Story of
USA Today.''
</TEXT>
