<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Thornburgh-Justice     09-27 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thornburgh-Justice,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dispute Prompts Thornburgh to Issue Rules on Justice-Congress
Contacts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the aftermath of a dispute with three
subordinates, Attorney General Dick Thornburgh on Tuesday spelled
out requirements governing contacts by Justice Department officials
with members of Congress.
   In a memo to department officials, Thornburgh directed that all
department personnel ``observe operating procedures'' to be sent
``from time to time'' by the Office of Legislative Affairs, headed
by Assistant Attorney General Tom Boyd. Thornburgh also asked that
department employees ``carefully follow'' the office's legislative
guidance.
   ``If we are to fulfill the duties and obligations of the
Department, it is essential that we speak with one voice to
Congress,'' Thornburgh said in the memo, which was distributed to
reporters.
   ``There has been and should contiue to be vigorous internal
debate over legislative policy,'' said Thornburgh. ``However, once
policy decisions have been made, we should work together using all
of our resources.''
   The request comes a week after three agency heads went to
Capitol Hill and opposed a legislative compromise Thornburgh had
worked on to create an inspector general to investigate some
components of the Justice Department.
   In what department sources subsequently described as an angry
meeting, Thornburgh bluntly told the three to drop their opposition
to the compromise.
   The three agency heads who spoke against the compromise to Sen.
John Glenn, D-Ohio, were Stanley Morris, director of the Marshals
Service; Alan Nelson, head of the Immigration and Naturalization
Service; and Michael Quinlan, director of the Bureau of Prisons.
Their agencies would be stripped of current internal inspection and
audit powers under the legislation.
   Thornburgh had reluctantly endorsed the compromise, saying the
alternative would be a more drastic approach placing the entire
department under the scope of an inspector general's investigative
and audit authority.
   Currently, the department's Office of Professional
Responsibility investigates allegations of wrongdoing within the
department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
