<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PornProbe     09-27 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Porn Probe,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Official Investigated for Allegedly Destroying Document</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Justice Department's
anti-pornography unit is on administrative leave and under
investigation for allegedly asking a department lawyer to destroy a
document in a pending case, department sources said Tuesday.
   Acting Deputy Assistant Attorney General H. Robert Showers asked
the lawyer this month to destroy the document, according to sources
who discussed the matter on condition they not be identified.
   As a result of the allegations, Showers, who was brought into
the Justice Department by former Attorney General Edwin Meese III,
is now the subject of an investigation by the Office of
Professional Responsibility, the sources said.
   Justice Department spokesman Loye Miller would not comment.
   The pending case involves Avram Freedberg, a Stamford, Conn.,
man who owns a mail-order business promoting sexually explicit
materials, the sources said.
   Freedberg is under indictment in Utah for using the mails to
send out allegedly obscene advertising brochures, magazines and
videocassettes.
   His attorney, David Kendall of Washington, filed a motion to
dismiss the indictment last week in U.S. District Court in Salt
Lake City, Utah.
   Freedberg's motion maintains that the indictment is tainted
because the entire foundation of the prosecution is based on
information which Freedberg was required under federal criminal law
to supply to the Postal Service.
   The information consists of envelopes sent by Freedberg's
company containing allegedly obscene material which are marked
``sexually oriented advertisements.''
   In regard to data supplied under the self-reporting requirement,
Freedberg is entitled under the Fifth Amendment to immunity from
prosecution, Kendall's motion said.
   In addition to the criminal matter, Freedberg's lawyers also
filed a civil suit in federal court in Washington in May against
Showers and other Justice Department employees, alleging that the
department was threatening to bring prosecutions against them in
four jurisdictions.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson temporarily enjoined
the department in June from proceeding in more than one district.
The Utah indictment was then filed.
</TEXT>
