<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BishopRetires     09-27 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishop Retires,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maine's Catholic Bishop Steps Down, Citing Ill Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY HARKAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Most Rev. Edward C. O'Leary announced
his retirement Tuesday as bishop of the Roman Catholic Diocese of
Portland, citing health reasons.
   The announcement by the 68-year-old Bangor native came as a
surprise.
   O'Leary, who has served for 14 years as spiritual leader of
Maine's 278,000 Catholics, will continue to administer the
statewide diocese until Pope John Paul II names a successor.
   Meeting with reporters at the Catholic Chancery, O'Leary did not
elaborate on his medical condition but acknowledged a history of
blood pressure problems and said he has been on a low-salt,
low-cholesterol diet for some time.
   ``It's just the general aging process, I guess, that's caught up
with me,'' he said, adding that he consulted with medical advisers
and concluded that he was no longer able to sustain the schedule,
responsibilities and expectations of his post.
   ``People tell me now that I've never looked better. Perhaps it's
because I made the decision (to retire) that accounts for the
healthful look,'' he said.
   O'Leary declined to speculate on his successor, citing the
confidentiality of the process. It normally takes three to six
months for the pope to name a replacement, said Marc R. Mutty,
director of communications for the diocese.
   Speculation immediately focused on Maine's auxiliary bishop,
Amedee W. Proulx, who was elevated to the episcopacy in 1975,
becoming the first Franco-American bishop in the state's history
and, at 43, the youngest.
   Proulx, who was not present at O'Leary's announcement,
characterized the resignation as ``a sad loss'' for the diocese and
praised O'Leary's 42 years of service to the church.
   O'Leary was educated at Holy Cross College in Worcester, Mass.,
and St. Paul's Seminary in Ottawa. Ordained a priest in 1946, he
served in parishes in Portland, Brunswick and Old Orchard Beach,
and as diocesan vice chancellor and chancellor, before being
ordained as auxiliary bishop in 1971.
   Three years later he succeeded Bishop Peter L. Gerety, who
became archbishop of Newark, N.J.
</TEXT>
