<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Rowan-Trial 1stLd-Writethru a0661 09-27 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rowan-Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rowan Testifies He Thought It Okay To Handle Gun</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New thruout with testimony from Rowan.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columnist Carl T. Rowan testified Tuesday that
police officials told his son there would be ``no problem'' if
Rowan Sr. handled a weapon that he used to wound a teen-ager
intruding in his backyard.
   Rowan, an outspoken opponent of handgun use and possession, has
been charged with using an unregistered handgun in the June 14
shooting of an intruder in his backyard. If convicted of the
misdemeanor charges, the 63-year-old syndicated columnist could
face up to two years in prison and a $2,000 fine.
   In 1982, Rowan's son, then an FBI agent, left a .22-caliber
pistol in his father's bedroom after the columnist had received
death threats from persons purporting to be members of the Ku Klux
Klan, Rowan told a District of Columbia Superior Court jury.
   His son was told by District of Columbia police officials that
he had a ``blanket exemption'' from the city's tough handgun
registration laws because he was a federal agent, Rowan also told
the court.
   Earlier, Rowan's son, Carl Jr., testified that twice in 1982,
and once when he was preparing to leave the FBI in 1983, he was
told by police that he did not have to register weapons he had
purchased for personal use.
   After telling police that other members of his family might
handle the weapon, ``they told me that as long as (the gun) was
where it lawfully should be, if others have access to it, it isn't
a problem,'' Rowan Jr. testified.
   Rowan's attorneys have maintained that the columnist and his son
were given inaccurate advice by members of the police department's
gun control unit about the city's gun registration policy, which
stipulates that a weapon can be used only by its registered owner.
   A police official also testified that Rowan broke the law by
using the unregistered weapon, but said he should not have been
prosecuted because he apparently was defending his property.
   Police Inspector James R. Lee, introduced by Rowan's attorney as
an expert witness on gun registration matters, told the court that
Rowan was not authorized to handle the weapon used to shoot a youth
who had taken an unauthorized swim in his backyard pool.
   Lee, however, testified that he would have recommended Rowan not
be prosecuted, since a police investigation revealed that the
columnist thought he was acting in self-defense.
   Detective Charles J. Jones, who arrived at Rowan's house
immediately after the June 14 shooting, told the court that a
sliding glass door at the rear of the house showed signs that
someone had tried to force it open.
   Jones could not say when the door was damaged. Rowan had claimed
that he shot Benjamin Smith, 18, of Chevy Chase, Md., because he
was afraid Smith was trying to enter his home.
   Jones also testified that evidence indicated that the shooting
had taken place at close range, near the door.
   ``I don't see how we could be doing much better,'' Rowan's
attorney, Raoul Carroll, said after the proceedings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
