<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 2138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-State-JusticeSpending     09-27 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State-Justice Spending,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves $14.8 Billion for Judiciary, State, Commerce and
Justice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Tuesday approved a compromise
spending bill appropriating $14.8 billion for the operations of the
federal judiciary and the State, Commerce and Justice Departments
for the fiscal year starting Saturday.
   The vote was 269-141 on the measure worked out by negotiators
for the House and Senate, which previously had approved two
separate bills. The Senate has to approve the compromise bill
before it can be sent to the White House for President Reagan's
signature.
   The total is $761 million or 5 percent more than was approved
last year but $655 million or 4 percent less than the Reagan
administration's request.
   Although some agencies received major increases _ including the
Census Bureau, which is preparing for the 1990 census _ the budgets
of some others were frozen or cut back.
   These include the Justice Department's antitrust division and
the U.S. Parole Commission; the Commerce Department's Economic
Development Administration, the Minority Business Development
Agency and the Patent and Trademark Office; the State Department's
maintenance program for buildings abroad; and the Commission on
Civil Rights, the Federal Trade Commission and the office of the
U.S. Trade Representative.
   The agencies, which are required to absorb a recently approved
4.1 percent pay increase, likely will face hiring freezes,
furloughs and reductions in force.
   The overall bill has a number of provisions unrelated to funding.
   The Federal Communications Commission, for example, is required
to reverse a recent ruling and prohibit radio stations from
broadcasting obscene or profane language at any time of the day or
night. The FCC had approved so-called adult broadcasting between
the hours of midnight and 6 a.m.
   The bill also creates the new position of ``special envoy to the
Afghan resistance'' with the rank of ambassador to coordinate U.S.
policy toward Afghan resistance fighters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
