<DOCNO> AP880927-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 2138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WomanBishop     09-27 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Woman Bishop,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Female Bishop-Elect Says Reaction Positive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Barbara Harris said Tuesday she was ``a
little incredulous'' at being elected the first female bishop of
the Episcopal Church, but she believes her historic status won't
overshadow her work.
   Some members of the church have objected to bringing a woman
into the line of apostolic succession, but Episcopalian officials
said they don't expect the election will split parishes or stall
the ratification process.
   ``I have ... been elected bishop of the church and not a symbol
or a token and my whole emphasis is ... on the role to which I have
been elected,'' Harris said at a news conference at St. Paul's
Cathedral in Boston, where she was elected Saturday.
   ``I do not feel that much emphasis needs to be placed on what
some people see as the historic or symbolic significance,'' the
58-year-old Philadelphia priest said.
   A few ``no'' votes were heard when Harris was elected to the
position of suffragan, or assisting bishop, for the eastern
Massachusetts diocese, but Harris said she hasn't personally
encountered opposition.
   ``Since I have no communication with some of those groups at the
moment, I would have nothing to say.''
   Harris said she was shocked when she learned she had been
elevated from associate at the Church of the Advocate in
Philadelphia to suffragan of the nation's largest Episcopal
diocese, with 155,000 members.
   ``The reaction that I have received has been overwhelmingly
positive, from bishops, from fellow clergy, from lay people,
throughout the country,'' Harris said.
   The election touched off strong opposition in the Church of
England, which does not elect women to the priesthood.
   The Bishop of London, the Rt. Rev. Graham Leonard, has said that
he would be unable to recognize a woman bishop, but Harris said
that is not a new development.
   ``Bishop Leonard has said that for some time now,'' she said.
   The Rt. Rev. David Johnson, the bishop of Massachusetts, said
questions about how Harris would deal with opposition are
hypothetical since she has not been consecrated yet, adding that
the two would work together on overcoming any possible resistance.
   The election must be ratified by a majority of the bishops
heading the nation's 120 dioceses and a majority of the standing
committees.
   As a transitional measure, parishes have the option of
requesting that male bishops visit them if they feel they cannot
accept a woman bishop, but the request is only good for six years
and Johnson, who voted against the measure, would have to approve
it. He said he has not yet had any such request.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
