<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Adams-Sex 1stLd-Writethru a0745 09-27 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Adams-Sex, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0745,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Denies Sex Allegation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new 4th graf to identify woman, ``The woman xxx''
Inserts new 11th graf with U.S. attorney quote, ``Joseph Di Genova
xxx''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., on Tuesday branded
as ``absolutely false'' allegations that he sexually assaulted a
26-year-old woman who spent the night at his home last year.
   ``My family and I have been harassed by this woman for over a
year,'' a somber Adams told reporters in his Senate office as his
wife, Betty, stood at his side.
   Adams said the woman sought $400,000 in ``hush money'' after the
U.S. attorney declined to prosecute the case. ``I will not be
blackmailed ... I am completely outraged. These charges are
absolutely false,'' he said.
   The woman was identified by Adams and in a report she filed with
the Metropolitan Police Department as Kari Tupper, her maiden name.
She has since married George Bridges.
   But Adams, 61, a former Transportation secretary in the Carter
administration, acknowledged he made an ``error in judgment'' by
inviting the woman, who he said was a long-time family friend he
had known since her childhood, to stay at his Washington, D.C.,
house on March 27, 1987 when his wife was out of town.
   He said he offered to let her sleep over because she was ``upset
about her job and not feeling well.'' The woman lived in suburban
Virginia.
   ``Looking back, I should have called her a cab, but at the time,
the suggestion seemed appropriate,'' Adams said in a statement. He
refused to answer questions beyond the statement.
   The woman, now married and living in Seattle, filed a report
with the Metropolitan Police Department on July 24, 1987, alleging
that her breasts and buttocks had been fondled while she was in
Adams' house nearly four months earlier. Adams was not identified
by name in the report.
   She alleged that the incident took place between 9:15 p.m. on
March 27 and 6:30 a.m. the next day, according to the report.
   Capt. William White III of the District of Columbia Police said
the allegation of simple assault was investigated. ``We consider
the matter closed,'' White told the Seattle Post-Intelligencer,
which reported the story Tuesday. The U.S. attorney's office, which
prosecutes offenses in the District of Columbia, reviewed the case,
but did not press charges.
   Joseph di Genova, the U.S. attorney at the time, told the
Seattle Times, ``It was handled like any other case and nothing was
found. We reviewed and found it totally baseless.''
   The woman could not be reached and her husband refused to
comment.
   Adams gave the following account of what happened last year:
   He said the woman, whom he had helped find a job on Capitol Hill
after his election to the Senate in 1986, had asked to meet him
March 27, 1987 at a swank Italian restaurant in Georgetown to
discuss job opportunities.
   When Adams called her office that day to confirm the dinner
date, he was told she was ill. Assuming the meeting was off, Adams
said he went to play tennis with three friends.
   Later that night, the woman, upset that Adams had not showed up
at the restaurant, called him at his home to ask if she could drop
by, Adams said. The woman had visited the house in the past and had
stored belongings in the basement.
   After the woman arrived, the pair went to a neighborhood
restaurant but found it closed. Neither was feeling very well,
Adams said, so they returned to his home to get her car.
   Once there, the woman went back inside the house. ``At this
point I told her I was exhausted and was going to sleep,'' Adams
said.
   ``I told her that she was welcome to stay at the house if she
was not well enough to drive home. She said she preferred to stay
and then I went to bed, alone. I did not sexually assault the
woman.''
   The woman was a legislative assistant with the House Select
Committee on Aging in 1987 when the alleged incident occurred, the
Post-Intelligencer reported.
</TEXT>
