<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Colorization     09-27 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Colorization,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Government Board To Police Film Colorization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation signed by President Reagan on
Tuesday sets up a government board to police the practice of film
colorization.
   The bill, appropriating $10.5 billion for the Interior
Department and related agencies, sets up a National Film
Preservation Board within the department with a budget of $100,000.
   The board is to establish a national film register labeling
movies according to their cultural, historical and aesthetic
interest.
   The board would make a report in the event alterations, such as
colorization, were made in a registered film.
   If the Patent and Copyright Office found a copyright
infringement, it would be required to apply to the appropriate U.S.
attorney's office for a temporary restraining order and make
recommendations for civil proceedings.
   The Office of Management and Budget expressed concern about this
provision of the bill, saying it would inject the Patent and
Copyright Office into an area that is normally the province of the
Justice Department.
</TEXT>
