<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Britain-Iran     09-27 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Britain-Iran,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Hints Diplomatic Ties With Iran Could Come Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe of
Britain said Tuesday he will meet with Iran's foreign minister with
the intention of restoring diplomatic relations between the two
nations.
   ``Certainly we are seeking normal relations,'' he told a group
of reporters at a breakfast meeting. ``That is one of the purposes
of the meeting.''
   Asked if an announcement of restoration of relations would be
forthcoming after the meeting, scheduled for Thursday, Howe smiled
and replied: ``Watch this space.''
   Secretary of State George Shultz meanwhile said U.S. diplomats
have no plans to meet with Iranian envoys while they are in New
York during the 43rd U.N. General Assembly.
   Britain withdrew its embassy staff from Tehran last year afer an
Iranian diplomat was arrested on shoplifting charges in Britain and
after Iranian militants beat a British diplomat in Tehran, the
Iranian capital.
   But British-Iranian relations have thawed recently. London sent
a British trade officer to Tehran's trade fair this month, and
British diplomat David Reddaway visited Iran for three weeks in
August.
   Last week, Britain's Foreign Office said other likely topics of
discussion between Howe and Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of
Iran include the fate of Britons missing in Lebanon and U.N.
efforts to end the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war.
   A Foreign Office spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with
department policy, said Britain would maintain its policy of not
negotiating for the release of hostages.
   The missing Britons include Anglican Church envoy Terry Waite;
journalist John McCarthy; and teacher Brian Keenan. All are
believed held by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremists, although no
claim of responsibility has ever been made for Waite's
disappearance.
   At a news conference in New York, Shultz was asked if American
diplomats might meet with the Iranians during the General Assembly.
   ``There's no plan or nothing that I know of that would bring
such a meeting about,'' Shultz said.
   Shultz said America and Iran carry on dialogue through other
nations that take care of their interests in Washington and Tehran,
and ``We have messages that come to us from countries that are
friends of both countries almost continuously.
   ``We're certainly prepared for direct talks if the setting is
right. But as of now, there's no plan,'' Shultz said.
</TEXT>
