<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Haiti,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Rules Out Resumption of Haitian Aid Pending Developments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Tuesday it is
premature to determine whether the new government in Haiti is
entitled to a resumption of American economic aid.
   Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, Haiti's new president, told a reporter
in Port-Au-Prince on Monday that the goals of his 10-day-old
government coincide with conditions for U.S. aid.
   But State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley told reporters,
``At this time, it is premature to judge the new government of
Haiti on any'' of the conditions imposed by the United States after
it suspended a $100 million aid program when violence halted last
November's elections under the government of Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy.
   Mrs. Oakley said that since the ``failed elections,'' the United
States has made it ``clear that we cannot consider resumption of
assistance until we see concrete progress ... toward the
establishment of an elected civilian government, on economic
development designed to alleviate the plight of Haiti's poor, on
respect for human and civil rights of all Haitians and on
cooperation with the U.S. on narcotics'' traffic control issues.
   The most recent developments have been encouraging, she said,
but the emphasis will be on concrete progress. In the meantime, the
U.S. government has been providing $37 million worth of
humanitarian aid through private and charitable organizations, Mrs.
Oakley said.
</TEXT>
