<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pesticides-Streep     09-27 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pesticides-Streep,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Streep Debuts as Lobbyist, Urges Action on Pesticides</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Meryl Streep played lobbyist Tuesday
when she urged lawmakers to approve stepped up safety regulation of
2.6 billion pounds a year of chemical pesticides sprayed on crops.
   ``I'm blatantly trying to draw attention to the issue, mostly
because of the safety of my children's food supply,'' Streep told
reporters as she arrived at the office of Sen. Richard G. Lugar,
R-Ind.
   The Senate is considering legislation that would sharply
accelerate safety reviews of pesticides and the banning of those
found too dangerous for use. It would require manufacturers to pay
for the process as well as the cost of storing and disposal of
dangerous chemicals.
   So-called government indemnity payments to pesticide makers
whose products are banned _ $20 million so far _ would be ended
under the plan to reauthorize the Federal Insecticide, Fungicide
and Rodenticide Act.
   Streep expressed surprise at the pack of reporters waiting for
her at Lugar's office but took it in stride, brushing back a wave
of blond hair and saying, ``Well, hi, guys.'' A statement issued
afterward by Lugar's office, however, said she was ``startled by
press interest in her visit.''
   ``I'm obviously not a professional lobbyist,'' the statement
quoted her as saying. ``I'm just sincerely concerned on a personal
level. This is a personal project I've adopted and I'm so
interested in it that you're going to get sick of seeing me on
these issues.''
</TEXT>
