<HEAD>NASA Crew Stages Simulated Shuttle Landing Exercise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANJUL, Gambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A NASA team staged a simulated landing of
the space shuttle Discovery on Tuesday at this emergency landing
site in West Africa, mission director Bob Fleming said.
   The U.S. space agency has constructed special facilities at
Banjul International Airport, Fleming said. He said a 28-person
team was stationed at the site for Thursday's scheduled launch.
   Another 50 NASA staffers would be sent to Banjul if the shuttle
landed there, Fleming said.
   On Thursday, a team of doctors will be standing by and Gambian
firefighters and policemen will be on alert to support the NASA
staff.
   Fleming said Gambia would be the shuttle landing site if two of
Discovery's three engines failed within 2{-8 minutes of takeoff.
   He said a shuttle landing would pose no threat to nearby
residents.
   A village near the airport, Baafuloto, has demanded compensation
for trees that were felled to build a huge lamp post to guide the
shuttle to its landing area.
   The villagers refused an offer of $2,505, and NASA subsequently
said it could no longer negotiate with the villagers because it had
a contract with the Gambia government.
