<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     09-27 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>15,000 Police Sent to Troubled Region in Southern Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 15,000 policemen and law enforcement
officers have been sent to the Nagorno-Karabakh region to prevent
further ethnic violence, a government official said Tuesday.
   But he said the situation was returning to normal in
Nagorno-Karabakh, an Armenian-dominated enclave of the southern
republic of Azerbaijan that has pressed for its unification with
neighboring Armenian republic.
   The official, Vasily P. Ignatov, chief of the Interior
Ministry's organizational and inspection directorate, appeared at a
news briefing in Moscow to explain measures taken to quell the
simmering unrest.
   His comments indicated that Soviet authorities still regard the
situation in Nagorno-Karabakh as potentially explosive.
   Ignatov said 30 buildings were set afire in recent unrest there
and that a crowd in the region's center, Stepanakert, placed the
local prosecutor's home under ``virtual siege'' and broke down
doors. He did not say when the siege occurred.
   Radio Moscow reported last Thursday that protesters attacked the
prosecutor's office.
   A government spokesman said last week that one man was killed
and 48 people were injured in clashes that began Sept. 18 between
Armenians and Azerbaijanis.
   A ``special situation'' was declared last Wednesday in
Nagorno-Karabakh and in the adjacent Agdam area of Azerbaijan, a 9
p.m.-6 a.m. curfew was imposed and demonstrations were banned.
   About 600 people have been detained for curfew violations,
Ignatov said, and residents' hunting firearms have been temporarily
confiscated.
   But Ignatov said no crimes have been committed since the curfew
took effect and authorities were considering shortening it.
   The 15,000 extra law enforcement officers are mostly from the
militia, the Soviet Union's uniformed police force, Ignatov said.
He did not say whether all were sent to Nagorno-Karabakh and Agdam,
or whether some were deployed to other regions of Azerbaijan and
Armenia.
   Hundreds of troops have been reported on the streets of Yerevan,
the Armenian capital, where a general strike began Sept. 16.
   Ignatov also accused an independent pro-unification group in
Nagorno-Karabakh of trying to sow ethnic disorder.
   ``The leaders of the ... (group) provoked an attack on forces of
law and order in Stepanakert. They tried to instigate a
demonstration and spread news of so-called clashes between the
Armenian and Azerbaijani populations,'' he said.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, reported from Yerevan
that strike organizers were stopping buses to prevent people from
going to work. It said 84 people were arrested for violating laws
on rallies, marches and demonstrations.
   In Vienna, Austria, the editor of the Soviet government
newspaper Izvestia said the Soviet Union should resist strong-arm
tactics to settle ethnic disturbances in its south and in the
Baltic area.
   ``There are people who say `Look, what you have done, now it's
time to bang a fist on the table,''' Ivan D. Laptiev said in an
interview in Russian. ``But no, we will not go that way.''
</TEXT>
