<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 2144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TortureSuit     09-27 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Torture Suit,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sues Saudi Government, Claiming 1984 Torture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American engineer filed a federal damage suit
Tuesday against the Saudi Arabian government, claiming Saudi
torturers broke his back and legs in 1984 and left him permanently
disabled.
   Scott Nelson, 34, of Davie said he now walks with a cane, has
had four knee operations in the past year and was about to enter
the Duke University Medical Center in Durham, N.C., for up to
another year of treatment.
   ``This suit is going to test our laws,'' Nelson said in a
telephone interview Tuesday from an apartment he has taken in
Raleigh, N.C. ``I'm suing them for the damages from the torture I
sustained. They broke my back and my legs and never even charged me
with a crime.''
   Nelson and other Americans who said they suffered at the hands
of Saudi authorities testified before a House Foreign Affairs
subcommittee in June 1987.
   In September 1984 Nelson was an engineer for Hospital Corp. of
America, monitoring systems at the King Faisal Specialist Hospital
in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia. He told Congress that police picked him up
from the hospital security office after he complained about
hospital safety problems, but said that to this day Saudi
authorities have never explained his detention.
   ``I have no idea why,'' Nelson said. ``In four years of trying
to find out, nobody has been able to give me an idea.''
   Nelson said he was held incommunicado and tortured for 39 days.
   ``They have a unique way of torturing people,'' he said. ``They
shackle your hands and feet and make you do deep knee bends over a
rod until they hear your knees break.''
   The torture and repeated beatings left him with a shattered
knee, ruptured disks in his back and partial damage to his sciatic
nerve, leaving one leg numb. His knee was so badly damaged an
artificial one may have to be implanted to save his leg, which
suffers from poor circulation.
   ``I'm walking now, but I have to use a cane,'' he said. ``I'll
always have the cane.''
   Saudi authorities eventually released him, telling him his
detention had been a mistake, and offering him increasing amounts
of money, he said.
   Nelson said Saudi agents later threatened him and his former
attorney when he insisted on pursuing the matter with the State
Department and Congress. The threats are under investigation by the
FBI, Nelson said.
   Miami FBI spokesman Paul Miller said he could not comment on any
investigation.
   The suit, filed Tuesday in Miami federal court, accused Saudi
authorities of negligence, battery, unlawful detainment, wrongful
arrest and imprisonment, inhuman torture, disruption of normal
family life and mental anguish. It does not specify monetary
damages.
   A spokeswoman for the Saudi Embassy in Washington said she did
not have any immediate reaction to the suit.
   Jorge Duarte, Nelson's attorney, said the case seeks to apply
United Nations human rights standards and international law to the
court suit, something that has rarely been done in the United
States.
   ``We expect it to be a ground-breaking suit,'' Duarte said.
``Prohibition against torture is fairly accepted worldwide.''
   Nelson complained that U.S. authorities were of limited help. He
praised U.S. Rep. Larry Smith, D-Fla., who served on the House
subcommittee, but said the State Department lost his files after he
appeared on Capitol Hill.
   He said the federal suit against a foreign government in U.S.
courts represents his best chance to get compensation for the
torture and damage he suffered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
