<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AngolaTalks     09-27 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola Talks,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Envoy Meets Soviet; Angolans Refuse Talks With
Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa's chief negotiator, Neil
Van Heerden, met with a Soviet official Tuesday as the
Angolan-Cuban delegation studied a proposal for the withdrawal of
50,000 Cuban troops from Angola.
   Withdrawal is the key to ending hostilities between South Africa
and Angola and securing independence for South-West Africa, also
known as Namibia.
   The latest round of U.S.-mediated talks began in the Congo
capital Monday. Hopes for a settlement were high, with President
Reagan telling the United Nations he believed agreement on a Cuban
withdrawal was imminent.
   Van Heerden, director-general of South Africa's foreign affairs
department, talked with the Soviet representative in the Soviet
Embassy. Officials did not identify the Soviet observer.
   South Africa has promised to grant independence to South-West
Africa, Angola's southern neighbor, if the Cubans withdraw within a
year.
   Angola has said it would take four years to complete the
withdrawal.
   Conference sources, who spoke on the condition of not being
identified, said U.S. envoy Chester Crocker sounded out the South
Africans on an Angolan offer to send the Cubans home within three
years. Crocker, an U.S. assistant secretary of state, later met
with the Angolan-Cuban delegation to give South Africa's reply,
they said.
   Although Marxist Angola has said the Cubans were needed only to
block attacks by South African forces, Angola also has been
battling U.S.- and South African-backed guerrillas of UNITA, the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola.
   Lt. Gen. Antonio Franca, the chief Angolan negotiator, said
Tuesday that his government would not open talks with Angolan
guerrillas on ending the 13-year-old civil war.
   In South-West Africa, the South African-led territorial army
said Tuesday it had abandoned its plan to lift a 7-year-old,
dusk-to-dawn curfew in the northern war zone because of continued
guerrilla activity.
   The army said last month the curfew in Ovamboland province would
be lifted provisionally during September to see if guerrillas of
the South-West African People's Organization would observe a
cease-fire.
   It said the curfew would be lifted permanently if guerrilla
activity ceased. Military headquarters claimed, however, that 17
skirmishes and several incidents of sabotage took place since Sept.
1.
   SWAPO has fought South African rule in a struggle for
independence since 1966. South Africa has ruled the territory for
73 years.
</TEXT>
