<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-27 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Front Brings Rain, Lower Temperatures to Parts of the West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front extended from the Great Lakes into the central High
Plains on Tuesday, sending rain showers over parts of Nebraska and
Colorado.
   Other parts of the West also got rain.
   A low pressure area was expected to enhance the strength of the
front and create high winds. Gusts between 30 mph and 40 mph were
reported in parts of northeast Oregon and in Idaho and Wyoming.
   Meanwhile, showers and thunderstorms continued over parts of the
central Gulf Coast and into Florida. Over 1\ inches of rain was
reported at Pensacola, Fla.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
a half-inch at Daytona Beach, Fla., and a quarter-inch at
Grangeville, Ind.
   A high-pressure system extended over New England and the
mid-Atlantic region into the lower Mississippi Valley, with
temperatures in the 60s and 70s. A similar system extended along
the Pacific Coast into the Southwest, where highs were in the upper
80s and 90s.
   Temperatures around the country at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 44
degrees at Butte, Mont., to 100 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif. The
low in the nation Tuesday morning was 27 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   The outlook for Wednesday called for widespread rain and
thunderstorms from the Northern Plains through the upper
Mississippi Valley and upper Great Lakes region into the lower
Missouri Valley and western Oklahoma. Scattered showers were
expected in northern Maine, and afternoon showers and thunderstorms
over southern Florida.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the 70s or 80s across
much of the nation east of the Great Plains. Highs in the 50s were
forecast from the northern Plains into upper Michigan and northern
New England. Highs in the 60s were expected from the middle
Missouri Valley through the lower Great Lakes into the remainder of
New England. Highs in the 60s or 70s were forecast over much of the
West, with 90s across much of Texas and into the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
