<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Gorbachev     09-27 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Appeals to U.S., Pakistan On Afghan Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev asked the United States and
Pakistan on Tuesday to ``come to their senses'' and stop arming
guerrillas fighting the Afghan government.
   He said Pakistan was trying to install leaders in Afghanistan to
its own liking, no matter what the Afghan people want. He alleged,
in remarks carried by the official Tass news agency, that the
United States has been increasing deliveries of weapons to the
guerrillas, including Stinger missiles.
   ``Do they (Pakistan and the United States) not contradict the
spirit of the Geneva accords and the interests of a peace
settlement?'' the Soviet leader asked. ``This is a very serious
thing, and we have a right to expect Pakistan and the U.S. to come
to their senses and give up adventurist actions.''
   Gorbachev made his comments at a luncheon for visiting Laotian
leader Kaysone Phomvihane.
   Under Geneva accords signed in April, the Soviet Union began
pulling out its more than 100,000 troops from Afghanistan on May 15
and is to finish by Feb. 15. Soviet troops intervened in Marxist
Afghanistan in December 1979.
   The accords do not require a cutoff of Soviet aid to its ally,
the Afghan government, or of U.S. and Pakistani aid to Afghan
guerrillas. They do oblige the superpowers not to interfere in
Afghanistan's internal affairs, however.
   Gorbachev said problems in the Afghan settlement were an example
of a ``deficit of responsibility'' by ``some of our Western
partners.''
</TEXT>
