<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Teamsters-Carhaulers     09-27 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters-Carhaulers,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Delays Teamsters' Mailing of Ballots on New Auto Transport
Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Tuesday ordered the
Teamsters Union to wait five days before mailing out ratification
ballots on a newly renegotiated three-year contract covering some
20,000 drivers of auto transport trucks.
   U.S. District Judge Royce C. Lamberth issued a temporary
restraining order prohibiting the union from mailing the ballots
until next Monday after dissident Teamsters complained that a
``quickie'' vote would preclude them raising a campaign to defeat
the accord.
   The Teamsters had planned to mail out the ballots this Wednesday
on a new tentative contract reached with some 30 auto transport
companies late last week.
   An earlier tentative accord reached in July was rejected by 72
percent of the covered members in the union, prompting a reopening
of negotiations that resulted in last week's agreement.
   Both tentative accords provided for yearly 40 cents-an-hour pay
increases _ or 2.5 percent annually _ for drivers now making about
$16 an hour. The agreements also provided total increases of $30 a
week in employer contributions to jointly administered pension and
health funds for each covered worker.
   The renegotiated pact eliminates ``new business'' concessions
included in the earlier accord that had been opposed by
rank-and-file members and increases unloading pay in some areas of
the country.
   Lamberth issued the order in response to a petition by two
Michigan members of Teamsters for a Democratic Union, a
10,000-member dissident faction.
   The petition claimed that the union's plan to mail out the
ballots on Wednesday, six days after the new accord was announced,
was ``well-calculated to prevent opponents from obtaining enough
information about it to disseminate their views to fellow members.''
   The TDU dissidents had sought a 10-day delay, but an attorney
for them claimed victory with Lamberth's order.
   ``It's not ideal, but we'll take second best,'' said Paul Levy,
a public interest law firm attorney retained by TDU. ``If the
ballots had been mailed out tomorrow, we wouldn't have had time to
get our leaflets out.''
   The union has set the third week of October for tabulating the
ballots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
