<DOCNO> AP880927-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 2227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gibraltar-IRA     09-27 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gibraltar-IRA,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Expert Disputes Claim That Guerrillas Could Have Detonated Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An electronics expert said Monday it was
impossible for three IRA members to have set off a radio-controlled
bomb from where they were standing when British soldiers, claiming
a bombing was imminent, gunned them down.
   Michael Scott, a Dublin electronics engineer, told an inquest
that he tested various radio transmissions from the site where the
March 6 shootings occurred to a car parked about a mile away.
   British commandos have claimed that they killed the three Irish
Republican Army guerrillas, who were unarmed, because they feared
the guerrillas were about to detonate a radio-controlled bomb in a
car parked about a mile away.
   But Scott said even if the guerrillas had tried, ``as an
academic, I must say it wouldn't have happened.'' Scott said walls
and buildings would have blocked the radio signals.
   Scott's testimony came on the 16th day of an inquest by
Gibraltar Coroner Felix Pizzarello and an 11-man jury into the
March 6 shooting deaths of Mairead Farrell, 31, Daniel McCann, 30,
and Sean Savage, 24.
   The IRA has acknowledged the three were on ``active service,''
meaning they were on a mission to strike at British targets at the
time of their deaths.
   Scott's testimony countered that of a senior British
intelligence official and a bomb expert in the elite military
Special Air Service, the squad whose members killed the IRA
guerrillas. That witness said a bomb could have been detonated by
remote control.
   On Monday, a Gibraltar constable claimed that Farrell was
reaching into her purse when the soldiers opened fire. Another
witness, a Gibraltar resident who had been looking out her
apartment window, testified Friday that Farrell had been raising
her arms in surrender.
   The inquest has no power of prosecution. Its aim is to determine
whether the shootings were lawful.
   Critics of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
claimed the shootings are evidence of an unofficial
``shoot-to-kill'' policy against members of the outlawed IRA.
   The mostly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
predominantly Protestant Northern Ireland and unite it with the
Irish Republic. The March 6 killings triggered a renewed round of
IRA attacks on British soldiers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
