<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     09-27 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Arrests Alleged Leader of Coup Plot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Tuesday arrested one of the
leaders of last year's bloody attempt to topple President Corazon
Aquino and said the renegade colonel was recruiting dissident
soldiers for a new coup plot.
   Brig. Gen. Rodolfo Biazon, commander of the Manila district,
said Lt. Col. Eduardo Matillano was arrested before dawn in a raid
on a hotel in Quezon City after informants reported seeing him
dining there.
   Biazon said Matillano, former constabulary chief in Nueva Ecija
province, was the ``chief recruiter'' of right-wing military
dissidents and had been traveling throughout the country seeking to
convert soldiers to his cause.
   Matillano played a major role in the failed coup on Aug. 28,
1987, that was led by former Lt. Col. Gregorio ``Gringo'' Honasan,
who remains at large.
   Matillano led an assault on the government television station
and a hotel near armed forces headquarters during the attempt, in
which at least 53 people were killed and more than 300 were wounded.
   He was arrested a short time later and was charged with
rebellion, but escaped last April during a visit to a dentist.
Honasan was arrested last December but fled a prison ship in Manila
Bay, also in April.
   Biazon said Matillano's arrest followed the recent capture of 63
followers of deposed President Ferdinand Marcos. He said those
arrests were kept secret for security.
   He said Honasan's group apparently forged an alliance with other
renegade officers linked to Marcos, adding: ``Matillano's capture
severely cripples recent attempts by ultra-rightist elements to
destabilize the government.''
   Elsewhere, military chief of staff Gen. Renato de Villa ordered
reinforcements sent to southeastern Luzon on Tuesday after
communist rebels killed 10 soldiers and a civilian in a weekend
ambush and captured five sergeants who were carrying a unit payroll
worth up to $50,000.
   In another incident, police said Sgt. Victor Dizon was driving
to work in suburban Malabon Tuesday when four attackers fired,
killing him instantly.
   Police said the attack was similar to those used by communist
rebels, who have killed scores of police and soldiers in the
capital this year.
</TEXT>
