<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-GulfTalks     09-27 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf Talks,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stalled Gulf Peace Talks Set To Resume</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers from Iran and Iraq are
to resume direct peace talks Saturday in New York, an official
said, the first meeting between the warring nations since peace
talks fell apart in Geneva on Sept. 13.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar and a special
mediator plan to meet separately Friday with Tariq Aziz of Iraq and
Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran, said Francois Guiliani, the
secretary-general's spokesman.
   The two foreign ministers then will have face-to-face
negotiations on Saturday with Perez de Cuellar and the mediator,
Ambassador Jan K. Eliasson of Sweden, Guiliani said Tuesday.
   The talks, aimed at ending the 8-year-old Persian Gulf war,
began in Geneva on Aug. 25, five days after a U.N.-sponsored truce
took effect.
   Negotiations bogged down over Iraq's demand that the
Shaat-al-Arab waterway, Iraq's only outlet to the Persian Gulf, be
cleared of sunken ships and silt as the next step in the peace
process.
   Disputes over navigation rights in the waterway was a main cause
of the war. A 1975 treaty puts the border down the middle of the
passage, but Iraq is seeking control of the entire waterway.
   The U.N. cease-fire resolution outlining an end to the Persian
Gulf war also calls for the sides to withdraw to internationally
recognized borders, an exchange of prisoners of war, and a formal
determination of who started the conflict.
   Iraq initially endorsed the U.N. cease-fire resolution in July
1987, but Iran did not accept it until a year later, after a series
of battlefield defeats.
</TEXT>
