<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0754 09-27 0845</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0754,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Proposes Tax-Deferred Savings for Middle-Income Americans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with Bush ACLU remarks, riverboat ride,
Dukakis comments on savings proposal; EDITS to tighten.
^By TERENCE HUNT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush, criticized for
advocating tax breaks for the wealthy, proposed a plan Tuesday that
would offer tax-deferred interest to low- and middle-income
Americans on long-term savings deposits.
   Bush said such ``individual savings accounts'' would help the
nation ``gain better control over our long-term economic future''
by increasing savings.
   ``Americans have increasingly gotten away from the sensible
frugality that says, `put some away for a rainy day,''' Bush said.
   The Dukakis campaign criticized the proposal as ``pitching
pennies'' at the financial struggles of working families because it
amounted to a tax break of 40 cents a week.
   Bush unveiled the proposal before the Ohio Republican state
convention on his second visit to Columbus in 11 days. The state,
offering a prize of 23 electoral votes, is a key battleground in
the election fight.
   In a later appearance across the Ohio River in Kentucky, Bush
softened his assaults on the American Civil Liberties Union, which
have become part of his attack on Dukakis.
   ``I need to carry Ohio to win the presidency of the United
States of America,'' Bush declared earlier in the day at a rally
before thousands of cheering students at Miami University in
Oxford, Ohio.
   He was headed Wednesday to Illinois, where he will take a bus
tour.
   As described by Bush, the savings plan would allow interest to
accumulate tax deferred for funds put on deposit for at least five
years. A maximum of $1,000 a year could be deposited.
   When withdrawn, the interest would be taxed at the saver's tax
rate then in effect.
   Michael Boskin, a Stanford University economist who advises
Bush's campaign, offered this example: If a person put $1,000 into
such an account and if it paid about 8 percent annual interest,
that would yield about $80 in interest income.
   For those in the 15 percent tax bracket, that would defer some
$12 in taxes the first year, slightly more in later years. It would
cost the Treasury about $70 million in 1989 if that were the first
year in effect, growing to $550 million by 1993, Bush's campaign
estimated.
   The full interest deduction would be available only to taxpayers
with adjusted gross incomes of less than $50,000 a year. Taxpayers
with adjusted incomes of $60,000 or more would not be eligible for
the program.
   Bush's campaign staff estimated that more than 8 million
Americans would take advantage of the plan.
   ``They will be helping themselves become better able to afford a
home, pay for college or start a business, and they will be helping
America _ by increasing investment and economic growth,'' Bush said.
   Bush has been repeatedly attacked by Dukakis for advocating a
cut in the maximum capital gains tax from its current level of 33
percent down to 15 percent. Most people who pay the tax are charged
about 28 percent.
   Dukakis, speaking in a Chicago suburb, said the Bush savings
proposal would yield the average family $20 a year. ``Twenty bucks
a year, who's he kidding?'' Dukakis said.
   ``Today, after I pointed that out to him on Sunday night, he
discovered the rest of America and he told just what his priorities
are,'' he said. ``He wants to give the wealthiest 1 percent of
Americans $30,000 and the rest of us are going to get twenty bucks.
That's a new definition of trickle-down.''
   Bush campaigned later Tuesday at a rally at a riverfront park in
Owensboro, Ky., after a brief ride on sightseeing boat on the Ohio
River. When a reporter tried to ask Bush about the minimal impact
of his savings plan, the question was interrupted and drowned out
by the blaring noise of the boat's horn.
   ``Thank you very much,'' Bush said, turning away with a smile.
   Speaking before a crowd of several thousand people, Bush made a
distinction for the first time about his opposition to the ACLU,
which he uses as a device to attack Dukakis as a liberal because he
belongs to the organization.
   ``I don't have a quarrel with their work in, you know, helping
whatever position they take in terms of defending the right of an
individual,'' Bush said, ``but I just don't agree with the major
positions that organization has taken.''
   In his Columbus speech, Bush avoided any attack on Dukakis and
tried to set a tone of compassion.
   ``The answer is up to us,'' he said. ``The answer is in each
individual act of kindness multiplied by thousands and tens of
thousands. The answer is in a new engagement in the pain of
others.''
   At Miami University, Bush entertained the students with a series
of barbs aimed at Dukakis.
   Referring to a television series, Bush said, ``There's a TV show
that reminds me of what interest rates might be if the Democrats
get back in again. It's called ``thirtysomething.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
