<DOCNO> AP880927-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 2052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Egypt     09-27 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Egypt,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports: Captured Beachfront Must Be Returned To Egypt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international team of arbitrators has ruled
that Israel must return a disputed beachfront resort area to Egypt,
Israeli media reported Tuesday.
   The ruling, which has been under consideration since May 1987,
is to be announced Thursday in Geneva.
   Israel captured Taba, a beach resort along the Red Sea, in the
1967 Middle East war and retained the property when it returned the
Sinai Desert to Egypt in 1982.
   The dispute over the 250-acre area has been a key sticking point
in Egyptian-Israeli relations. The two countries signed a
U.S.-mediated peace treaty in 1979.
   Israel radio and newspapers said the arbiters, who have visited
the site and studied old maps and thousands of documents from both
sides, had decided to return all the property to Egypt.
   A Foreign Ministry official declined comment on the reports but
said Israel planned to honor whatever decision the arbiters reached.
   He noted that if Taba were returned to Egypt, some compensation
would likely have to be made to Israeli citizens who own a hotel
and a beach resort along the half-mile beachfront.
   In Cairo, Egyptian Foreign Ministry officials said President
Hosni Mubarak's government was so confident the arbiters will
decide in Egypt's favor that the ministry already was preparing a
statement to be issued after the announcement.
   A state-run trave agency in Cairo, Misr Sinai Tourist Co., has
begun advertising trips to the Taba area. ``Now Taba is the talk of
the whole world,'' said the advertisement in the English-language
Egyptian Gazette.
   In Israel, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's hardline Likud bloc
and Foreign Minister Shimon Peres' left-leaning Labor Party clashed
over Taba, an issue expected to surface in the elections campaign.
Israel's parliament elections are scheduled for Nov. 1.
   The Likud said if the decision goes against Israel, it would be
proof of its contention that Israel cannot expect a fair hearing
from an international body and should not agree to an international
conference on Middle East peace.
   ``We should not agree beforehand to the demands of the other
side,'' Likud legislator Ronnie Milo said on Israel army radio. ``I
accuse Shimon Peres and Labor officials, who threaten that if we
don't accept some demand, everything will collapse.''
   Peres, who favors an international conference, said he still
believed Israel could sign a peace treaty with neighboring Jordan
without necessarily returning all the territory it occupies, as was
the case with Egypt.
   ``I'm also not sure we had to reach such a treaty with Egypt.
But I supported it because it was the only one in the field,'' he
said on the radio in a telephone interview from New York.
   Peres is scheduled to meet with his Egyptian counterpart, Esmat
Abdel-Meguid, in New York on Thursday. The two leaders are expected
to work out how to implement the ruling.
   The five-member Taba arbitration team is made up of Swedish
chief arbitrator Gunar Lagergren, Pierre Bellet of France, Dietrich
Schindler of Switzerland, Hamed Sultan from Egypt and Ruth Lapidot
from Israel.
   Israel also captured the Gaza Strip from Egypt and the West Bank
from Jordan in the 1967 war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
