<DOCNO> AP880927-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 2302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DiplomatsStrike     09-27 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diplomats Strike,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disgruntled Diplomats Threatening Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diplomats at the French Embassy are
threatening to strike in a pay dispute, a source told The
Associated Press on Tuesday.
   French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas met in New York on Monday
with representatives of French diplomatic missions in the United
States and Canada to see whether he could defuse the problem and
dispatched an aide to talk to staff in Washington, said the source,
who refused to be identified.
   The Washington diplomats, who had planned to walk out this week,
agreed to delay any protest until after French President Francois
Mitterrand makes a one-day visit to Washington on Thursday.
   ``It has nothing to do with the visit, and they didn't want to
disrupt it,'' said the source who is close to a committee
representing staff.
   Dumas reportedly promised to look into the matter.
   Some 80 percent of the 250 embassy employees in Washington,
ranging from typists to top diplomats, already staged a walkout on
Sept. 9, and other diplomatic missions also have been involved in
the dispute, the source said.
   The protest concerns a decision to cut foreign-living allowances
by 20 percent for staffers who live in some 90 countries where
compensation is based on the value of the U.S. dollar, which has
been rising against the franc this year.
   There have been protests in other posts in North America and
elsewhere, the source said.
   Besides the embassy in Washington and mission to the United
Nations in New York, the French have 12 consulates in the United
States.
</TEXT>
