<DOCNO> AP880927-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 2056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0794 09-27 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0794,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Bush Might Cut Social Security, Medicare</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Dukakis stumble in Melrose Park, INSERTING four
grafs after 10th pvs, ``Today, in...trickle-down; EDITING
throughout to tighten.
^By WILLIAM M. WELCH</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, appealing to
``mainstream Americans,'' assailed George Bush on Tuesday as an
enemy of Social Security and Medicare who might cut both programs.
   The Democratic presidential nominee traveled to the city that
has become a symbol of middle America to combat his Republican
rival's suggestion that he is outside the nation's mainstream.
   ``If you want to see the difference between George Bush and me
on the things that concern mainstream America, look at where we
stand on Social Security and Medicare,'' Dukakis told a rally
outside Peoria's city hall.
   He said Bush had called the Medicare health plan ``socialized
medicine'' while running for the Senate years ago, and that in
1980, while a presidential candidate, Bush called Social Security
``basically a welfare program.''
   ``When it comes to Social Security and George Bush, don't read
his lips, read his record,'' Dukakis said in a remark that turned
around Bush's ``read my lips'' declaration he would not raise taxes.
   ``He was wrong then and he's wrong now,'' the Democrat said.
   Later, during a speech in the Chicago suburb of Melrose Park,
Dukakis riduled a proposal made Tuesday by George Bush to allow
small savers to sock away up to $1,000 a year and defer paying
taxes on the interest.
   ``Twenty bucks a year _ that's Mr. Bush's solution for average
Americans,'' Dukakis said referring to his campaign's calculation
of the benefits from the plan,
   ``He says it will make them, and here I'm quoting, `better able
to afford a home, pay for college, start a business,''' he said.
``Twenty bucks a year, who's he kidding?
   ``Today, after I pointed that out to him on Sunday night, he
discovered the rest of America and he told just what his priorities
are. He wants to give the wealthiest 1 percent of Americans $30,000
and the rest of us are going to get twenty bucks. That's a new
difinition of trickle-down.''
   Dukakis fell on his face when he tripped while climbing stairs
to the stage at the Melrose Park event. He got up, showed no sign
of being injured or upset, and shrugged it off when asked about it
later.
   ``It happens in every campaign at least once,'' he said.
   While there he was presented with a shirt bearing the name
Eureka College, an Illinois school that is President Reagan's alma
mater.
   On the back were the words, ``We like Dutch but we love the
Duke.''
   Seeking to encourage the notion that he had tightened the
presidential race with a strong debate performance two days
earlier, Dukakis escalated his assault on Bush's views on Social
Security and Medicare.
   The Massachusetts governor repeatedly referred to his debate
performance, asking the Peoria crowd ``How many of you thought I
won?'' and drawing a thunderous cheer.
   He said Bush ``said our family farms must be doing just fine''
in the debate.
   ``He must be kidding,'' Dukakis said, saying there were 200,000
family farms and half a million farm-related manufacturing jobs
lost in eight years.
   Dukakis said both Social Security and Medicare were likely
targets for Bush to cut to finance additional defense spending and
to offset a cut in the tax on capital gains, a tax break Dukakis
contended would primarily benefit the wealthy.
   He recalled Bush's tie-breaking Senate vote to cut
cost-of-living increases for Social Security, and repeated his
suggestion that Bush might tap the Social Security trust fund.
   ``Now, if Mr. Bush wants another tax give-away for the rich, and
if he can't think of a single weapons system in the budget that he
opposes ... and if he says he's going to bring down the deficit,
then how's he going to do it without raiding the Social Security
trust fund and trying to cut Social Security and Medicare again?''
Dukakis said.
   ``My friends,'' he added, ``Social Security is not a `welfare
program.' Social Security is a contract between generations, and
... I will never break that contract.''
   Dukakis campaigned in Illinois, a tossup industrial state, a day
before Bush was taking an eight-hour bus trip across the state.
   Dukakis appeared with former Democratic rival Sen. Paul Simon in
Peoria, the city recalled in political memory for the Nixon
administration's reference to it as a barometer of middle America.
</TEXT>
