<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Touts Democrats' Economic Skills</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, From Detroit...Omaha, Neb., with five
grafs to UPDATE with Kansas City appearance, picking up 9th pvs,
Bentsen told...debtor nations.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen told Michigan business leaders
Tuesday that with Republican George Bush at the helm, the American
economy would sail into ``the Bermuda Triangle of debt, deficit and
dependence.''
   The Democratic vice presidential candidate said he and Michael
Dukakis were tough, experienced economic managers who would tackle
U.S. trade and budget deficits and _ unlike Bush _ would strictly
enforce the new trade law aimed at opening up foreign markets to
American products.
   The Texas senator began a four-day campaign swing with a visit
to this key industrial state, where public opinion polls have shown
a close race between Bush and Dukakis with 20 electoral votes at
stake.
   ``Mike Dukakis and I both have a long record of success when it
comes to dealing with the economy,'' Bentsen told the Detroit
Economic Club.
   ``Mike took a state that was an economic basket case and turned
it around. ... As a businessman, as a senator and as chairman of
the Finance Committee I have made it a point to look for honest,
bipartisan effective answers to America's economic problems.''
   He touted Dukakis' call for expanded public-private partnerships
and said promised an activist Democratic president willing to
listen closely to the needs of business and industry.
   By contrast, he said, the Reagan-Bush administration has stood
idly while the United States lost its edge in research and
development of new products and deficits piled up, leaving the
nation reliant on foreign bankers to finance its debt.
   From Detroit, Bentsen went to Kansas City, Mo., where he
criticized Republican vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle for
leading the unsuccessful opposition to a law giving workers 60
days' notice before they are laid off.
   ``But Dan Quayle lost the fight against plant closing and the
American people won,'' Bentsen told an airport crowd of about 250.
``We're going to open the Quayle season a little early this year.''
   Bentsen also applauded Dukakis' performance in his Sunday debate
with George Bush.
   ``He finally got George Bush out of that flag factory and
talking about the issues,'' he said.
   Bentsen was spending the remainder of night preparing for the
debate next week in Omaha, Neb. He had several briefing books with
him.
   Bentsen told the Detroit business leaders that since President
Reagan took office eight years ago, the federal budget deficit has
nearly tripled, the trade defict has grown to nearly a
half-trillion dollars and the United States has been transformed
from the largest lending nation to the largest debtor nation.
   ``Those are the facts and as President Reagan has suggested,
facts are stubborn things,'' Bentsen said. ``To me and to Mike
Dukakis, the facts suggest that staying the course, putting this
country on automatic pilot, is not an acceptable thing. Not when
the course leads to the Bermuda Triangle of debt, deficit and
dependence.''
   He said U.S. trade representative Clayton Yeutter has been
``putting out the word that if George Bush wins this election you
won't see any change, they're not going to provide rigorous
enforcement of that trade bill ...''
   Said Bentsen: ``That would be a disaster for America _ and no
city knows it better than Detroit.''
   Tailoring part of his speech to blue-collar workers, Bentsen
said income in Michigan has grown slower than the national average
and domestic car production has fallen during the economic recovery
that Reagan brags about.
   Bentsen is to visit President Truman's birthplace at
Independence, Mo., on Wednesday and deliver a speech that aides
said would compare his credentials for the vice presidency with
those of Quayle, 41, an Indiana senator.
</TEXT>
