<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0672 09-27 0842</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0672,0867</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital Reports Deaths By Plastic Bullets; Rabin Defends Use</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout UPDATES with television
report of snipers firing plastic bullets; six more reported
wounded; other. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIT EL, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hospital authorities on
Tuesday reported the first three deaths of Palestinians from the
army's newly introduced plastic bullets, which have stirred
controversy and drawn a U.N. protest.
   The army confirmed the deaths, all in the Gaza Strip, but said
in all three cases it still was checking to determine the cause of
death.
   The Palestinian hospital officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity for fear of retribution, have proven reliable in the past
in providing information on Palestinian casualties.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin on Tuesday defended plastic
bullets as a useful tool in dealing with violence in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip and acknowledged they could increase
casualties.
   ``The plastic bullet is intended to hit stone throwers,
organizers and inciters of demonstrations, outside the range of the
rock,'' Rabin told a news conference at a military camp in Beit El,
about 12 miles north of Jerusalem.
   ``The fact that there are more casualties among the rioters for
the same number of disturbances _ that is exactly our aim.''
   Rabin's comments indicated a change in the army's firing rules.
Soldiers previously could not fire tear gas and rubber bullets at
protesters unless their lives were threatened. In a
life-threatening situation, the soldiers could use regular lead
bullets.
   These were the deaths blamed by hospital officials on plastic
bullets:
   _Osama Braikah, 17, of Gaza's Khan Yunis refugee camp, died
after a plastic bullet pierced his heart Tuesday during a clash
with troops in the camp, said an official at nearby Nasser Hospital.
   An army official confirmed the death but said he did not know if
a plastic bullet was the cause. He acknowledged plastic bullets
were used to break up a stone-throwing mob Tuesday at Khan Yunis.
   _Aiman Abu Sharar, 17, died in Gaza's Nuseirat refugee camp
after soldiers shot him in the chest Tuesday with a plastic bullet,
hospital officials said.
   The army confirmed the death and said plastic bullets were
probably used in Nuseirat, but that it could not give the exact
cause of death.
   _Jihad Zanoun, 27, of Gaza City, died Monday after he was hit in
the chest by a plastic bullet, doctors at Shifa Hospital said.
   The army confirmed Zanoun's death and said it was checking
whether he was shot by a plastic or a standard lead bullet.
   A fourth shooting death was reported Tuesday, but officials
could not say whether Hussam Gharbawi died from a plastic bullet or
lead bullet. Gharbawi was wounded in clashes in Gaza Monday and
died Tuesday in Tel Hashomer Hospital near Tel Aviv, the army and
Arab reports said.
   The deaths raised to 278 the number of Palestinians killed since
their uprising began on Dec. 8. Six Israelis also have died.
   On Tuesday, at least 26 Palestinians were wounded in clashes
with Israeli troops in the occupied lands, hospitals reported.
   The army said two injuries were confirmed and other reports were
being checked.
   The latest casualties followed an upsurge of violence in the
occupied lands Monday that left two other Palestinians dead and at
least 67 wounded. The violence accompanied a general strike in the
territories to protest Israeli imprisonment of Palestinians. Israel
took the territories from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
war.
   The plastic bullet has greater range and impact than rubber. Its
introduction last month sent Arab casualties soaring and drew calls
for limiting its use.
   The U.N. Relief and Works Agency, which aids Palestinian
refugees, protested to the army, noting that woundings in the Gaza
Strip alone jumped from 19 in July to 130 in the first 25 days of
September.
   A senior U.N. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
casualties ``have risen to an unacceptable level'' and that growing
use of plastic and lead bullets ``cannot be justified.''
   Rabin said his job was to reduce violence _ ``Other protests,
with all due respects, are of secondary importance to me.''
   Israel television said snipers fired plastic bullets after
troops first fired in the air. ``In several cases, the use of
plastic bullets in an improper manner and against the orders has
caused fatalities,'' it said, without elaborating.
   An army spokesman said standing orders were that plastic bullets
were fired only by specially trained officers and aimed at the
legs, but he could not confirm the procedure was fulfilled in every
case.
   Dr. Elias Artin of Gaza City's Ahli Arab Hospital said in an
interview that plastic bullets tended to do less damage than lead
bullets but could kill.
   ``They can kill if they hit the chest, abdomen or neck,'' he
said. ``If they hit a nerve, they can paralyze.''
   He said he treated several patients with wounds to the central
body. ``One patient took six plastic bullets, one in the abdomen,''
Artin said.
</TEXT>
