<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Panama     09-27 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Panama,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Acting President Claims U.S. Seeks Overthrow Of Panamanian
Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's acting president, Manuel Solis
Palma, told the General Assembly Tuesday that U.S. drug charges
against Gen. Manuel Noriega are false and part of a U.S. attempt to
extend its control of the Panama Canal.
   Solis Palma said Panama was waging a battle against narcotics
traffickers. Noriega and Panama were victims of a U.S. propaganda
war that could turn into armed conflict, he declared.
   Ambassador Vernon A. Walters, the chief U.S. representative to
the United Nations, described Solis Palma's allegations as lies
``against the United States by Gen. Noriega's hand-picked chief of
state.''
   Noriega, head of Panama's 15,000-member Defense Forces, is
considered the real power behind the civilian government headed by
Solis Palma.
   In Panama, a government official said 26 activists arrested last
week were planning to overthrow Noriega under a U.S.-devised plot.
   The Noriega-controlled National Assembly named Solis Palma as
Panama's chief executive in February, after ousting President Eric
Arturo Devalle. The United States still recognizes Devalle as
president.
   Noriega was indicted in Florida last February on federal drug
trafficking charges and Devalle attempted to fire him. Noriega
denies wrongdoing.
   Solis Palma told the General Assembly, ``I say that the whole
campaign ... is nothing other than a sinister tissue of lies and
falsehoods carried out by the United States government.''
   The purpose of the attack is to overthrow the government and
impose another ``committed to renegotiation'' of the Panama Canal
treaty, he said.
   Under provisions of that treaty, the United States agreed to
relinquish operational control over the canal on Dec. 31, 1999.
   The United States has frozen millions of dollars in Panamanian
assets and witheld millions of dollars more in aid to force Noriega
from power.
   Solis Palma warned that hostile U.S. economic moves might turn
into war.
   ``My government has more than enough reason to fear direct
military aggression by the United States against Panama,'' he said.
   Walters denied charges of impending invasion and said Panama
``was already a seriously troubled economy.''
   Walters said he stayed away from Solis Palma's speech to
emphasize that the United States does not recognize him as
president.
   Col. Guillermo Wong, head of the Panamnian army's G-2
intelligence unit, presented a six-page document to reporters in
Panama City on Monday which he said security agents discovered
while arresting 26 opposition activists.
   He said the document, which urged making contacts with
dissidents and releasing anti-Noriega propaganda, was written by
U.S. officials and proved U.S. involvement in efforts to oust
Noriega.
   Terrence Kneebone, a U.S. Embassy spokesman in Panama City,
dismissed the allegation as ``absurd'' and said it was designed
``to divert attention from Panama's political problems.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880927-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 2339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YellowstoneFires     09-27 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yellowstone Fires,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marines Prepare To Head Out Of Yellowstone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marines who were called
in to help fight fires in Yellowstone National Park this summer
began leaving Tuesday, and officials expressed concern that gusting
winds might whip flames across containment lines.
   An approaching cold front increased wind speeds at the park
Tuesday afternoon.
   ``With the winds, there's always concerns about fire activity,''
said park spokeswoman Sandy Robinson.
   One area on the 107,500-acre Wolf Lake fire that firefighters
worried about was along the western edge of the Grand Canyon of the
Yellowstone.
   ``They're watching for spots on the other side because the
eastern slope of the canyon is heavily timbered,'' said Robinson.
``So they obviously do not want the fire in that area because of
the potential for spreading.''
   Elsewhere in Yellowstone, little activity was reported on the
400,100-acre North Fork fire that earlier this month swept around
the Old Faithful Geyser complex. Although fire managers were
concerned about the strong winds, they said higher humidity levels
would help keep the flames in check.
   ``There were a few hot spots in the Mary Lake area, and they had
firefighters camping out last night at spike camps,'' said
Robinson. ``But today all firefighters have been brought into the
base camps because of the wind and cold weather.''
   Still, conditions improved enough in the past few days to allow
640 Marines to pack up their gear for the return trip to California.
   About 500 civilian firefighters remained.
   Officials estimate that since the fires began, as much as 60
percent of an area covering more than 1.6 million acres of
Yellowstone and surrounding national forests has been burned.
   To the east of Yellowstone in the Shoshone National Forest,
firefighters were attacking a section of the 413,410-acre
Clover-Mist fire that Monday had slopped over the border into
Montana.
   ``They've pulled most of the crews from the mop-up effort
(elsewhere on the Clover-Mist) to try to corral that fire,'' said
spokesman Tom Mitchell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
