<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0685 09-27 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Kuwaiti Tanker Sails Under New U.S. Escort Policy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs after 5th graf pvs, Iran is ... UPDATING with
Iran claims north gulf clear of mines. Picks up 6th graf pvs, U.S.
warships ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tanker to
sail without a close escort of U.S. warships left Kuwait Tuesday,
heading south through waters where three mines have been discovered
in the past five days.
   Although traveling alone, the 81,283-ton oil products carrier
Surf City would not be unprotected should trouble arise, U.S.
military sources said.
   ``She's on her way, and will be under surveillance at all
times,'' said one source, insisting on anonymity. Attacks on
commercial shipping stopped Aug. 20 when Iran and Iraq declared a
cease-fire in their 8-year-old war.
   However, fears of mines were heightened with reports that
Italian mine-hunters found an explosive device floating in the
south-central Persian Gulf _ the third such discovery in five days
and the fifth since Aug. 19.
   Iran is considered responsible for virtually all gulf mines.
   Iran's navy commander said Tuesday that Iran's territorial
waters in the northern gulf are cleared of mines, as are major
parts of the international waters, the official Islamic Republic
news agency reported in a dispatch monitored in Nicosia, Cyprus.
   IRNA quoted Rear Adm. Mohammed-Hussein Malekzadegan as saying an
Iranian warship and two guided missile boats arrived in the
northern gulf ports of Imam Khomeini and Mahshahr after clearing
the shipping channels in Khur Musa of mines. Khur Musa is the
extended bay leading to the two ports.
   U.S. naval experts estimate that about 200 mines remain in the
gulf.
   U.S. warships were to monitor the Surf City's two-day passage
from patrol stations along the 550-mile track through the gulf and
the Strait of Hormuz.
   The missile frigate USS Vandegrift trailed the tanker at a
distance, but for the first time no warship was sailing in ``close
convoy'' with it, the sources said.
   The unescorted voyage reflected President Reagan's decision,
announced Monday, to scale back the Navy's role in the escort
program.
   The close-quarter convoy operation formally ended Monday, when
the USS Vandegrift delivered the 294,739-ton supertanker Townsend
to Kuwait after escorting it through the gulf.
   That movement was the 67th this year and the 89th since July
1987, when Washington agreed to reflag 11 Kuwait-owned tankers to
protect them from Iranian attack.
   U.S. officials say its first ocean convoy operation since World
War II proved successful by assuring the export of billions of
barrels of Kuwaiti petroleum products.
   Some U.S. diplomats and officials say it also forestalled Soviet
efforts to gain greater influence in the waterway that provides
nearly 20 percent of the non-communist world's petroleum.
   Kuwait's support for Iraq made its shipping a special target of
Iranian gunboats during attacks. The White House said reduced
tensions made possible the Navy's reduced role.
   Administration officials say the new policy might allow the
withdrawal of one ship. The 26-member fleet now includes 16 in the
gulf and a carrier battle group in the Arabian Sea.
   The missile cruiser USS Vincennes was withdrawn earlier this
month and was not replaced.
   The Pentagon also has curtailed air patrols and other escort
activities. That cost had been estimated by U.S. officials at $20
million a month.
   Nine Americans were killed in helicopter and jet crashes during
the operation.
   Other incidents included the mining of the supertanker Bridgeton
in the first convoy July 24, 1987, an Iranian Silkworm missile
attack that disabled the tanker Sea Isle City at Kuwait, and the
near-sinking of the frigate USS Samuel B. Roberts by a mine April
14.
   The U.S. forces retaliated, wrecking two oil platforms and
sinking or damaging six Iranian naval craft in an attack April 18.
   On July 3, the Vincennes mistook an Iranian jetliner for an
attacking military jet and shot it down, killing all 290 aboard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
