<2ND_LINE>AM-Building Collapse, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0765,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Apartment Building Collapses, 2 Dead, Four Trapped</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with four
believed trapped. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A six-story apartment building on a
steep hillside collapsed Tuesday, killing a man and his baby son
and leaving at least four people trapped in the rubble, officials
said.
   Authorities said the building may have been weakened by
Hurricane Gilbert, which hit this northern industrial city on Sept.
17 and caused widespread flooding that killed at least 140 people
in the area.
   At least four people were rescued after the collapse, said state
prosecutor Alejandro Garza Garza.
   A woman, her clothes torn and covered with blood, was pulled
from the debris. She told rescuers someone else was trapped there.
As she was carried away on a wooden stretcher a man ran up, took
off his shirt and said: ``Here my daughter, take this.''
   Juan Francisco Rivera, the attorney general of Nuevo Leon state,
identified the woman as Maria Eugenia Gonzalez de Rodriguez, about
26, wife of the man who died and mother of the dead baby.
   Rivera said at least four people were believed still inside the
building. Earlier, he said five people were believed trapped, but
officials later determined that the sixth floor had been empty when
the building collapsed.
   Rivera reported that he called off all but 10 of the 100
rescuers at 1:30 p.m. because of dangerously shifting rubble.
   ``The movement could be dangerous for those who are alive,''
Rivera said. ``We are trying to approach it more technically.''
   Garza identified the dead man as Antonio Rodriguez, 25 to 30
years old, and said he did not know the name of the baby boy.
   The lower floors of the 3-year-old building pancaked atop one
another but the top three levels slid about 250 feet down the
hillside. The rubble stood about one story high, with mattresses,
clothing, furniture and crushed air conditioners half buried.
   The building, in a wealthy area of the city, was one of the
highest structures in Monterrey.
   Francisco Javier Nakashima, an investigator with the state
judicial police, said heavy rains from Hurricane Gilbert must have
contributed to the collapse. He said the structure was reported
leaning to one side six months ago.
   Ruben Salinas Garcia, 27, who was in his second floor apartment
at the time, said he didn't realize what was happening until the
building was falling.
   ``I woke up and the roof was on top of me,'' he said at the
scene. He said his maid apparently still was trapped inside the
builidng.
   His face and pink T-shirt were covered with blood and a bandage
covered his chin.
</TEXT>
