<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gangs-Vietnamese     09-27 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gangs-Vietnamese,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Immigrant Gang Members Robbing Neighborhood Homes and Businesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young Vietnamese immigrants robbing homes and
businesses are part of a growing wave of gang violence up and down
the Pacific Coast, authorities say.
   One gang police broke up last year had robbed as many as 50
Vietnamese families, and even more violent groups have since
emerged, Detective Jim Bryan said.
   ``These are brand-new, newly identified, never-before-heard-of
Vietnamese gangs. It's going to be a continuing problem,'' Bryan
said. ``It's the same thing as last year, but they're getting more
violent now. They're pistol-whipping people.''
   The Vietnamese gangs are emerging at a time when Los Angeles
authorities already have a full-time war on their hands against
well-established Hispanic and black gangs.
   Gang violence over the weekend claimed the lives of four people
and left seven others wounded, including two pregnant women.
   The Vietnamese robbers range in age from 15 to 25 and usually
are either runaways or juvenile parolees or delinquents on
probation, Bryan said.
   In a June 23 Vietnamese gang attack, 30-year-old Thang Vo
survived several gunshot wounds. His assailant and three other
robbers tied up a wounded Vo, his wife, brother-in-law and a family
friend, while Vo's three young children were left untied.
   The robbers, known to police as ``Dracula's Group,'' then sat
down to eat lunch in Vo's kitchen.
   ``They ate lunch while (Vo) was lying there bleeding,'' Bryan
said. ``He's lucky he lived.''
   Another Los Angeles-based group of Vietnamese immigrants is
suspected of committing at least a dozen robberies, from here to
Portland, Ore., and Seattle, police said.
   ``We've got so much activity with these guys now that it's hard
to even track it anymore,'' said Portland police officer David
Hauck.
   A continuing problem in Portland is a reluctance of victims to
report crimes out of fear of retaliation, Hauck said.
</TEXT>
