<DOCNO> AP880927-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a AM-GatesofHellI ADV02-2Takes   09-27 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gates of Hell I, ADV 02-2 Takes,0791</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Part I: Deliverance</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto, LaserLogo</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   For a decade, in a bucolic corner of
Mississippi, the Rev. Herman Fountain ran his Bethel Home for
Children. From time to time, tales of abuse circulated, but nothing
came of them _ Mississippi is one of six states where such church
homes are unlicensed and rarely scrutinized. But as this summer
began, a boy's tale of beatings, neglect and imprisonment brought
state authorities to Bethel's door and ignited a conflict fueled by
outrage from both sides. ``Gates of Hell'' is the story of these
children, who have been given pseudonyms to protect their
identities as required by Mississippi law, of their lives inside
Bethel and of the emotional struggle over their futures _ and their
souls. This is the first installment of three.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``A wise man feareth, and departeth from evil ...'' _ Proverbs
14:16, from a sign on a building at the Bethel children's home.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LISA LEVITT RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The time had come. Patrick was ready. He
would hide and wait, and when the moment was right, he would blow
through the gates of hell and never look back.
   Quietly now, quietly. He slipped inside the locker and waited,
hardly breathing. The other kids at the Bethel Home for Children
were filing past, on their way to church.
   Patrick opened the locker door. To the bicycle by the steps.
Carefully now, carefully. If anyone saw, he would be caught, and
there'd be more punishment, more pain, more humiliation.
   No more. He'd had enough for a lifetime.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Kathy Prine had just finished stabling her horse when the phone
rang Sunday, May 8. It was after 7 p.m.
   As a child welfare investigator in George County, she was used
to calls at all hours, seven days a week. It was the sheriff's
office: another runaway from Bethel. That wasn't unusual. The
Baptist church home's 10-year history was rife with kids trying to
escape its rigorous regimen.
   Prine had dealt with some of Bethel's children but had never
seen the operation firsthand. Because the state does not license
its church-run boarding homes, and therefore cannot regulate them,
it rarely ventures in.
   Among those who have, some call them hospitals for the soul;
others consider them spiritual torture chambers.
   The truth about the Bethel Home for Children was a matter of
opinion.
   In 1980, a runaway brought assault charges against Bethel's
founder, the Rev. Herman Fountain, for a beating he received with a
switch _ ``licks,'' Fountain called them. After a hearing, the
Youth Court judge removed all the children and directed the church
to follow certain regulations. But the charges were dropped and the
order was never enforced. Many of the children were returned to
Bethel.
   Since then, other children had run away, and others told stories
of abuse and neglect. But few had been at Bethel long enough to be
credible witnesses, the kind whose stories would hold up in court.
   Now there was Patrick.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   He had come to Bethel in October 1986 at age 13, a sometime
truant sent from Florida by his mother.
   Life might have been hard at home, but Bethel was like boot camp
with a wrathful God as drill sergeant. Patrick's description was
the same as those of other children and that of Herman Fountain
himself.
   Each day had a schedule: up at 5 a.m., so many minutes in the
bathroom, so many minutes to dress, so many to clean the dormitory.
There were prayer sessions morning and evening.
   In the summers, the children picked beans, pulled weeds on the
church's 28 acres, dug ditches, picked up trash and cared for
Bethel's menagerie of goats, horses, ducks and deer. Sometimes
crews of children would tear down abandoned buildings, including
some at Keesler Air Force Base in Biloxi, and return with what they
salvaged to Bethel, where it would become part of new structures
they built themselves.
   There was no payment for work, but plenty of punishment for
slackers.
   In the winters, they had Bible memorization and school. Lessons
came from religious workbooks. Often, children had to erase other
children's answers to fill in their own.
   Like every new Bethel charge, Patrick spent his first month ``on
watch'' under the eye of more trusted child. Children on watch were
allowed to speak only to designated individuals. It was a way to
prevent them from planning escapes. Talking on watch meant sure
punishment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880927-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a AM-GatesofHellI ADV02-1stAdd   09-27 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gates of Hell I, ADV 02-1st Add,0739</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LUCEDALE: sure punishment.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   There were no calls to parents for the first two months, and no
visits for the first six.
   Incoming mail was opened and money was removed. Letters home
that complained about Bethel were ordered rewritten. Telephone
calls, when allowed, were monitored.
   Meals were heavy on oatmeal, grits and rice. At the end of the
week, leftovers were mixed together, a meal the kids called
``compost stew.'' Failure to eat everything on the plate brought
punishment.
   No cigarettes, drugs, alcohol or carbonated drinks were allowed.
There was no television, no radio, no movies: these worldly media
were of the devil. So were newspapers, magazines and most music,
except certain religious selections. At night, trusted children
guarded the doors against runaways. No one was allowed out.
   This was the program, steeped in fundamental religion, rooted in
biblical principles and imbued, its supporters said, with the
Lord's power to change incorrigibles into God-fearing, clean-living
Christians. And anyone who deviated from it, in word, deed or
spirit, learned a lesson about pain.
   Patrick had learned those lessons well.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Mark Maples questioned Patrick closely. Maples had been George
County prosecutor only since January, but he had already
interviewed several former Bethel children.
   The 30-year-old Maples had grown up in George County, and he
knew a little about Bethel. In a town the size of Lucedale, with
2,500 residents, it was hard to avoid. Some days at lunchtime,
Bethel preachers stood out on Main Street, hollering about hell and
damnation to passersby.
   That usually prompted stories from the patrons at the nearby
Coffee Pot restaurant, but mostly they left the subject alone.
After all, they figured, none of the kids out there was local; they
probably were bad kids who deserved what they got.
   Now this boy was telling Maples stories as awful as any he had
heard. It would take testimony from those who'd left earlier and
knew Patrick, and two more who would leave after his escape, to
corroborate his treatment from the day he arrived to the day he
fled Herman Fountain.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   In 1969, Fountain was a heroin addict dabbling in witchcraft. He
had forsaken his native Oklahoma for the streets of New York; in
three years, he says, he lost his family and his health, ending up
in a Queens hospital with hepatitis from shooting up with a dirty
needle.
   Then he found the Lord.
   Born again, he won back his family and went off to bible college
in Pensacola, Fla., later moving to Corpus Christi, Texas, to join
the ministries of the Rev. Lester Roloff, an evangelist who ran a
well-publicized home for troubled children before his death in a
1982 plane crash.
   Fountain felt the call to begin his own ministry and his own
children's home, and in 1978, he, wife Carol, and seven children
pulled into Lucedale.
   His Bethel Baptist church and children's home thrived. At one
point, as many as 150 children were on campus. Parents who could
afford it paid $275 a month plus $750 for materials and
registration. Some paid less. Some paid nothing.
   It didn't matter to Fountain. The Lord had called him for this
work.
   The state had tried to shut him down in 1980 and failed. Six
years later, the welfare department raided the Bethesda Home for
Girls in Hattiesburg, run by his friend, the Rev. Bob Wills, and
Wills' wife, Betty Sue.
   The 113 girls taken from the home spoke of strip-searches,
paddlings and starvation diets. One-fourth of the girls reported
missing their menstrual periods for two months to a year _ the
result, Mrs. Wills forthrightly explained, of stress brought on by
much-needed discipline.
   Discipline. That was the key to a spiritual life, the Willses
believed, and Fountain agreed wholeheartedly. Children needed
discipline. It said as much in the Bible, and his charges knew
Proverbs 23:13 by heart:
   ``Do not withhold correction from a child,
   For if you beat him with a rod, he will not die.
   You shall beat him with a rod
   And deliver his soul from hell.''
   That was Fountain's calling: delivering young souls from hell.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NEXT: Revelations</HEAD>
