<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-KidsofBethel ADV03   09-27 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kids of Bethel, ADV 03,0833</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Oct. 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Many Bethel Kids Abandoned by Parents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Gates of Hell II</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA LEVITT RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the children of Bethel are human
throwaways, tossed out by parents who no longer want to deal with
them or no longer know how.
   Some of the kids have no parents. Others simply feel as if they
don't.
   ``I would phone,'' said 12-year-old Joshua, clutching his
red-leather Bible. ``But they wouldn't accept my calls.''
   The children, whose names have been changed to meet Mississippi
law about juveniles' identities, came from across the nation, with
the majority from Texas, Florida, Arizona and Washington. Some had
physical or mental disabilities such as hyperactivity or Down's
syndrome. Some had emotional problems, drug or alcohol habits or
had been in trouble with the police.
   Others were typical teen-agers experiencing the upheaval of
adolescence, and all the confusion and rebellion that comes with
growing up.
   Scott, adopted at age 7 by people who later changed their minds,
bounced in and out of foster homes for years. His last family sent
him to Bethel two years ago. ``My parents had written me after I
was there for a while and said the reason I was there was because
they didn't have the facilities to handle me and take care of me.
   ``They wanted someone who would take the responsibility on them
of bringing me up right. My parents never really wanted me.''
   Freed from Bethel by the state, Scott earned his GED equivalency
certificate (because the Bethel school is unaccredited, its
diplomas are not recognized by any state) and applied for
cosmetology school. He began dating Stephanie, another former
Bethel resident, and they plan to marry someday and raise a family.
Both say Bethel taught them how not to treat children.
   ``I'm not going to have my kid switched every second he acts
up,'' Scott said. ``I'm going to make sure I can deal with it.''
   ``I'd try to work out any problems with my child,'' said
15-year-old Stephanie, who wants to be a teacher. ``If that didn't
work, I'd keep on trying. I'd never give up. I'd never send them to
a place like Bethel.''
   Scott and Stephanie are in counseling now, as are all the Bethel
children in state custody. Months and months of being told that the
outside world is Satan's playground, that saying, thinking, doing
or feeling certain things will send them straight to hell, has left
many confused and fearful.
   But for others, Bethel is salvation. Outsiders don't understand
what they were, what they've become, and what they went through
along the way. One after the other they will say they deserved the
whippings they used to get, but they don't deserve the bad rap
they're getting now.
   These are Fountain's success stories, followers like Sophia, who
call the pastor ``Daddy.'' Arriving at Bethel in 1985 was like
landing on another planet for the rebellious 16-year-old street
veteran from Boca Raton, Fla., a drug abuser and runaway who
frequented every tavern's ladies night in town.
   ``I thought these people were crazy,'' she recalled. ``I got
smart to Brother Fountain, and he said, `I'm going to bust your
bottom!' He showed me a switch. I thought, `A twig! What's that
going to do?'''
   She soon found out. Back talk to the dorm leader ended in a
brawl broken up by Brother Owens and his switch.
   ``He smacked me around,'' Sophia said. ``It's the first spanking
I ever got. And whoa! I knew they meant business. I was cussing up
a storm.''
   The head leader slapped Sophia's face, and when Brother Fountain
came back, he slapped her, too.
   ``I said, `Go ahead and kill me.' Everything had been drained
out of me,'' she said. ``All that rebellion that I had built up for
16 years of my life was gone. The devil really was beat out of me.''
   She spent a week in the revival room, a small, windowless room
used to isolate disruptive children, where two girls pointed out
the error of her ways. ``They talked to me and they helped me and
they showed me the Lord, and I got saved.''
   Her eyes opened, she realized she had finally come home.
   ``You can say, `Do good, do good. But they lived it. They're
really happy,'' Sophia said, and she started to cry. ``I came here
and they showed me something like a reason to live, a purpose in
life.''
   Now 20 and married, dandling her baby boy on her lap, Sophia
believes she has found the happiness she craved.
   ``I love this home,'' she said resolutely. ``I can't believe
what all these ignorant people are doing, saying I'm brainwashed!
If I'm brainwashed, I think everybody needs to be.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Oct. 3</NOTE>
