<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 0844EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV09   09-27 0867</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 09,0905</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv09</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 9</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Karen Curlee and her two sisters used to
sing as the Curlee Sisters, their mother had dreams of their
becoming as famous as Lawrence Welk's Lennon Sisters. But it was
the '60s and girl groups were passe.
   But one decade's passe is a later decade's nostalgia. Today
Karen Curlee is one of the four singing actresses appearing in
``The Taffetas,'' an off-Broadway hit at the Cherry Lane Theater.
   They play four rather naive, singing sisters living in Muncie,
Ind., in the 1950s and making an out-of-town appearance as a group
called the Taffetas.
   ``We're not a slick girls group,'' Curlee says. ``We haven't
gotten that far.''
   Curlee, at 34, and her ``sister'' Taffetas are too young to
remember when songs like ``Mockin' Bird Hill'' (Patti Page),
``Ricochet'' (Teresa Brewer), ``Mr. Sandman'' (Chordettes),
``Dedicated to the One I Love'' (Shirelles), and ``Sincerely''
(McGuire Sisters cover of a Moonglows hit), were on ``The Hit
Parade.''
   Audiences at the Cherry Lane range from people who do remember
those songs with nostalgia to younger listeners curious about what
was pop just before rock to girls admiring the Taffetas' prom
dresses.
   The other Taffetas are Tia Speros of San Francisco, Jody
Abrahams of Chicago, and Melanie Mitchell of Hartford, Conn.
   Mitchell has sung in a show set in the 1940s, playing Patti
Andrews of the Andrews Sisters. On TV she has been Angela, a rich
girl who got into drugs, on ``Another World'' and Judy, a mean
high-school cheerleader, on ``As the World Turns.''
   Curlee, from Fresno, Calif., became a Taffeta just before the
Cherry Lane Theater opening in August, when Susan Carson left to
play Grizabella, the ``Memory'' cat, in ``Cats'' in Vienna. Curlee
had been understudying five cats in ``Cats'' on Broadway for two
years.
   ``The Taffetas'' is the brainchild of Rick Lewis, who's onstage
playing piano at the Cherry Lane with two other musicians.
   Researching '50s music, he was amazed to find Doris Day's record
of ``A Bushel and a Peck.'' ``I thought my mother made that up to
put the kids to sleep.''
   Now he's working on four-part harmony for ``Santa Baby,'' an
Eartha Kitt hit 34 years before Madonna recorded it, to insert into
the show before Christmas.
   He thought of the name, a takeoff on the Chiffons, then the
image, the McGuire Sisters.
   ``They captured what the '50s singing group was like _ gorgeous,
great teeth and smiles and they sang incredibly,'' he says.
   The Taffetas aren't singing note-for-note the '50s arrangements.
``But if you don't hear something that sounds like what you
remember,'' Lewis says, ``you can't really remember it.''
   Lewis also picked the Taffetas' hometown, Muncie, Ind., a place
none of the quartet ever has been. He visited there, for journalism
seminars, from his high school in Dayton, Ohio.
   The Taffetas have been written about recently on Page 1 of the
Muncie Star, under the headline, ``Natives of a Town They Never
Knew.'' ``We're giving everybody from Muncie free tickets to see
the show, if they can prove it,'' Curlee says.
   In college, Lewis studied music education, then did some acting
and musical directing. He moved to New York thinking he'd pursue
both. He included on his resume his Ohio musical directing credits.
He got offered musical directing jobs, often for industrial shows.
   ``I'd build shows from scratch. They would spend $50,000 and it
would be performed one night. I did a show that was $100,000 a few
years ago.'' Trying for a reuseable, cheaper approach, he put
together the Taffetas.
   ``We kept showcasing it for people who book those things. The
amount of people we fed and gave booze to over a two-year period _
I'd like to spend that much on parties for my friends sometime.
They'd say, `When you've got reviews, let us know.'''
   So Lewis took the Taffetas into two New York cabarets, Don't
Tell Mama and Westbeth Cabaret Theater. ``I thought we'd put a nice
little brochure together. Instead we got fabulous reviews. We were
chased by producers wanting us off-Broadway. We made the best
choice. We took Arthur Whitelaw.''
   Since ``The Taffetas'' is an off-Broadway hit, there are offers
for industrial shows, conventions and parties.
   Asked what they think about the 1950s songs they're singing,
Speros says, ``They have an underlying sweet, smiling quality.''
   Curlee says, ``They sang much slower then. My inner tempo as a
34-year-old woman is to lock in much faster.''
   Mitchell says, ``Being slower, you can understand the lyrics.
Not having angst in the voice makes a more vulnerable, innocent and
youthful sound. I think this music grows on you. For me, it does.''
   Abrahams says, ``I love the lyrics. I think `I Cried' (Patti
Page) is one of the most beautiful songs. It pulls on those
heartstrings.''
   The Taffetas were photographed with Patti Page when she sang
recently at a New York nightspot. ``She does a lot of our songs,''
Lewis says with a smile.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
