<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1508EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Asia-Anti-American ADV02-1stadd   09-27 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Asia-Anti-American, ADV 02-1st add,0518</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>BANGKOK: Asian country.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The State Department's Sigur ascribed the South Korean
demonstrations to ``Korean nationalism reacting to the visible
presence of another nation's soldiers. This sort of problem is
difficult to eradicate entirely.''
   However, this very military muscle is welcomed by much of the
rest of Asia, including China, which continues to have shaky
relations with Moscow while building what U.S. diplomats call a
``solid, mature, many-sided'' relationship with Washington.
   The Soviet Union is entrenched at Vietnam's Cam Ranh Bay, its
largest military base outside the homeland, and enjoys a close
alliance with Vietnam.
   Moscow has also made political and economic inititatives since
1986 when General Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev declared in
Vladivostok in Soviet Asia that the ``Soviet Union is also an Asian
Pacific country.'' Recently he offered to pull out of Cam Ranh Bay
if the United States terminated its air and naval stations in the
Philippines.
   ``The real, long-term and very difficult obstacle to remove is
not the American bases but the Soviet bases and military
alliance,'' the head of Malaysia's Institute for Strategic and
International Studies, Noordin Sopiee, wrote this year.
   Asians are also noting that Japan has become the world's fifth
largest spender on defense and is taking a more aggressive role in
international politics. In countries like Indonesia, South Korea,
China and the Philippines, Japanese atrocities in World War II are
far from forgotten.
   ``What kind of a leader is Japan when it worries more about
selling transistors than human rights?'' asked an Indonesian
intellectual, remarking that unlike the U.S. Embassy, the Japanese
mission in Jakarta shuns opposition figures for fear of losing the
government's favor _ and business.
   Princeton's Calder said, ``In comparison with the Japanese
juggernaut the U.S. superpower is more appealing to many Asians. .
.. There are a lot of people after Vietnam who see the U.S. as more
distant, the lesser evil if you will. They balance the generosity
of the Americans with the mercantilism, the strategic approach of
Japan.''
   To offset what many Asians call Japan's ``economic invasion,''
they urge the United States to increase its trade, aid and
investment in Asia. The Japanese have outpaced the United States in
all three in recent years. Official development assistance by Japan
to Asian countries in 1987 was $3.4 billion in contrast to less
than $900 million from Washington.
   U.S. policy makers also say the democratic wave that has in
recent years swept the Philippines, South Korea, Taiwan and now
Burma, along with the economic failures of Asia's communist
societies, are in the U.S. interest.
   The emerging democracies, they say, are not only closer to the
U.S. system and spirit but also eliminate the earlier dilemma of
the United States propping up right-wing, anti-communist dictators.
This had been a source of anti-Americanism in the past.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Denis D. Gray is bureau chief for The Associated
Press in Thailand and has been reporting from Asia since the
mid-1970s.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 2</NOTE>
