<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Strasbourg-Pope ADV02   09-27 0897</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Strasbourg-Pope, ADV 02,0920</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Strasbourg, City of Reconciliation, Awaits Pope John Paul II</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note Oct. 8 date 3rd graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After centuries at the center of a
tug-of-war between Germany and France, this city nestled on a
tranquil river now harmonizes French joie de vivre with German
efficiency.
   ``Strasbourg is a symbol,'' says Deputy Mayor Germain Muller,
who is in charge of the celebrations marking the city's 2,000th
anniversary this year. ``France and Germany, which often fought
over this place, are now the countries leading us toward a united
Europe.''
   Pope John Paul II will spend four days, beginning Oct. 8, in
this city between West Germany's Black Forest and France's Vosges
Mountains. He will address the entity that symbolizes European
unity, the European Parliament, which meets in the chambers of the
Council of Europe.
   In coming to Strasbourg, the pope will not find a better place
to illustrate reconciliation _ an appropriate theme at a time when
the Roman Catholic Church in the area is shaken by a traditionalist
schism.
   Memories of the Nazi occupation are fresh enough to cause
Strasbourgeois, as the local people are called, to feel
passionately French.
   Taxi drivers boast that the French national anthem, the
Marseillaise, was written here. Shopkeepers mention that Napoleon
Bonaparte came here to go to school. The city is still the biggest
university town in eastern France.
   They mention less often, however, that Goethe studied here, too,
or that Johann Gutenberg spent a decade in Strasbourg inventing the
intricate press on which he later produced his Bible, the first
book printed with movable type.
   For centuries Alsace and the neighboring region of Lorraine were
part of an independent republic bordering the Rhine River. From
1870 to 1945, the region passed regularly back and forth between
German and French hands.
   The bicultural history is felt today in nearly every aspect of
daily life _ from the bildings on the street to the music on the
radio. Even the names of city streets reveal Strasbourg's seesaw
history.
   In 1871, Avenue Napoleon became Kaiser Wilhelmstrasse, after the
Germans moved in. That was changed to Boulevard de la Republique
after World War I. Then for some years it was known as Adolf Hitler
Strasse until it was given its current name, Avenue Charles de
Gaulle, when the French reclaimed the city at the end of World War
II.
   The avenue today is filled with a blitzkrieg of German tourists
who arrive by the busload in this city of 400,000, just two miles
from the West German border. They are outnumbered only by French
sightseers who stroll through the narrow, medieval streets of
half-timbered houses, past outdoor cafes and hidden courtyards and
over picturesque bridges on the Ill River.
   Many people speak both German and French, and older people often
are fluent in Alsatian, the regional linguistic hybrid.
   The intertwining of cultures has produced a cuisine that melds
German ingredients and French know-how to cook up regional dishes
like choucroute _ sauerkraut and smoked meat cooked in wine.
Kronenbourg beer is brewed here. Rhine wines, in a dry French
style, are produced nearby.
   Cuisines and languages have blended with ease; the region's two
religions have not. Unlike most of France, which is 80 percent
Roman Catholic, Alsace-Lorraine is half Protestant.
   ``When a Protestant girl married a Catholic boy here it used to
be considered a disgrace. Except for a very few small villages,
it's not that way anymore,'' said City Councilman Gilbert Roos,
whose father was a medical officer in the German army in World War
I and in the French army in World War II.
   Roos said the two groups now live in harmony. The discord these
days is within the Catholic church itself.
   In June, a long-brewing dispute between the Vatican and Catholic
traditionalists culminated in the excommunication of rebel
Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre. It was the first schism within the
Roman Catholic Church in more than a century and has led to
repeated calls by the French hierarchy for unity in the face of the
challenge posed by Lefebvre and his flock.
   As he did on a trip to France two years ago, Pope John Paul is
likely to stress loyalty to Rome on this visit, which begins at
Strasbourg's massive cathedral, a dramatic setting for the pope's
first speech.
   Built between 1190 and 1489 by master French and Rhineland
craftsmen, the pink sandstone cathedral rises 465 feet and was the
highest building in the Christian world until a century ago.
   Inside is an astronomical clock of ingenious works. At 12:30
each afternoon a bell is struck by a figure representing Death,
while the 12 Apostles receive the blessing of Christ and a cock,
beating its wings, crows three times in memory of Peter's denial.
   A perpetual calendar on the clock calculates the phases of the
moon, solar eclipses and rising and setting of the sun.
   While here, the pope also will speak at both the European
Parliament and Council of Europe.
   The presence of these two European institutions has stirred the
ambitions of some local boosters.
   ``It is not surprising the pope is coming here,'' said Roos.
``One day we won't be just another beautiful city. Someday we will
be the capital of Europe.''

</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 2</NOTE>
