<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews ADV00   09-27 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, ADV 00,0831</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Chimes of Freedom'' (Columbia Records) _ Bruce Springsteen
   
   This extended play recording was released to coincide with the
six-week Human Rights Now! global tour now under way featuring
Bruce Springsteen, Sting, Peter Gabriel and a host of other
musicians, with some of the EP's proceeds donated to the human
rights group Amnesty International.
   The disc's four songs were all recorded live during
Springsteen's 1988 ``Tunnel of Love'' tour; the opening ``Tougher
Than the Rest'' already appears on that album. This live version,
recorded at the Los Angeles Sports Arena, has a slower, more
country-tinged tempo to it, and wraps up nicely with fine harmonica
work by Springsteen.
   ``Be True,'' recorded at the Joe Louis Arena in Detroit, is what
Springsteen fans would call typical ``B Side Bruce.'' The artist
has a penchant for putting catchy, danceable tunes on the flip
sides of his singles that aren't included on any album.
   Backed, as always, by the hard-rocking E Street Band,
Springsteen croons to the fictional heroine, ``You be true to me
and I'll be true to you.'' Isn't it kind of tacky for Springsteen,
whose split with wife Julianne Phillips made all the gossip columns
during his tour, to include this song here?
   Incidentally, vocals by back-up singer Patti Scialfa, with whom
Springsteen is now involved, are far more prominent on this EP than
on any previous recording.
   ``Chimes of Freedom,'' the third song, is alone worth buying
this EP for. The Bob Dylan protest song is the perfect anthem for
the Amnesty International tour, and Springsteen's rendering,
recorded in Stockholm, Sweden, is faithful to the original. The
artist, whose lyrics were often compared to Dylan's early in his
career, proves he can salute his influences and still add something
uniquely his own to their songs.
   By far the most ambitious of the four songs is Springsteen's
acoustic version of ``Born to Run,'' also recorded in Los Angeles.
That song was the artist's signature tune before being replaced by
``Born in the USA,'' and it had the raw power of a motorcycle
opened up at full throttle.
   However, Springsteen, who has proven himself an accomplished
accoustic artist with ``Nebraska'' and several cuts on ``Tunnel of
Love,'' falls flat here. His vocals meander all over the place like
a Leonard Cohen prose-poem and the impression is one of the
motorcycle run out of gas and being pushed along like a scooter.
   _ By Geneva Collins, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Still Live'' (ECM) _ Keith Jarrett Trio
   
   Jazz pianist Keith Jarrett, who unlike many of his
electronic-minded contemporaries still plays only the piano, has
never sounded better than in this two-disc live recording.
   Communicating intuitively with bassist Gary Peacock and drummer
Jack DeJohnette, Jarrett combined his signature moody chord
voicings with sharp improvising in a collection of jazz standards
for a concert audience in Munich, West Germany.
   He took the songs' familiar melodies and stretched, twisted and
bent them in fascinating ways. The listener is never lost, though,
and he ends each journey back at the beginning, exhilarated and
ready for another.
   Jarrett's interpretation of ``My Funny Valentine'' was
understated and sensitive, while ``When I Fall in Love'' became a
ballad with a bit of an attitude.
   ``Come Rain or Come Shine'' had just the right bluesy edge. Only
``The Song Is You,'' a Kern-Hammerstein composition, failed to
achieve a groove that matched its length, nearly 17 minutes.
   Keith Jarrett is an intelligent pianist who has done his share
of experimenting. ``Still Live,'' with its classic tunes played on
acoustic piano, should give purists plenty to cheer about.
   
   _ Barry Hanson, Associated Press Writer
   
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Day By Day'' (EMI-Manhattan) _ Najee
   
   Najee sets a mellow groove on his second LP, ``Day By Day,'' and
never strays very far from the course.
   The album is always tasteful, with the New Yorker's soaring
saxophone solos taking center stage and showing his jazz and rhythm
and blues influences. Back-up singers dart in and out of the
arrangements, keeping things moving along smoothly.
   But the album tends to be swallowed up by its tastefulness, and
often fades into backround music. While this album can be the
perfect accompaniment to a romantic dinner, it unfortunately is
just as appropriate later on when the dishes are being washed.
   Only ``Najee's Nasty Groove,'' a funky track dominated by drums
and synthesizer, breaks the mold.
   Anyone in the market for some easy listening jazz could do worse
than this album. But those looking for something more, well,
inspiring, would do well to keep on looking.
   _ By Marc Rice, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
