<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Moore ADV7-9   09-27 0918</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Moore, ADV 7-9,0942</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07-09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct 7-9, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: A Never-Ending Discovery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The life's work of sculptor Henry Moore has gone
on show in London in a comprehensive way that was never managed
while he lived.
   ``We discussed an exhibition with him in 1984 to mark his 90th
birthday this year, but he died in 1986. Now this is his
memorial,'' said Roger de Grey, president of the Royal Academy of
Arts.
   The venerable academy, which has been presenting art exhibitions
since 1768, has done Moore proud, spreading 112 sculptures and 127
drawings by him through its 12 main galleries to show all the
stages of his career.
   There are Giant abstract bronzes and lifesize human figures in
stone that had to be lifted in by crane, and little plaster figures
smaller than a hand.
   His famous drawings of restless sleepers who sought refuge in
the London subway to escape bombings in World War II also are
shown, along with sketches of coal miners, trees, elephants, sheep,
landscapes and ideas for sculpture, often based on bones, stones
and bits of wood which he picked up.
   Dr. Susan Compton, a British art historian who organized a
popular exhibition of Marc Chagall at the Philadelphia Museum of
Art, spent 15 months arranging the exhibition, which ru a global thing.
That's
where the `Small World' concept came from.''
   The album's first single is the brassy ``Perfect World'' written
by Alex Call, a longtime friend of Lewis' who used to be in his old
country-rock band Clover.
   Lewis said the second single will be an edited version of
``Small World (Part One)'' and the instrumental ``Small World (Part
Two),'' which features a guest appearance by jazz saxophonist Stan
Getz.
   ``I once went to a benefit show with my dad, who's a jazz
drummer, and Stan came up and introduced himself to me,'' Lewis
recalled. ``He said, `Hey man, why don't you let me play on some of
your stuff? I can play that stuff, too.' Then he gave me a card
that said, `Stan Getz: Have Sax, Will Travel.'''
   Other album cuts are the 1960s-style soul instrumental
``Slammin','' the Cajun-sounding ``Old Antone's'' which features a
guest appearance by Bruce Hornsby on accordion, the reggae-tinged
love song ``Better Be True'' and the pure reggae jam ``Bobo Tempo.''
   ```Bobo Tempo' was written by Sean and myself about 13 years ago
when we were both in Clover,'' Lewis said. ``It was for a gig we
had in Bolinas, Calif. `Bobo' is a nickname for Bolinas, which is a
nutty place. We used to play out there every so often and there
would be huge street parties.
   ``We wrote the song just for that one gig, just for a laugh
really,'' he said. ``On the last day of the ``Fore!'' album
sessions (in 1986), we piled into the studio at midnight and cut
that song. The track really held up.''
   But not the video, which involves a topless girl, a surfer and a
horse on a surfboard and probably will never be commercially
released.
   The cleft-chinned Lewis, born Hugh Anthony Cregg III in New York
City, grew up near San Francisco and was known as ``Huey Louie''
when he joined Clover in 1972. He changed his name to Huey Lewis
when he formed his band in late 1979 with Hopper, 35, Hayes, 30,
and three members of the Bay Area group Soundhole _ Gibson, 36,
Cipollina, 33, and Colla, 36.
   The group originally was called Huey Lewis and The American
Express, but the name was quickly altered to avoid an infringment
lawsuit.
   Their self-titled first album in 1980 went nowhere, but the
follow-up ``Picture This'' in 1982 had the Top 10 hits ``Workin'
for a Livin''' and ``Do You Believe in Love.'' Next came the
landmark ``Sports'' album, which has sold 9 million copies since
its September 1983 release and won several Grammy Awards. It
spawned five Top 10 singles including ``I Want a New Drug'' and
``Heart of Rock & Roll.''
   In 1985, the band had its first No. 1 single with ``Power of
Love,'' an Oscar-nominated song recorded for the year's
largest-grossing movie, ``Back to the Future.''
   The tour will take Huey Lewis and The News well into 1989 and
mark their 10th anniversary together.
   ``I'd be surprised if we're not together another 10 years,''
Lewis said.
   ``But it's funny. I still remember when we got our first
paycheck from our manager, Bob Brown. I remember I told him, `I got
to have $150 a week for these guys. Otherwise, that's it.' It
doesn't seem that long ago.''
</TEXT>
