<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Whitley ADV07-09   09-27 0779</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Whitley, ADV 07-09,0804</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07-09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 7-9, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Keith Whitley Is Just Getting Started</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising country music performer Keith
Whitley says his career is just getting started even though he's
been singing on the road for 18 years.
   The 33-year-old singer hit the top of the country music charts
in August with the single ``Don't Close Your Eyes.'' The album of
the same name has been in the Top 10.
   ``We're at the point where all systems are go,'' said Whitley,
whose honky-tonk style of singing is traditional country music with
lyrics embracing pain and joy. ``That sounds odd for somebody who's
been on the road for (about) 20 years.''
   He was only 15 when he and friend Ricky Skaggs, a year older,
joined Ralph Stanley's Clinch Mountain Boys, a bluegrass band. Like
Whitley, Skaggs eventually became a solo country singer.
   Whitley then survived his remaining, reckless teen-age years and
battled a stubborn drinking problem to become one of country
music's emerging stars along with Randy Travis and Dwight Yoakam.
   ``I've been in this business for a long, long time,'' he said in
an interview. ``But from the musical standpoint and a personal
standpoint, we're really just at the beginning of my career.''
   As a carefree teen in Sandy Hook, Ky., he bought bootleg
bourbon, poured it down his thirsty throat and then enjoyed
challenging the rural roads at breathless speeds deep in Appalachia.
   ``Basically when I was growing up, the only thing we did for
pastime was go to bootleggers and get something to drink and ride
around and drink it and drive around and see how fast you could
take those mountain curves,'' he recalled.
   At age 17, he was in a car with a companion who attempted to
round a curve at 120 mph. The car wrecked, killing his friend.
   ``The doctor told me I came close to breaking my neck,'' said
Whitley, who was cut but not hurt in the accident.
   At 19, he drove off a 120-foot cliff into a frozen river,
escaping with a broken collarbone.
   ``There were a lot more less serious accidents and brushes with
the law,'' he said.
   But always, he was intrigued by music. He played with Stanley's
band on the weekends as a teen-ager and later was lead singer for
J.D. Crowe and the New South, a country-bluegrass band.
   After earning the reputation as a fine musician and singer, he
moved to Nashville in the mid-1980s and landed a recording contract
with RCA Records. His hits besides ``Don't Close Your Eyes''
include ``Miami My Amy,'' ``Ten Feet Away,'' ``Homecoming '63'' and
``Hard Livin.'''
   He quit drinking in 1987.
   ``It was a matter of life and death,'' he said. ``If I hadn't
stopped drinking, I don't think I'd be alive today. I did so many
crazy things while drinking.''
   Whitley, who is married to Grand Ole Opry singer Lorrie Morgan,
said his lifestyle intensified his music.
   ``Not to sound conceited, but I've lived, breathed and cried
this music since I was 3 or 4 years old,'' Whitley said. ``I take
it very seriously. Most of the things I sing in my songs, I've
lived.
   ``I don't wish the others would have to go through that. But I
believe I've got the credentials to sing some of the things I sing
about where some others don't.
   ``The whole deal with my music has been the emotional quality.
Songs I do have to strike an emotional chord the first time I sing
them. It's not uncommon for me to get so wrapped up in a song that
I cry several times when I sing them. That's the difference between
my music and some of the other folks.''
   His ``Don't Close Your Eyes'' is about the desperation of love.
   ``People identified with it. Women seemed to like it and they
are a big part of the record-buying public. At shows, people often
come up to me and say they feel like it was written about them.
   ``The melody is real mournful. You can get lost emotionally
singing it.''
   One of the songs on the album is ``I Never Go Around Mirrors,''
a hit years ago by the late country star Lefty Frizzell.
   Whitley had a verse added to the song. A few hours before he
recorded it, he visited Frizzell's grave and wept.
   ``That sounds weird to people. But his music was very important
to me growing up,'' Whitley said. People don't understand why I did
that, but it meant a lot to me.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct 7-9</NOTE>
