<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1208EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--SexGene Adv29   09-27 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Sex Gene, Adv 29,0607</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Sept. 29, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Researchers Disagree Over Reported Genetic Sex Trigger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAR HARBOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now that scientists have found the gene
that makes a man a man, some of them would like to see equal rights
for the gene that makes a woman a woman.
   Last winter, Dr. David Page of the Whitehead Institute in
Cambridge, Mass., announced the discovery of what appears to be the
male sex trigger _ a bit of genetic material that separates the
boys from the girls.
   If Page is right, there is one sex switch. Those who get this
gene at conception will be boys. Those who don't will be girls.
   Page has offered a variety of explanations. But many scientists
assume it means there is a gene for masculinity and not for
femininity.
   One researcher who disagrees with this assumption is Dr. Eva M.
Eicher, a geneticist at the Jackson Laboratory in Bar Harbor. She
said she has no quarrel with Page, only with how his discovery is
interpretted.
   ``There is sexism in biology,'' Eicher said. ``There is no
question about it. It influences the way that biologists approach
problems, such as sex determination.''
   Even the language of genetics, such as ``dominant'' and
``recessive,'' carry subconscious connotations about the roles of
men and women, she said.
   According to her theory _ and she emphasizes it's only that _
the genetic library of the human race contains two sex genes. One
contains the instructions for building boys, the other for making
girls.
   She said many experts believe a maleness gene is necessary to
make testis and all the internal and external sex organs of
manhood. But for making females, only the absence of this gene is
necessary.
   ``When it comes to sex, the active process is testis and the
passive or default process is ovary,'' she said. ``I don't think
nature works by doing nothing. There has to be an active pathway''
to womanhood.
   Dr. Elizabeth Simpson of the Clinical Research Center in Harrow,
England agrees. ``It may be simple-minded to think that you have a
switch to go down one pathway but nothing to go down the other,''
she said.
   Everybody is born with two strings of genes, known as sex
chromosomes, that are called X and Y. Women have two X chromosomes,
but men have an X and a Y.
   Page found the gene that seems to control maleness on the Y
chromosome. But he also found a closely related gene on the X
chromosome; nobody knows what that gene does.
   Eicher speculates that this is the female gene. The process
might work like this:
   If an egg is fertilized by a ``male'' sperm, the sex gene on its
Y chromosome kicks to life, starting a chain reaction of hormones
that eventually direct the fetus to become a boy. Among its jobs is
shutting off the female sex gene on the X chromosome.
   But if there is no Y sex gene, then a few hours later, the X sex
gene turns on, starting the process toward womanhood.
   This is mostly speculation, although Eicher said she has found a
hint in some strains of mice that something like this could be
going on. But at least by challenging people's assumptions, she
hopes to eventually get closer to the biological truth.
   ``We think we know so much,'' she said. ``What I am continually
amazed by is that we know almost nothing.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
