<DOCNO> AP880927-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--PheromonesFuture Adv29   09-27 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Pheromones Future, Adv 29,0728</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Sept. 29, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Much Ballyhooed Alternative to Pesticides Facing Uphill Struggle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Tim Dennehy gets frustrated about the
EPA, he starts talking about Oreo cookies and milk.
   Dennehy says that if he believed Oreos could control insects and
he wanted to dangle them in a field, the Environmental Protection
Agency would force him to do a battery of tests to learn if the
cookies were an environmental threat.
   ``At this point, I don't know if that's an exaggeration,'' says
Dennehy, who spent two years getting permits to test pheromones _
chemicals that insects produce to communicate _ as an alternative
to pesticides.
   He and pheromone expert Wendell Roelofs have devised a compound
simulating the mating scent of female Grape Berry Moths. Dennehy
says it is as safe ``as spraying milk'' on crops, can replace up to
12 pounds of insecticides, and doesn't even kill the bugs it is
meant to control.
   James Touhey, an EPA adviser, acknowledges that regulations for
toxic pesticides are unnecessarily stringent for such non-toxic
alternatives, but is confident that ways can be found to simplify
the process.
   ``Pheromones are in their infancy in terms of practical use,''
says Richard Ridgway, head of the Insect Chemical Ecology
Laboratory at the Agricultural Research Service in Beltsville, Md.
   About 250 pheromones have been identified since their discovery
in 1959, and some are being used, Ridgway says, including one to
control the cotton boll weevil and another on the Oriental fruit
moth on California peaches.
   However, they never lived up to their early promise. Companies
can't make enough profit because they only work for one species,
limiting the market. They are not successful on pests that gather
in great numbers, masking the scent. And research and development
has run into regulatory roadblocks and apathy.
   Dennehy and Roelofs spent nearly two years getting a permit for
a large-scale test. They had to learn legal jargon to explain what
they wanted to do, track down the right forms and present pages of
evidence and documentation required by the Federal Insecticide,
Fungicide and Rodenticide Act.
   ``Our problem is that we have a non-toxic chemical being watched
over by regulations for toxic chemicals,'' said Roelofs, who works
with Dennehy at the New York Agricultural Experiment Station of
Cornell University.
   Touhey, senior agricultural adviser to the EPA office of
pesticide programs, said, ``It seems the traditional mechanisms
that were working in the past to regulate things doesn't seem to be
working now.''
   In Dennehy's experiment, male moths attracted to clear plastic
twist-ties laced with the pheromone have trouble finding fertile
females, thus preventing explosive growth of the bugs in the
vineyard.
   He had sought a permit letting him use pheromones _ which have a
chemical makeup similar to olive oil _ and sell the grapes. EPA
said OK, but only if he destroyed the grapes, costing him $10,000
he might have earned.
   Then it said he could sell them.
   Dennehy expects to have results from his tests in 100 acres of
grapes across New York after the harvest. If they are favorable,
the next step will be to get the pheromone on the market.
   Dave Ross, who grows 275 acres of grapes in Westfield near Lake
Erie, said he would welcome a chance to stop using the pesticide
Parathion. ``Any time we can eliminate using something that
dangerous, I think it's a good thing.''
   Under current rules, however, the EPA requires a study to
determine environmental impact of the ``pesticide.'' That includes
feeding it to ducks and shellfish, and could cost millions, Dennehy
said.
   Both Touhey and Ridgway believe a compromise can be reached that
will make it easier for pheromones to reach farmers and growers.
   In some cases, tests could be waived, Touhey said. In others,
the number of tests could be cut. Meanwhile, he's trying to help
pheromone researchers get certain permits and guide them through
the regulatory maze.
   And while theoretically Oreo cookies and milk used to ``control
or mitigate'' insects would be pesticides, realistically the morass
of regulations includes a waiver of tests, he said. ``But I get the
point.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
