<HEAD>Heartworm Drug Can Prevent African Parasite Infection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drug long used to free dogs of heartworms also
apparently prevents a serious parasitic disease among visitors to
some parts of Africa.
   An estimated 13 million people in western and central Africa are
infected with loa loa, the African eyeworm, but loiasis, the
disease it causes, is usually most severe among outsiders who visit
Africa.
   The worm is spread by biting flies that feed on human blood, and
is parasitic in or just under the skin, often migrating to around
the eyes.
   The heartworm drug, diethylcarbamazine, kills the worm before
the body mounts a strong immune response to it. The major
consequences of the disease, including possible heart and kidney
damage, result from the body's immune reaction to the worm.
   Doctors from the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious
Diseases tested diethylcarbamazine on Peace Corps volunteers in
Gabon, Cameroon and the Central African Republic. Forty-one took
weekly doses of the medicine for two years, while 60 others took
placebo pills. Six in the placebo group got loiasis, but none of
the diethylcarbamazine users got sick.
   While the drug is considered safe, the doctors said it is not
necessary for people who make brief visits to major cities in the
region.
   The research team, headed by Dr. Thomas B. Nutman, reported
their findings recently in the New England Journal of Medicine.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Archaeologist Seeks To Market Obsidian, Glass Surgical Blades</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An archaeologist who cut himself 20 years
ago on a 3,500-year-old obsidian blade thinks the Mayans had the
right idea.
   Payson Sheets says obsidian blades can be 500 times sharper than
steel, resulting in more exact cuts that heal quicker and with less
scarring. He and ophthalmologist Firmon Hardenbergh are seeking
Food and Drug Administration permission to make and sell glass and
obsidian surgical blades.
   Obsidian, formed when lava cools too quickly to crystallize, was
traded throughout the Americas by Indians as tool material. Unlike
steel, Sheets says, the black, glassy material can be fractured to
a few molecules thick.
   Hardenbergh uses the blades in cornea transplants and cataract
surgery, and the partners have loaned obsidian and glass blades to
other surgeons while they await FDA approval, Sheets says. That
process could take more than a year.
   Sheets also is experimenting by mixing a hardening agent into
molten glass so blades will hold a tougher and more consistent
edge. He pours the molten glass into molds to make blades of
different shapes and sizes.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Planned Building Will Display Effects of Wind, Quakes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anyone nervous about the effects of wind
or earthquakes on the University of Tennessee's planned engineering
building will have only to go down to the lobby and see what the
building says.
   Instruments planted throughout the building when it is built
beginning next summer will measure those forces and display them
and the movements of machines and people on a computer-generated
graphic display.
   ``We will put transducers in the beams and columns to measure
varying loads and how the building responds to those loads,'' said
Richard Bennett, associate professor of civil engineering.
``Instruments that measure wind pressure will be installed so we
can determine how the building is affected by wind, and how the
real responses compare to the formulas we now use to design
buildings.
   ``It will be a working laboratory. We will be able to make
precise measurements of forces that before could only be
estimated.''
   The building can be used to ``demonstrate engineering mechanics
principles, and as a research tool to learn more about design and
construction and the long-term behavior of people,'' Bennett said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 29</NOTE>
