<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange says its ``collar''
restraint on computerized program trading will end on the
anniversary of the Oct. 19 crash.
   The collar is to be replaced by previously announced measures
designed to quell price volatility and restore investor confidence.
   Donald J. Solodar, senior vice president of the nation's largest
securities market, mentioned the termination Monday at a briefing
aimed at reviewing the exchange's efforts to expand computer
capacity and undertake other reforms in the year since the market
panic.
