<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 0336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Crash-Reforms Bjt   09-27 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Reforms, Bjt,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYSE Seeking SEC Approval of Reforms By Black Monday Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange hopes its post-crash
reform package announced earlier this year will receive government
approval by the anniversary of the Oct. 19 market rout, but federal
regulators aren't making promises.
   Donald Solodar, senior vice president of the largest U.S. stock
market, said Monday the Securities and Exchange Commission actively
was reviewing the reform proposals, devised jointly with the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   The reforms would supercede the NYSE's temporary ``collar''
restraint on computerized program trading, a six-month experiment
approved by the SEC last April 20 that was aimed at calming wild
price swings. The collar expires Oct. 19, the anniversary of the
crash.
   Speaking to reporters at an NYSE briefing about steps taken to
improve the climate for stock trading since the crash, Solodar said
it was possible the new reforms would not be in place by the
anniversary, but ``we believe the SEC will approve them.''
   In Washington, SEC officials declined to specify when the
reforms would be approved. They were announced in July, but not
filed with the regulatory agency until late August.
   ``The staff is actively reviewing these matters and is trying to
expedite its review consistent with the NYSE request,'' said
Brendon Becker, SEC associate director of market regulation.
   Market regulatory officials have said privately that potential
complications have arisen because other U.S. securities markets
dislike the proposed reforms. For example, the National Association
of Securities Dealers, which supervises over-the-counter trading,
has expressed opposition to them.
   Under the reforms, the New York and Chicago markets agreed on a
one-year pilot program for what they called coordinated ``circuit
breakers'' that would halt trading temporarily if price moves
exceeded preset limits.
   The halts would be triggered in New York by a 250-point move in
the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks and in Chicago by a
12-point move in the Standard & Poor's 500 stock-index futures
contract.
   The reforms also call for tighter communication between the
Chicago and New York exchanges and a common policy on ``intermarket
front-running,'' an abuse in which traders are able to take a
profitable position in one market based on what they know will
happen in another market.
   The NYSE also has prepared what it calls an ``Individual
Investor Express Delivery Service,'' which will provide
transmission priority to individual investor orders when the Dow
average moves 25 points from its previous close.
   This reform was designed to reassure investors that their orders
will receive equal treatment with those from large institutional
investors. On Black Monday, many individuals complained they could
not sell their stock because larger investors were served first.
   NYSE officials conceded at the Monday briefing that individual
investors remain unwilling to re-enter the stock market, which has
failed to recoup much of the loss from the crash and has been
plagued by low trading volume.
   Asked to speculate when individuals would regain the confidence
to invest in stocks, NYSE President Richard Grasso said: ``That is
beyond my crystal ball at the moment.''
   A bleak assessment of when individual investor confidence also
was offered Monday in a post-crash review by Edward I. O'Brien,
president of the Securities Industry Assocation, a leading Wall
Street trade group.
   O'Brien said in a statement that although the worst fears about
the economy never materialized after the collapse and market
conditions have improved in some areas, ``the overall current
environment is at best gray.''
   He said the SIA ``believes the near-term outlook isn't likely to
improve substantially until full investor confidence is restored in
both the integrity of the marketplace and the strength of the
economy.''
   O'Brien also said there have been a few steps to correct
problems exposed as a result of the crash, ``but major regulatory
reform hasn't taken place.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
