<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CreditCards     09-27 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Credit Cards,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Industry Survey Finds 40 Percent Pay Bank Credit Cards In Full
Each Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Bankers Association says
changing tax laws are prompting more consumers to pay their credit
card balances in full each month.
   A new survey by the industry trade group indicates 40 percent of
consumers pay their monthly card bills in full, up from about 33
percent last year.
   David Hunt, vice chairman of ABA's Retail Electronic Services
and Bank Card Division, said the increase stemmed from the federal
tax law, which is phasing out credit card interest deductions over
a four-year period ending in 1991.
   The study, released Monday, also found that overall growth in
the bank credit card business had slowed because of stiff
competition from other issuers, such as Sears and American Express.
   ``The survey results reflect the fierce competition among bank
card issuers,'' said Hunt. ``The range of prices and card features
gives consumers a virtually unlimited number of options.''
   The number of Visa and MasterCard cardholders grew by about 9
percent last year, a slowdown in the rate of previous years,
according to Hunt. Visa and MasterCard, both bank-owned credit card
associations, represent 60 percent of the bank credit card market.
   ``We've seen the entrance of significant new competition over
the last couple of years,'' said Hunt, who also is executive vice
president of Signet Banking Corp., Richmond, Va.
   The report found consumers charged more than $165 billion on
their bank cards last year, an increase of 18.8 percent for
Mastercard and 12.3 percent for Visa.
   The ABA report was based on a survey of 1,444 card-issuing banks
selected from a national sample based on asset size and includes
1987 and first quarter 1988 data on bank card interest rates, fees,
marketing and operations.
   The number of banks charging the maximum interest rate allowed
in their states declined to less than one-fourth, according to
Hunt, who attributed the drop to increased market competition.
   Banks that charged the maximum rate included 18 percent of banks
with assets under $300 million and 27 percent of large banks with
assets above $1 billion, the report said.
   In comparison, last year's report found that 35 percent of the
large banks, with assets above $1 billion, charged the maximum
rate. That report also showed that about 26 percent of banks with
assets below $500 million charged the highest rate allowed in their
states.
   The ABA is the national trade and professional association for
U.S. full service banks of all sizes. The bank card conference runs
through Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
