<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoLeasing     09-27 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Leasing,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Three Competitors Say GMAC Leasing Incentives No Big Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Acceptance Corp. is planning waves
of publicity for its new car and truck leasing incentives but its
Big Three competitors say the offerings are nothing new.
   GMAC, the finance arm of the world's largest manufacturer, said
Monday its ``SmartLease'' program can save customers money on
monthly payments and tell them in advance how much it will cost to
buy the car at the end of the lease.
   The most popular cars GM makes are included in the program, but
GMAC offered neither a range of savings nor specific examples of
savings on any models.
   The finance divisions of Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. said
they have offered similar deals for most of the decade.
   ``We have had a consumer leasing program that has been promoted
extensively,'' Ford Motor Credit Co. spokeswoman Joy Wolfe said.
``We feel that we have been a leader in consumer leasing.''
   Clifford Damaska, Ford retail lease manager, said the company
has offered a variety of incentives over the last 18 months while
competing with the special interest rates and cash rebates offered
to retail buyers.
   Chrysler Financial Corp. spokesman Robert Heath said the No. 3
carmaker's Gold Key Lease Finance Plan offers the same features as
GMAC's.
   Heath said Chrysler dealers work out the final post-lease
purchase price with the customer.
   Included in the GMAC promotion, which runs through Dec. 31, are
the Chevrolet Corsica and Beretta, the Pontiac Grand Am, three
Cutlass models and two GMC truck lines, company spokesman John
Andrews said.
   ``What we've done is a corporate-wide program,'' Andrews said.
``Leasing programs have been done by each of the divisions. Under
our old programs, the purchase price was determined at the end of
lease and was the fair market value of the car.''
   Knowing the post-lease or residual value of the car up front is
an advantage to the buyer in considering whether to buy out the
lease at its end, Andrews said.
   The end of auto interest deductions on federal tax returns has
made leasing a more attractive option, especially for young
families trying to meet mortgage payments, which still are partly
tax deductible, he said.
   ``It's also a lifestyle thing,'' Andrews said. ``It isn't
important for people to own things like it used to be.''
   National promotion of the SmartLease program began during Sunday
night's telecast of the Summer Olympics. Extensive electronic and
print ads are planned.
</TEXT>
