<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Zenith-Brookhurst     09-27 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zenith-Brookhurst,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zenith Removes Obstacle To Shareholder Referendum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dissident shareholder group trying to
sell Zenith Electronics Corp. says it was pleased the board of
directors will allow a vote on the plan but that it still lacks
important company data.
   Zenith's board of directors amended the company's bylaws Monday
so that New York-based Brookhurst Partners' plan to sell the
company would require approval by a simple majority of shareholders.
   Before the action, company bylaws would have required unanimous
consent from shareholders, a provision contested in court by
Brookhurst.
   Brookhurst spokesman Tom Franco said the revison was a positive
step but his group needed to see Zenith's financial records and a
list of company stockholders.
   ``It's hard for us to make any qualitative statement on the
action by the board of directors today,'' Franco said in a
telephone interview Monday. ``We look forward to bringing our case
to the shareowners, but we are still waiting for the owners' list.''
   Zenith stock fell 25 cents a share to $19.75 Monday in New York
Stock Exchange trading.
   Zenith Chairman Jerry K. Pearlman said in a statement that his
company revised the bylaw ``so shareholders will not be distracted
from the key issue of who is best qualified to direct the future of
this company _ Zenith's present board or Brookhurst Partners.''
   Zenith spokesman John Taylor refused to elaborate on Pearlman's
statement, citing Securities and Exchange Commission regulations,
or to say whether Zenith had made any recommendation to
shareholders on the Brookhurst offer.
   Zenith, the last remaining U.S. television manufacturer, has
lost millions in recent years struggling to compete with low-cost
imported electronic goods.
   Last year, the company posted a loss of $19.1 million on sales
of $2.36 billion.
   Brookhurst, which owns 6.1 percent of Zenith's outstanding
common shares, bought into the company in June with the intention
of selling the television and computer maker, Franco said.
   But Franco said his group, formed by Herbert Abelow and Nicholas
Ihasz, would be open to a ``realistic management plan to achieve
profitability.''
</TEXT>
