<DOCNO> AP880927-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 0845EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Trade     09-27 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Trade,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britian's Trade Gap Fells In August</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit totaled 1.813
billion pounds, or $3.06 billion, in August _ the second-worst
monthly shortfall _ but it narrowed sharply from the previous
month's record gap, the government reported Tuesday.
   The deficit report was below market forecasts of up to 1.9
billion pounds, or $3.17 billion, and the British pound firmed on
the news. Stock prices also got a slight boost.
   Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson said in a statement
that the Conservative government had tightened monetary conditions
to curb sharp rises in imports and ``the effects of this will
inevitably take some time to come through.''
   British commercial banks have pushed up their base interest
rates by 4.5 percent to 12 percent since early June.
   The seasonally adjusted merchandise trade deficit had spurted 72
percent to a record 2.65 billion pounds, or $4.5 billion, in July,
prompting a full percentage point increase in interest rates.
   Exports in August totaled 6.75 billion pounds, or $11.4 billion,
down from 6.775 billion pounds, or $11.45 billion, in July and up
from 6.6 billion pounds, or $11.1 billion, in August 1987.
   Imports totalled 8.561 billion pounds, or $14.5 billion, down 9
percent from 9.427 billion pounds, or $15.9 billion, in July and up
from 8 billion pounds, or $13.5 billion, in August 1987.
   For the first eight months of the year, the merchandise trade
balance has been in deficit by 12.85 billion pounds, or $21.7
billion, more than double the 6.160 billion pound, or $10.4
billion, gap a year ago.
</TEXT>
