<HEAD>Taiwan To Reimpose Capital Gains Tax On Stock Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance Minister Shirley Kuo said Tuesday
the reimposition of a capital-gains tax on stock profits next year
is meant to maintain a fair taxation system despite investors'
worries the levy would trigger a market slump.
   ``It is not government intervention. We merely want to make it
fair to all taxpayers,'' Kuo told a news conference.
   On Saturday, Kuo announced the government would reimpose the tax
on stock profits next year after a 12-year freeze.
   Individual investors who sell stocks worth more than 3 million
Taiwan dollars, or $103,448, should include the stock income when
filing their annual income tax, she said.
   Observers said the surprise move, timed before the four-day,
Mid-Autumn Festival holiday, was designed to cool down the stock
market.
   ``There will surely be heavy selling pressure when it re-opens
Thursday,'' said Philip Young, vice president of International
Investment Trust Company Ltd.
</TEXT>
