<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FamilyLeave     09-27 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Family Leave,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Push Job-Protected Leaves For Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fresh from losing a bruising fight to raise
the minimum wage, Senate Democrats marched back onto the
battlefield with an equally controversial proposal requiring
job-protected medical and parental leaves for workers.
   ``What a profound and strong signal it would be'' to approve
such a requirement, Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said Monday in
opening debate on the measure. ``It would be catching up with the
needs of people in this country.''
   Dodd's bill would guarantee at least 13 weeks of unpaid,
job-protected leave to seriously ill workers and at least 10 weeks
to those with newborn, newly adopted or seriously ill children.
Businesses of under 20 employees would be exempt.
   Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., planned to offer a substitute
reducing the medical leave length to 10 weeks but it was unclear
whether such a change would attract the 60 votes necessary to cut
off debate.
   Conservatives and many in the business community contend the
government should not mandate benefits.
   ``I am concerned that this legislation may impede the trend ...
now developing in the workplace where employees are able to choose
from a variety of benefits,'' said Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.
   He and others also say any leave requirement would be an
economic hardship on small businesses. But Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., chairman of the Labor and Human Resources Committee, said
Congress' watchdog agency, the General Accounting Office, has
estimated the bill would cost employers $3.50 per worker per year.
   ``A penny a day so that working parents won't lose their jobs
when they care for a newborn ... when they must care for a
seriously ill child,'' Kennedy said. ``I put the choice to the
opponents of this bill _ can you spare a penny a day for these
children? Or is this economic expansion so fragile that a penny a
day will do us in?''
   Kennedy said he had received three veto letters from the Reagan
administration on the family leave bill.
   Dodd appealed Monday for bipartisan support from his colleagues
and from Vice President George Bush, the Republican presidential
nominee. Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the Democratic
presidential nominee, already has endorsed the Dodd approach.
   Bush has said women shouldn't have to worry about getting their
jobs back after a maternity leave but has not issued a detailed
proposal. He is said to favor a voluntary approach involving tax
breaks for businesses that offer job-protected leaves. Sen. Dan
Quayle, R-Ind., the GOP vice presidential nominee, opposed the Dodd
bill in committee.
   Senate work on the parental leave bill came as the chamber's
Democratic leaders on Monday gave up all hope of passing
legislation to increase the minimum wage this year, conceding
defeat to a Republican filibuster.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
