<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru f0006 09-27 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0006,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crude Futures Prices Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to show oil prices plunge; picks up 7th
graf pvs, ``Energy futures ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices plunged to near two-year lows
for the second time this month as fears of a worsening oil glut
spread through the market.
   Analysts said rumors that Saudi Arabia, OPEC's largest producer,
was continuing its discount strategy to boost market share in the
wake of the cartel's price meeting sent the market into a tailspin.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil, was trading
as much as 35 cents lower, between $13.85 and $14.02 a barrel,
compared with Monday's closing price of $14.20.
   Today's rumors were that the Saudis were offering discounts to
the Japanese, said Peter Beutel, an analyst with Elders Futures Inc.
   But other OPEC nations, including the United Arab Emirates,
Kuwait and Iraq also are reported to be producing far in excess of
their assigned quotas.
   ``It seems as if there's been a complete breakdown, with the
Arabs leading the charge toward market share,'' Beutel said.
   The fall in crude prices pulled down oil product prices.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery was trading
between 44.50 and 44.90 cents a gallon, down from its close of
45.25 cents a gallon on Monday.
   And October wholesale heating oil had lost 1.13 cents before
midday, to 39.10 cents a gallon from Monday's settlement price of
40.23 a gallon.
   The long-anticipated meeting of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries' price committee adjourned Monday after two
days of talks with no concrete steps announced for dealing with the
world oversupply of oil or weakening oil prices.
   On Monday, confusion and uncertainty over OPEC's intentions
caused wild gyrations in prices and trading activity, analysts said.
   ``Rumors went both ways but there were points where buying
completely dried up, then came back,'' Beutel said.
   Energy futures prices opened higher, then tumbled after
statements by OPEC Secretary General Subroto that the pricing
committee had adjourned without calling for a full meeting of the
cartel to deal with the problems of excess oil production and
sagging prices.
   Instead, Subroto said the pricing committee and OPEC's long-term
strategy committee would meet jointly next month to review supply
and demand problems.
   Analysts said the marketplace interpreted the statements as an
indication the cartel was unwilling to cut production.
   ``The marketplace was disappointed in the committee's failure to
come up with a concrete direction,'' said John Azarow, Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc.
</TEXT>
