<HEAD>Crop Futures Mixed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
mostly lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade, then turned mixed
as follow-through selling from Monday abated.
   ``Everyone's just kind of feeling their way a little bit here
this morning after yesterday's bang,'' said Jerry Gidel, an analyst
in Chicago with the G.H. Miller division of the British-owned
trading company LIT America Inc.
   Soybean futures registered their lowest daily settlement price
in nearly four months Monday, $8.06\ a bushel for November delivery.
   Buying prompted by technical market factors provided some
support for corn and soybean futures this morning, but wheat
remained weak due to slack export demand, Gidel said.
   Analysts blamed Monday's slide on the advancing harvest, which
is increasing the amount of available corn and soybeans.
   The Agriculture Department reported Monday that corn harvesting
was 20 percent complete and soybean harvesting was 14 percent
finished as of Sunday.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to } cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.21} a bushel; corn was {
cent to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.82 a bushel; oats were
1 cent lower to 1{ cents higher with December at $2.46 a bushel;
soybeans were 3 cents lower to 3 cents higher with November at
$8.07 a bushel.
