<2ND_LINE>PM-Bonds,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Mixed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices were mixed in subdued trading early
today with little new economic data to move the market.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year issue was up 3-32 point,
or about 90 cents for every $1,000 in face value.
   Its yield, which moves inversely to its price and is often an
indicator of interest rate trends, slipped to 9.07 percent from
9.08 percent late Monday.
   Analysts said the market had not responded to an early drop in
oil prices, which usually is favorable to bonds because it signals
an easing of inflationary pressures.
   The dollar also appeared stable after waffling on Monday and
closing higher against most major currencies.
   ``It seems the (bond) market doesn't want to do anything until
we get more information,'' said Elizabeth Reiners, vice president
of money-market research for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Analysts said bond investors are already looking to next week's
U.S. unemployment report for a clearer indication of the economy's
direction. Unemployment rose slightly last month, which many
interpreted as a sign the economy is slowing.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
government issues were down 1-32 point, intermediate maturities
were 1-32 point higher to 1-32 point lower, and 20-year issues were
1-16 point lower, according to Telerate Inc., a financial
information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, was down 0.16 at 1,140.47.
   Meanwhile, Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which
measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of
five years or longer, advanced 0.18 to 289.96.
   Three-month Treasury bills were up 6 basis points to a discount
rate of 7.28 percent and a yield of 7.51. Six-month bills advanced
4 basis points to 7.90 percent and a yield of 7.51 percent, while
one-year bills were unchanged at a discount rate of 7.61 and a
yield of 8.18 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 8\ percent, down from 8 5-16 percent late
Monday.
</TEXT>
