<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ForkliftDumping     09-27 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Forklift Dumping,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Alleges Japan Trying To Evade Duties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hyster Co. contends that its Japanese
competitors now are ``dumping'' forklift parts in the United States
in an effort to evade new U.S. customs duties imposed on them for
selling complete forklifts below cost.
   After a yearlong battle by Hyster, the U.S. government decided
last spring to impose customs duties ranging as high as 50 percent
on the imports.
   The company now alleges that the Japanese are trying to
circumvent those duties by importing the vehicles in pieces and
assembling them in the United States.
   Hyster officials say they have collected data that show imports
of forklift parts have nearly doubled this year compared to last
year.
   In a letter to Department of Commerce and U.S. Customs Service
administrators, Hyster notes U.S. statistics list truck part
imports at $16.7 million in the first six months of 1987. This year
those imports jumped to $34.9 million.
   The company asks the government to determine whether trucks
assembled in the United States also should be subject to the duties.
   Hyster notes in its letter that the new trade law allows federal
officials to assess duties against companies that simply switch
from dumping finished products to dumping parts, which then are
assembled in the United States or in a third country.
   In a similar case involving dumping televisions in the United
States by South Koreans, the government decided imported parts that
were assembled in the United States also were subject to dumping
duties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
