<HEAD>IBM To Buy Back Up To $2 Billion In Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp.'s board
authorized the company Tuesday to buy back up to $2 billion of its
own stock, which at current prices would amount to about 3 percent
of outstanding shares.
   IBM had 592 million shares as of July 31, which at Monday's
close of $112.25 a share gave the company a market value of $66.45
billion. That made IBM the world's second most valuable company
after Japan's huge Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp.
   The directors did not give any timetable for the repurchases.
Since May 1986, IBM has purchased about 28 million of its shares at
a cost of about $3.5 billion.
