<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0040,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Strongly Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose strongly in active trading
Tuesday on the London Stock Exchange, bolstered by news that
Britain's trade performance for August was better than expected.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended 15.3
points, or 0.85 percent, higher at 1,808.0, below its best level
for the day of 1,813.2 but well above the psychologically important
1,800 barrier.
   Volume was a solid 461.5 million shares, up sharply from the
299.6 million shares that changed hands Monday.
   The report on the August trade figures assumed major importance
after the figures for July showed a deficit more than double what
private economists had forecast.
   The August trade deficit was 1.813 billion pounds, or about
$3.06 billion. Market expectations had been for a shortfall of
around 1.9 billion pounds, or $3.2 billion.
   The deficit narrowed 31 percent from July's record of 2.651
billion pounds, or around $4.5 billion, but was still Britain's
second worst monthly trade performance on record.
</TEXT>
