<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-27 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Rally; Wheat Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most corn futures prices closed moderately to
sharply higher in a late rally Tuesday on the Chicago Board of
Trade after an expected increase in farmers' selling of newly
harvested corn failed to emerge.
   Soybean futures advanced with the corn market, but wheat futures
finished slightly lower amid slack export demand, analysts said.
   The discovery over the weekend of the naturally occurring poison
aflatoxin in some corn in Iowa and Indiana had prompted speculation
that farmers would try to sell such corn immediately, since the
Agriculture Department would refuse to accept it as loan collateral.
   The tainted corn is harmless when blended with enough good corn
to render the total aflatoxin content no more than 20 parts per
billion for human consumption or 100 parts per billion for animal
consumption.
   But with no evidence of a surge in farmers' selling of corn
since Monday, futures traders decided the aflatoxin scare had been
exaggerated, analysts said.
   ``The talk was there but there wasn't the physical evidence of
the corn coming to market,'' said Jerry Gidel, an analyst in
Chicago with the G.H. Miller division of the British-owned trading
company LIT America Inc.
   At the close, wheat was } cent to 1} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.21{ a bushel; corn was }
cent lower to 6\ cents higher with December at $2.87 a bushel; oats
were 1{ cents lower to 2{ cents higher with December at $2.46 a
bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 7{ cents higher with November at
$8.09{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
