<DOCNO> AP880927-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1859EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-27 0827</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0857</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Surge On Signs Of International Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices surged Tuesday on New York's Coffee, Sugar
& Cocoa Exchange on indications that a new coffee price-support
agreement was near.
   On other markets, sugar futures soared; energy futures
retreated; copper and precious metals advanced; frozen pork bellies
plunged; livestock were mixed; grains and soybeans were mixed; and
stock-index futures retreated.
   News arrived in New York at midday from the International Coffee
Organization's meeting in London that Brazil and Colombia,
respectively the world's No. 1 and No. 2 coffee producers, had
proposed an initial global export quota of 54 million bags for the
1988-89 marketing year.
   The reports sparked high-volume buying of coffee futures by
roasters and speculators on ideas that the proposal could become
the cornerstone of a new ICO agreement for stabilizing coffee
prices in the upcoming marketing year, which begins Oct. 1.
   ``This was significant not only in that these two countries have
agreed on something but in that it sets the tone for the conference
as a whole,'' said Arthur Stevenson, coffee market analyst in New
York with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``It indicates the
meeting is progressing harmoniously.''
   Under the proposal, coffee producers would limit sales to ICO
consumers to 54 million bags during the marketing year, compared
with this year's initial quota of 58 million bags. The ICO can
adjust the quota upward or downward during the year, depending on
market conditions, to keep prices stable.
   Global coffee consumption is declining, but demand for
higher-priced ``mild'' coffees _ as opposed to the more plentiful
``robusta'' coffees _ is on the rise.
   Stevenson said consumer nations might agree to the lower quota,
which would tend to support prices, if producers agree to increase
the percentage of milds in the export mix.
   Coffee settled 2.15 to 2.83 cents higher with the contract for
delivery in December at $1.2924 a pound.
   Sugar futures recovered nearly all of Monday's sharp losses on
buying inspired by technical factors and rumors of physical sugar
purchases by China and the Soviet Union, Stevenson said.
   Sugar settled .37 cent to .69 cent higher with October at 9.86
cents a pound.
   Crude oil futures dipped to 2-year lows below $14 a barrel early
in the session on the New York Mercantile Exchange but recovered to
finish only slightly lower than Monday's final prices.
   Analysts linked the early weakness to reports of continued
discount sales of crude by Saudi Arabia and pessimism about OPEC's
search for a solution to the overproduction that has been blamed
for the persistent weakness of crude oil prices.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents to 15 cents
lower with November at $14.14 a barrel; heating oil was .55 cent to
.72 cent lower with October at 39.51 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .45 cent lower to .34 cent higher with October at
45.59 cents a gallon.
   Copper futures posted new contract highs in most delivery months
for the fourth straight day on New York's Commodity Exchange on
continuing concern about tight supplies and rising demand.
   Copper settled 1.20 cents to 1.80 cents higher with September at
$1.214 a pound.
   Precious metals futures also advanced on the Comex, buoyed by
the stability in the oil market, analysts said.
   Gold settled $2.10 to $3 higher with October at $397.90 a troy
ounce; silver was 5.5 cents to 6 cents higher with September at
$6.166 a troy ounce.
   Frozen pork bellies for February and May delivery settled down
the allowable daily limit of 2 cents a pound on a
technically-inspired selloff on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
analysts said.
   Hog futures retreated on position-evening ahead of Friday's
quarterly hogs-and-pigs report from the Agriculture Department,
while cattle finishednarrowly mixed.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .38 cent higher with October
at 70.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .37 cent lower to .15
cent higher with September at 79.80 cents a pound; hogs were .38
cent to .63 cent lower with October at 39.92 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.10 cents to 2 cents lower with February at
50.10 cents a pound.
   Most corn futures finished moderately to sharply higher in a
late rally on the Chicago Board of Trade after an expected increase
in farmer selling of newly harvested corn failed to emerge.
   Soybean futures advanced with the corn market, but wheat moved
slightly lower amid slack export demand, analysts said.
   Wheat settled { cent to 1 cent lower with December at $4.21} a
bushel; corn was } cent lower to 5} cents higher with December at
$2.86{ a bushel; oats were 1{ cents lower to 2{ cents higher with
December at $2.46 a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 7{ cents
higher with November at $8.10 a bushel.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of Standard &
Poor's 500 stocks settled 1.45 points lower at 270.50.
</TEXT>
