<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Texaco-Krowe     09-27 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texaco-Krowe,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM's Allen Krowe Going to Texaco as CFO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allen Krowe, a former chief financial
officer for International Business Machines Corp., will assume a
similar position at Texaco Inc. next month, the oil company said
Tuesday.
   The move, effective Oct. 1, came as no surprise to analysts, who
said Krowe had fallen into disfavor at the computer giant.
   Krowe, 56, will succeed Richard Brinkman, who has opted to take
early retirement. Brinkman will stay with the company until some
projects are completed during 1989, Texaco spokesman Peter Maneri
said.
   After he retires, Brinkman will serve as a consultant to Texaco.
   ``He (Krowe) sort of fell into the penalty box at IBM, if I can
put it that way,'' said analyst Jay P. Stevens of Dean Witter
Reynolds. ``Allen Krowe is a former CFO at IBM, and in the most
recent years he has retained his titles at the senior vice
president but has had fewer and fewer operational assignments.''
   ``Allen Krowe was effectively depositioned a while ago at IBM,''
said Stephen Dube of Shearson Lehman. ``I think it's not,
therefore, to be viewed as a surprise.''
   Texaco, Dube said, is getting ``a very experienced and qualified
individual.''
   Krowe, who elected to take early retirement from IBM effective
Oct. 1, joined the company in 1960 and had played a role in
acquisitions and business restructuring. Most recently he served on
the corporate management board and the management committee.
   Brinkman joined Texaco in 1956. He became chief financial
officer in December 1986, and helped form the company's strategy
during its reorganization under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy
Code. He will report to Texaco President and Chief Executive
Officer James W. Kinnear.
</TEXT>
