<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SmithKline 1stLd-Writethru   09-27 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SmithKline, 1st Ld-Writethru,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SmithKline Beckman Announces $400 Million Restructuring</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS lead to CORRECT that 25 percent loss was for second
quarter sted first half; SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that Philadelphia
operation employs about 800 sted 900; picks up 3rd graf pvs bg'ng,
U.S. and ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beckman Corp., which saw a 25
percent drop in profits in the second quarter of the year,
announced Tuesday a major restructuring of its pharmaceutical
business that will cost up to $400 million and force the layoff of
1,600 workers.
   The company also said it will close its Philadelphia drug
manufacturing operation, which employs about 800 workers.
   U.S. and international drug sales and research, which had been
the three main units of the company's drug business, will be
consolidated and headed by John F. Chappell, who has been head of
the international business since 1985, the company said.
   Sixty percent of the corporate staff in Philadelphia will also
be fired.
   The restructuring will result in annual pretax savings of $100
million by the end of 1990, the company said in a press statement.
   ``Our purpose remains unchanged,'' Henry Wendt, chief executive
officer, said. ``We are a technology-driven company pursuing
worldwide leadership positions in fast-growing segments of the
health care and life sciences markets.
   ``We are positioning Smith Kline & French Laboratories, our
pharmaceutical business, to receive more focused leadership and
attention under a single organization designed to more rapidly
commercialize current products and develop and market future
products on a worldwide scale,'' he said.
   Earnings for this year are expected to be $3.75 to $4 a share,
up from a 5 to 10 percent anticipated drop in 1987's $4.50-a-share
profit, the company said.
   Also, the company will issue 5 million new shares of Beckman
Instruments, a subsidiary of SmithKline Beckman.
   The company said in July that it would reorganize its business
following a lackluster first-half performance in which earnings
dropped by 25 percent. The company also predicted that earnings for
the full 1988 fiscal year would be down by 25 percent as well.
   SmithKline blamed the drop in its profits on the disappointing
sales of its two top drugs _ Tagament, an anti-ulcer drug, and
Dyazide, a drug used in the treatment of hypertension.
</TEXT>
