<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MGM-UAShuffle     09-27 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MGM-UA Shuffle,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United Artists Studio Apparent Casualty of Latest Shuffle at
MGM-UA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Artists studio is the
latest casualty in continued corporate shuffling at MGM-UA
Communications Co., under a $200 million restructuring announced
Tuesday.
   The complex plan apparently depends on a substantial injection
of cash from Kirk Kerkorian, the Los Angeles investor who owns 79
percent of the show-business congolmerate and has been trading its
parts periodically for nearly 20 years.
   The restructuring a $200 million stock rights offering to
present stockholders, who would get the right to buy additional new
shares in MGM-UA, maker of Academy Award-winning ``Moonstruck.''
   Kerkorian's Tracinda Corp., which already owns 79 percent of
MGM-UA, intends to buy any of the new shares not bought by other
stockholders, the company said.
   The plan appears similar to Kerkorian's previous, failed,
shuffle of MGM-UA in that most of the cash injected into the
debt-burdened company would be his through purchase of more shares.
   The company said it would stop producing all but a few movies
under the United Artists name, consolidating production under MGM,
the former Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, noted for its roaring lion
trademark. He said the James Bond movies and other strings of
sequels will continue carrying the UA name, which also presently
appears on ``Betrayed.''
   MGM-UA is exploring the possiblity of selling a part-interest in
its television production arm, but does not plan to sell the UA
name or film library, said Stephen Silbert MGM-UA's chairman and
chief executive officer.
   ``That's not under consideration,'' he said, when asked about
Hollywood speculation that UA might be up for sale.
   He refused to discuss a potential investor for MGM-UA's TV
production unit, which is responsible for the critically-acclaimed
series ``thirtysomething,'' among other shows.
   ``We're at the stage of exploring it, we haven't made a
decision,'' Silbert said.
   Details of the plan to issue new shares to present stockholders
have not been worked out, Silbert said, adding that the rights
offering was expected to take place near the end of the year.
   The announcement follows by a day the resignation of UA's
chairman and chief executive, Anthony Thomopoulos. Lee Rich,
MGM-UA's chairman and chief executive, resigned in mid-July, and
Alan Ladd resigned as head of the MGM production unit two weeks
later.
   In late July, Kerkorian's two-week-old plan to split MGM and UA
and sell a part-interest in MGM to Beverly Hills investor Burt
Sugarman and two moviemakers fell through for undisclosed reasons.
That plan also called for sale of new stock to present
shareholders, with Kerkorian buying any unsold shares.
   Under the new plan, MGM-UA's bank debt of between $250 million
and $275 million would be paid by money raised through the stock
issue and sale of assets, Silbert said.
   Kerkorian, who bought MGM in 1969, engaged in his biggest
shuffle of MGM and UA assets in 1986 by selling the combined
company to Atlanta media entrepreneur Ted Turner and then buying
back parts over a period of several months.
   Turner ended up with MGM's library of classic films, including
``The Wizard of Oz'' and ``Gone with the Wind.'' Kerkorian got the
MGM and UA production companies minus the MGM studio lot, which was
sold to Lorimar-Telepictures Corp.
</TEXT>
