<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 2337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GeneralTire     09-27 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-General Tire,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Tire's Parent Firm Announces $470 Million Capital
Investment Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continental AG, the German-based parent of
General Tire Inc., plans capital investments totaling $470 million
to improve General's plants during the next four years, Continental
Chairman Horst W. Urban said Tuesday night.
   The investments will be in addition to $220 million in
previously announced capital expenditures. Most of the money will
be spent in North America, Urban said.
   Urban said financing for the improvements would come largely
from the company's cash flow, with debts of $220 million to $280
million being incurred.
   ``The North American market is the most important in the
world,'' Urban said. ``All our major customers from Europe and
Japan are represented on this continent and also expect us, as
suppliers, to manufacture here. Finally, our presence in North
America reduces our currency risk.''
   General Tire President Gilbert H. Neal said the planned
investment ``demonstrates to General Tire's 10,000 employees
Continental's commitment to the North American market. It will
modernize our manufacturing facilities, making them more efficient
and productive.''
   In a related move, Continental, General Tire, Yokohama Rubber
Co. Ltd. of Tokyo and Toyo Tire & Rubber Co. of Osaka, Japan,
announced plans for a joint venture to produce radial truck and bus
tires in Mount Vernon, Ill.
   General Tire will manage the Mount Vernon plant, and the
operation will supply the North American sales operations of the
four companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
